<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DiabetesBoy     11-15 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Diabetes Boy,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Sect Pastor Gets 2-Year Prison Term In Boy's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN K. WILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Monday sentenced the former
pastor of a faith-healing sect to two years in prison for his part
in the death of the son of church members, saying he wanted to send
a message to cultists.
   Jeffrey A. Siegel, 33, of Chapel Hill, N.C., was convicted of
second-degree criminal mistreatment. Spokane County Superior Court
Judge John Schultheis said circumstances warranted going beyond the
standard 90-day sentence for the crime, the maximum the prosecutor
sought.
   ``I have an obligation to send a message ... to anyone who might
be interested in beginning a religious cult,'' Schultheis told
Siegel.
   Siegel was the former pastor of a nameless Christian sect that
eschewed conventional medicine in favor of prayer. Aaron Norman, the
10-year-old son of sect members Bobby and Judith Norman, died Dec.
20, 1987, of untreated juvenile diabetes.
   Bobby Norman, 43, was convicted last month of first-degree
manslaughter for failing to seek medical attention for his son.
Charges against Mrs. Norman were dismissed prior to the trial.
   ``Why is it that it takes a tragedy for people to realize what
they've been doing is wrong?'' asked Schultheis. ``Medicine has been
given to us by God as much as the power of prayer.''
   Siegel also was sentenced to serve six months for a charge of
simple assault stemming from a spanking administered to an adult
church member in a separate incident. That sentence will be served
concurrently, meaning Siegel will be eligible for parole in 16
months, Schultheis said.
   Before he was sentenced, a tearful Siegel told Schultheis he was
``absolutely ashamed'' of his participation in the sect and its
``rigid view of the outside world.''
   ``I am absolutely heartbroken for what happened to Aaron
Norman,'' Siegel said.
   Testimony during the three-week trial indicated the gravely ill
boy was beaten the day before his death by his father and sect
founder Doug Kleber while Siegel and other church elders watched.
The beatings were believed necessary to get the boy to confess the
sin of masturbation and be healed.
   As pastor, Siegel knew, or should have known, that Aaron Norman
was vulnerable, Schultheis said. Spankings and other discipline of
the 10-year-old ``manifested deliberate cruelty,'' the judge said.
   Kleber, 34, of Champaign-Urbana, Ill., has pleaded guilty to
second-degree criminal mistreatment and is scheduled to be sentenced
later.
   Testimony also revealed that members were expected to consult
with church leaders on matters ranging from buying a car to their
sex lives. The fellowship once claimed 300 adult members in four
states, but disbanded in February.
</TEXT>
