<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SivaBust     11-15 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Siva Bust,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Khmer Bust Auction Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A five-headed Khmer bust of Siva, the Hindu god of
destruction and reproduction, has sold for $574,200, an auction
record for any Southeast Asian work of art at auction, Sotheby's
said.
   The 31{-inch high, gray sandstone bust was sold Monday by an
anonynmous collector and bought by an unidentified overseas bidder.
   The figure dated from the third quarter of the 10th century. No
history of it was otherwise recorded, except that the uppermost head
had been in the Pan Asian Collection, most of which is in the Los
Angeles County Museum.
   Each of the heads wears an enigmatic smile. The uppermost head
was acquired by the seller, who reunited it with the rest of the
figure.
   The sale at Monday's auction of some 100 lots of Khmer, Thai,
Indian and Himalayan art totaled $2.8 million. The three top-priced
lots were sold by the same collector.
   A 7th century head of Buddha from Thailand, larger than lifesize,
was bought for $376,200 by a Swiss collector. Another anonymous
buyer paid a similar price for a 4-foot standing figure of a Khmer
four-armed male deity from the first half of the 9th century.
   The bidders included American and Swiss collectors and London
dealers.
</TEXT>
