<2ND_LINE>PM-Box Office,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Child's Play' Thriller At Top Of Box Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A thriller called ``Child's Play,'' featuring a
homicidal doll named Chucky, carved out first place in the nation's
weekend box office sweepstakes with a take of $6.5 million.
   Pesky pitchman Ernest P. Worrell (played by actor Jim Varney)
teamed up with Santa Claus in ``Ernest Saves Christmas,'' an early
holiday offering that was in second place with $5.7 million in its
first week of release.
   ``Iron Eagle II,'' with Lou Gossett reviving his tough fighter
pilot character, was third in formation with $3.5 million for its
debut.
   ``They Live,'' director John Carpenter's exploration of yuppies
as space aliens, was in fourth place with $2.7 million, followed by
``Everybody's All American.'' The movie about a football hero and
his sweetheart earned $2.6 million.
   Several new movies are set for release this week in anticipation
of large holiday audiences. They include ``High Spirits,'' ``1969,''
``Fresh Horses,'' and two animated offerings: Walt Disney's ``Oliver
and Company'' and the Steven Spielberg-George Lucas ``Land Before
Time.''
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations Co. Inc., with distributor, weekend gross, number of
theater screens, average per screen, total gross, and number of
weeks in release.
   1. ``Child's Play,'' UA, $6.5 million, 1,377 screens, $4,781 per
screen, $8 million (five days), one week.
   2. ``Ernest Saves Christmas,'' Walt Disney, $5.7 million, 1,634
screens, $3,495 per screen, $5.7 million, one week.
   3. ``Iron Eagle II,'' Tri-Star, $3.5 million, 874 screens, $4,038
per screen, $3.5 million, one week.
   4. ``They Live,'' Universal, $2.7 million, 1,459 screens, $1,900
per screen, $8.9 million, two weeks.
   5. ``Everybody's All American,'' Warner Bros., $2.6 million,
1,123 screens, $2,327 per screen, $7 million, two weeks.
   6. ``The Accused,'' Paramount, $2.4 million, 930 screens, $2,594
per screen, $24.3 million, five weeks.
   7. ``U2 Rattle and Hum,'' Paramount, $1.7 million, 1,459 screens,
$1,178 per screen, $6.6 million, two weeks.
   8. ``A Cry In The Dark,'' Warner Bros., $1.5 million, 334
screens, $4,676 per screen, $1.5 million, one week.
   9. ``Mystic Pizza,'' Samuel Goldwyn, $1.38 million, 440 screens,
$3,139 per screen, $6.5 million, four weeks.
   10. ``Without A Clue,'' Orion, $1.34 million, 460 screens, $2,920
per screen, $5.1 million, four weeks.
</TEXT>
