<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     11-15 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Problems To Face Incoming Agriculture Secretary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nagging trade problems and preliminary
maneuvering on a new U.S. farm bill will face the Bush
administration's incoming secretary of agriculture next year.
   Lobbying for the Cabinet post already is in full swing, although
President-elect George Bush and his advisors have been focusing on
other matters and have dropped no hints about who might get the job.
   Trade issues will be near the top of the agenda for the new
agriculture secretary.
   Little progress has been made in reaching agreement on farm
provisions of a new 97-nation General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade
(GATT) agreement, despite two years of talks in Geneva. A U.S. call
for phasing out farm subsidies by the year 2000 has received a
chilly reception.
   Also stalled are talks aimed at reaching a new long-term grain
agreement with the Soviet Union.
   The most recent, five-year agreement expired Sept. 30 and there
have been no formal talks since Oct. 24, when the United States
rejected a Soviet proposal calling for a one-year agreement.
   A free-trade agreement that would phase out most tariffs between
the United States and Canada had been approved by Congress but is
running into trouble in Ottawa. That is not viewed as altogether bad
among some U.S. wheat producers and potato growers who never had
much use for the pact anyway.
   Failure of the agreement, however, would be guaranteed to make
life more complex for the next agriculture secretary.
   On Capitol Hill, the House and Senate Agriculture Committees plan
to start talking next year about a farm bill to replace the omnibus
1985 farm legislation that expires in two years.
   The 1985 law is largely a blueprint for a massive cleanout of
huge grain surpluses that had piled up, driving down prices and
bringing on what came to be known as the crisis in rural America.
   Huge subsidies were provided to boost exports at clearance sale
prices as part of the effort to make farm surpluses disappear.
Surplus milk and cheese remaining on the shelf were simply given
away to the poor.
   The measure is generally viewed as a success. USDA analysts say
net cash income for the farm sector in 1988 should be near, and may
top by a small margin last year's record $57.1 billion, despite the
summer drought.
   For that reason many in the agricultural community think there
will be little change in the thrust of the next bill.
   But the secretary is certain to face an array of tough challenges
as lawmakers set about their work. New programs to help specific
crops are bound to be debated along with plans to reform the
troubled federal crop insurance program and further tighten
pesticide regulation.
   With the 70-year-old Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng saying
the time for retirement has arrived, or at least will when Bush is
sworn in, candidates are lining up for the secretary's job.
   One who says he does not want to serve in the Cabinet and would
like to return to private industry is U.S. Trade Representative
Clayton K. Yeutter. The one-time Nebraska feedlot operator had long
been mentioned as a possible future agriculture secretary.
   Getting a strong boost from congressional Republicans is Rep. Tom
Coleman, R-Mo. He is a force on the House Agriculture Committee but
is not a farmer and, thus, like Lyng, might need to have someone
with experience in production agriculture in the deputy secretary's
slot.
   Lyng's deputy, Peter C. Myers, raised crops and livestock in
southeastern Missouri between 1955 and 1982, when he came to
Washington to become head of the Soil and Conservation Service. He
has become a favorite at USDA.
   Bush's campaign assurances to voters that he is an
environmentalist might sway him to opt for Myers, the architect of
several major soil conservation measures contained in the 1985 farm
law.
   That far from exhausts the list. If Lyng's low-key, businesslike
approach captures Bush's fancy, the new president could turn to Bill
Lesher, a Washington consultant and former Lyng business partner.
Also being mentioned are former Rep. Cooper Evans, R-Iowa;
Mississippi soybean farmer Seymour Johnson and American Farm Bureau
past President Bob Delano.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An additional 300,000 metric tons of U.S. corn
has been sold to the Soviet Union for delivery in the current
marketing year, the Agriculture Department announced.
   The announcement Monday brings the total of American corn sold to
the Soviets for delivery in the year that started Sept. 1 to
4,715,600 tons, the department said in a statement.
   It did not give further details but at the price of $134.50 a
metric ton delivered at Rotterdam, announced by USDA last week, the
value of the shipment could be a little more than $40.3 million.
</TEXT>
