<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ScotusRdp     11-15 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus Rdp,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court: No Abortion Veto Rights for Fathers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, at least for now, is keeping
out of the continuing national debate over abortion rights.
   The justices on Monday refused to give husbands legal power to
prevent their wives from terminating pregnancies.
   Without comment, they rejected arguments by an Indiana man who
said he had ``fundamental rights and interests in his unborn
child.'' The action left intact a state court ruling that upheld a
mother's right to have an abortion.
   There has been speculation that an increasingly conservative high
court is prepared to take a new look at its landmark 1973 ruling,
Roe vs. Wade, that legalized abortion nationwide.
   The author of the 12-year-old court opinion, Justice Harry A.
Blackmun, has said he believes there is ``a very distinct
possibility'' Roe vs. Wade will be reversed during the court's
current term.
   But on Monday, the justices gave no signs they are eager to
tackle an abortion controversy now.
   The court let stand a ruling last July by the Indiana Supreme
Court that said allowing a husband to block a wife's abortion is
barred by past high court rulings.
   The high court in 1976 struck down a Missouri law requiring
spousal consent before a woman could obtain an abortion during the
first 12 weeks of her pregnancy.
   The Indiana case stems from an attempt last summer by Erin Andrew
Conn of Elkhart, Ind., to prevent his estranged wife, Jennifer, from
having an abortion. She was about six weeks pregnant at the time.
   A state trial judge issued a temporary order barring Mrs. Conn
from having the operation, but a state appeals court threw out that
order.
   ``Erin has no right to veto Jennifer's decision ... as such
decision concerns only her,'' the appeals court ruled.
   The Indiana Supreme Court upheld the appeals court ruling.
   The injunction prohibiting Mrs. Conn's abortion was lifted last
July 22 and she had an abortion.
   The Conns are in the midst of divorce proceedings. Conn's
attorney, James Bopp of Terre Haute, said a decree is expected
within days.
   The father argued that the 1973 and 1976 high court rulings did
not preclude state courts from taking a husband's rights into
consideration ``on a case-by-case basis.''
   ``The father has fundamental rights and interests in his unborn
child which should be judicially considered, on the facts of this
case, along with the rights and interests of his wife in aborting
their child,'' lawyers for Erin Conn said.
   But the Indiana courts rejected such a balancing test.
   In other action, the Supreme Court:
   _Cleared the way for enforcement of federal court subpoenas
requiring Ferdinand and Imelda Marcos to turn over financial records
and other material to a grand jury.
   The justices refused to shield the deposed president and first
lady of the Philippines from the subpoenas, related to a New York
case in which they are charged with looting their nation's treasury
of more than $100 million.
   _Ruled, 6-3, in a case from Arkansas that states may hold a
second sentencing trial for a defendant mistakenly sent to prison as
a habitual offender.
   _Let stand a ruling in a Louisiana case that the federal Voting
Rights Act, designed to prevent racial discrimination, applies to
state judicial elections.
   _Agreed to consider the constitutionality of a Connecticut law
aimed at assuring that beer sold in the state costs no more than it
does in three neighboring states.
   _Agreed to decide in a case from Texas whether investors' claims
against brokers must be settled by binding arbitration.
   _Agreed to use a case from Arkansas involving truckers and one
from Florida involving a liquor distributor to determine whether
states must refund taxes collected under laws later declared
unconstitutional.
</TEXT>
