<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BankingChairman     11-15 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Banking Chairman,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gonzalez Says S&L Industry Crisis Is Top Priority</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: St Germain with no period is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez says the savings and
loan industry crisis would be his top priority as chairman of the
House Banking Committee, but analysts say his expected selection to
the post may might delay a solution.
   With the backing of House leaders, the 72-year-old Texas Democrat
is considered the most likely successor to Rep. Fernand J. St
Germain, D-R.I., defeated last week in his bid for a 15th term.
   Gonzalez, a hot-tempered, outspoken maverick, is urging swift
action before the poor condition of the Federal Savings and Loan
Insurance Corp. becomes a ``chaotic crisis.''
   He advocates establishing a $50 billion line of credit from the
Treasury, to be partly repaid from the sale of loans and property
from failed S&Ls.
   ``Nobody wants a taxpayer bailout ... but there are limits to
what the industry can do and they've reached those limits,''
Gonzalez told the National Association of Mortgage Brokers on Monday.
   Gonzalez later told reporters, ``If it ever gets around that
there's nothing insuring those accounts and deposits, you could have
chaos.''
   Some analysts said they believed Gonzalez' sometimes
confrontational style could further fragment an already divided
House Banking Committee, thus complicating congressional efforts to
find a solution to the S&L industry crisis.
   ``He's bright. He understands problems and he can be very direct
with what he says,'' said Bert Ely, a financial institutions
consultant in Alexandria, Va. ``But it's one thing to be able to
make cogent comments and it's another thing to be able to forge a
legislative compromise. That may be where he has problems.''
   A new banking chairman is also taking over in the Senate, where
Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich., is expected to succeed William
Proxmire, D-Wis., who is retiring.
   The new Bush administration likely will fill the leadership
vacuum left by the transition in Congress, according to R. Dan
Brumbaugh, a savings industry consultant and former chief economist
of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board.
   But, he added, ``it's hard not to believe this is going to slow
momentum.''
   Gonzalez, a 27-year veteran of Congress, gets high marks from
colleagues for personal integrity and a willingness to speak his
mind. They also say he is a likeable man, despite a temper that
caused him two years ago to slug a man who called him a communist.
   However, many question Gonzalez's ability to rein in his own
views enough to ride herd on a committee with more than 50 members
and nearly as many factions.
   In 1977, Gonzalez was appointed to chair a special committee to
investigate the assassinations of President Kennedy and Martin
Luther King Jr. But within weeks he quit in a dispute with the chief
counsel, leaving the committee in turmoil.
   As chairman of the Banking subcommittee on housing since 1981,
Gonzalez has shown a confrontational style. He once called Housing
and Urban Development Secretary Samuel Pierce, the only black member
of the Reagan Cabinet, ``a Stepin Fetchit.''
   He also had advocated the impeachment of former Federal Reserve
Board Chairman Paul Volcker, who was pushing up interest rates in
the early 1980s to fight inflation.
   Former Rep. Henry A. Reuss, a Wisconsin Democrat who preceded St
Germain as banking committee chairman, says Gonzalez might do better
in the post than many expect.
   Under the Reagan administration it just has not been possible to
pass housing legislation, Reuss said, adding that Gonzalez has
``shown a capacity to learn and grow ... and I think that will stand
Congress in good stead.''
   Gonzalez discounted talk that he may be too rigid in his views.
   ``I've never considered myself an ideologue no matter how I've
been labeled,'' he said. ``You (can't) last in politics unless
you're in the traditional American vein of pragmatism.''
   He said much of the criticisms circulating are ``hobgoblins
calculatedly set forth by those who ... have ambitions themselves.''
</TEXT>
