<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Bush-Fitness     11-15 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Fitness,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President-elect Covets Time For Exercise, Fishing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GULF STREAM, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, just finished with a
two-mile run, bounded across the beach and threw himself into the
choppy waters. He caught a wave, body-surfed in and swam around a
while. Later he waded back in shoulder-deep to cast a fishing line
against the brisk waves.
   After an hour or so, he took a break to visit his mother and go
to church, then piloted a U.S. Customs power boat some 40 miles back
down the coast and leaped into the water for more fishing. Afterward
he played nine holes of golf.
   This was a typical vacation day for the 64-year-old man who takes
over the White House next Jan. 20.
   Bush showed during his four-day stay in this balmy beach
community that his idea of relaxation is physical activity. He
enjoys a variety of outdoor sports.
   One day he followed his morning jog with a trip out to a Coast
Guard cutter 400 yards offshore in a motorized raft. He jumped off
the cutter and swam part of the way in, then grabbed a rope off the
raft for an arm-numbing tow to shore against the choppy waters.
   White House physician Dr. Rodney Savage has pronounced Bush's
fitness ``exceptional for a man his age'' and expressed amazement at
his health and stamina.
   His loping walk is that of a younger man, and he moves around a
tennis court with an alacrity that makes up for his unimpressive
serve.
   In an Election Day match, he and son Marvin Bush played doubles
with son Jeb Bush and son-in-law Bill LeBlond in Houston, just hours
before Bush learned he had been elected president. The
president-to-be lunged for balls and zigzagged across the court,
energetic and clearly competitive with the younger men.
   Toward the end of his long presidential campaign, Bush complained
of physical fatigue, saying he missed having the time to jog, which
he said invigorates him. Often on the campaign trail he had a
stationary bicycle brought to his hotel room.
   Since the election, he seems to be making up for the inactivity
of long airplane rides and motorcades.
   Bush told reporters in a beachfront news conference that his
Friday-through-Tuesday morning vacation in Florida helped him clear
his mind.
   ``I've been able to run every day,'' he said. ``I love the
fishing. It doesn't matter what you catch, it's the fact you're out
there and fishermen know that. And so I'm still of the Isaac Walton
school, that the days I spend fishing should not be deducted from
the time I spend on earth.''
</TEXT>
