<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Sakharov     11-15 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sakharov,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nobel Laureate Steps Up Criticism Of Gorbachev</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andrei D. Sakharov, the Nobel laureate and
Soviet human rights activist, says Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev is using ``undemocratic means'' in attempts to improve
conditions in their country.
   ``From my point of view this is dangerous,'' Sakharov said.
   He spoke Monday to a group of American intellectuals after
comparing notes on human rights and the U.S. Strategic Defense
Initiative with President Reagan at the White House.
   Today, Sakharov is scheduled to receive the Albert Einstein peace
prize and a $50,000 award for making ``an enormous impact on the
conscience of the world.''
   A nuclear physicist who helped develop the Soviet hydrogen bomb,
Sakharov has long been the principal human rights advocate in his
country. He was confined to virtual house arrest in Gorky for six
years until Gorbachev arranged his release in 1986.
   The Soviet leader also arranged for Sakharov's first visit to
America.
   But Sakharov, at a session Monday of the Woodrow Wilson Institute
for Scholars, said Gorbachev may not have a long-range program for
reform.
   He said Gorbachev improvises, and often ``compromises with
existing forces that negate his efforts.''
   Specifically, the Soviet nuclear physicist criticized Gorbachev's
consolidation of power, the absence of multi-party and free-market
systems as well as restrictions on meetings and demonstrations.
   ``There is no clear realization how this system should be
reformed,'' Sakharov said.
   In fact, he said, the partial reforms arranged by Gorbachev could
lead to ``disequilibrium.''
   Before leaving the Soviet Union on his first trip to the West,
Sakharov leveled similar criticisms at the Soviet president.
   Sakharov supports glasnost _ a term for openness that has marked
Gorbachev's 3{ years in power _ but complains that the Soviet leader
has accumulated too much power as both president and Communist party
chief.
   ``His tactic seems to be getting democratic reforms through
undemocratic means,'' Sakharov said. ``From my point of view this is
a dangerous action.''
   On the human rights front, Sakharov said some dissidents remain
in psychiatric institutions along with many more people who were
chronic critics of their employers.
   He called the detention system ``one of the most acute abuses''
in the Soviet Union.
   Earlier, Sakharov discussed the plight of dissidents with Reagan
at the White House.
   The president said until the problem is ``completely eliminated''
human rights will remain an irritant in U.S.-Soviet relations.
   The 67-year-old Sakharov met with Reagan for about 20 minutes in
the Oval Office. They shared a cautious approach to the measures
taken by Gorbachev.
   Sakharov, mindful of reporters at a picture-taking session, drew
Reagan's attention to two dissidents, Vazif Meylanov and Mikhail
Kukobaka, who Sakharov said still are being held.
   He called the detention of Meylanov ``ironic'' since he was sent
to prison protesting the removal of Sakharov from Moscow to Gorky in
1980. ``I'm free to travel and he is in prison,'' the human rights
activist said.
   Sakharov, speaking through an interpreter, said Kukobaka is in
prison for refusing to bear false witness against a foreign diplomat.
   Reagan praised Gorbachev as more cooperative than any Kremlin
leader before him, but said ``we can only wait and see'' if the
Soviet leader makes good on a promise to release all political
prisoners.
   Sakharov told the president ``there are only individuals'' left
in jails, implying that Gorbachev, in principle at least, does not
adhere to a policy of detaining dissidents for their views.
   Sakharov, winner of the Nobel Peace Prize, also voiced concern
about the impact that Reagan's missile defense program, known
popularly as Star Wars, might have on efforts by the superpowers to
negotiate a cut in long-range nuclear missile stockpiles.
</TEXT>
