<HEAD>Soviet Shuttle Lands</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: COMBINES bulletin series. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet space shuttle Buran touched down on a
concrete runway in Soviet Central Asia on Tuesday morning,
flawlessly ending its unmanned 3 hour, 25 minute maiden voyage,
Radio Moscow said.
   ``The U.S.S.R. has successfuly tested its first reusable space
craft Buran,'' the official radio said.
   ``The unmanned shuttle has just landed on a special runway near
the Baikonur Space Center,'' it said, interrupting its regular
programming.
   The delta-winged Buran, Russian for snowstorm, had orbited Earth
twice, lifting off on schedule despite a cold rain. The official
Tass news agency said the shuttle landed exactly on schedule.
   A previous attempt to launch the Buran had been frustrated by
last-minute technical troubles.
   The shuttle was launched at 6 a.m. Moscow time (10 p.m. Monday
EST) in yellow flame and clouds of white steam from the special
launch site in the Soviet republic of Kazakhstan. Forty-seven
minutes later it reached orbit, firing its own rockets for the first
time.
   The U.S. shuttle lookalike completed two orbits and then returned
to the 2.7-mile concrete landing strip eight miles from its launch
pad.
   Before liftoff, technicians had been concerned that the Buran and
Energia might get covered with a coat of ice.
</TEXT>
