<DOCNO> AP881115-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 0157EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Shuttle 6thLd-Writethru a0629 11-15 0851</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Shuttle, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0629, a0448,0873</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet Shuttle Lands After Brief, Flawless Unmanned Maiden Flight</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs with details of landing, quotes. Picks up
graf 9 pvs, `The craft's ...' INCORPORATES a0448, AM-Shuttle Lands.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet space shuttle Buran touched down Tuesday
morning on a concrete runway in Soviet Central Asia, flawlessly
ending its unmanned 3-hour, 25-minute maiden flight, Radio Moscow
said.
   Buran had flown twice around Earth on fully automatic control,
then landed at the special 2.7-mile concrete runway eight miles from
its launch pad at the Baikonur Cosmodrome.
   ``The U.S.S.R. has successfuly tested its first reusable space
craft Buran,'' Radio Moscow said, interrupting its regular
programming.
   A previous attempt to launch the Buran had been frustrated by
last-minute technical troubles.
   An escort plane followed the shuttle as it approached the runway,
tracking the last moments of the flight with special optical and
television equipment. The official news agency Tass said the shuttle
systems of the Buran, or snowstorm in Russian, were tested during
the completely automated flight.
   In yellow flame and clouds of steam, the delta-winged Buran
lifted off on schedule at 6 a.m. Moscow time (10 p.m. EST) despite a
cold rain, indicating there had been no hitches in the automated
countdown and launch.
   The engines of Buran were fired twice about three-quarters of an
hour later after it had separated from its booster Energia, and the
craft reached orbit exactly on schedule, Soviet media said.
   There was no live broadcast of the liftoff, but 90 minutes later
Soviet television showed its first film. The shuttle, attached to
Energia and four first-stage rockets, lifted slowly off its pad in
the early morning dark.
   Controllers were shown applauding the launch and green computer
screens showed the flight trajectory.
   The craft's own engines were fired for the first time at an
altitude of 99 miles to nudge it into orbit with its left wing
facing Earth.
   Before liftoff, technicians had been concerned that the Buran and
Energia might get covered with a coat of ice.
   ``If the wind rises into a squall and the orbital vehicle (and)
Energia become covered with a crust of ice, then launch time will be
changed again,'' said correspondent Sergei Slipchenko, referring to
a failed attempt to launch Buran last month.
   U.S. officials won't launch the American space shuttle if there
is ice on the booster rocket or orbiter, and cold temperatures
contributed to the failure of booster rocket seals that led to the
Challenger disaster in January 1986.
   The radio report said the flight would be long enough to check
out all the shuttle systems and determine when a manned flight is
feasible.
   Technicians began fueling the 198-foot Energia, the world's most
powerful booster, with nearly 2,000 tons of liquid hydrogen, oxygen
and kerosene, Radio Moscow reported Monday night.
   Launch had been set for Oct. 29, but the countdown was halted
with 51 seconds left when an access arm failed to pull far enough
away from the space craft. Officials said Monday they redesigned the
joint and expected no more trouble from it.
   The United States flew its first shuttle, the Columbia, in 1981,
and for years the Soviets criticized the craft as wasteful and
unreliable. But Western space specialists say the Soviets began
planning their space plane in 1982 at the latest.
   Few technical details have been made public about the Buran, a
lookalike to the U.S. shuttle, and state-run media have only
indirectly indicated its cost.
   ``Comparing the cost of the Buran program and that of the similar
U.S. shuttle program ($10 billion), newspapers say they are
approximately identical,'' Tass reported.
   The Buran can carry up to 10 cosmonauts, Tass said.
   Alexander I. Dunaev, chief of the commercial Soviet space agency
Glavkosmos, told reporters Thursday the maiden flight of the 100-ton
Buran will show the Soviets if they are ready to begin manned
shuttle missions.
   The Soviets have cited the Jan. 28, 1986, explosion of the
Challenger, which killed all seven crewmembers aboard, as an example
of the hazards they are trying to avoid.
   Dunaev said the Buran and ``several'' additional shuttles planned
by the Soviets will have a different role than their U.S.
equivalents, which were designed to ferry payloads into orbit.
   The Buran and its sister craft will be used to park satellites in
space ``only in exceptional cases,'' Dunaev said, since the use of
shuttles for that purpose costs ``tens, even hundreds of times''
more than conventional booster rockets.
   ``Soviet reusable spaceships will be used, first of all, for the
accomplishment of tasks involved in the operation of space
technology: maintenance operations and recovery of worn-out
satellites,'' he said.
   The Soviets repeatedly have criticized the military uses of the
U.S. shuttle, but the Pentagon says the Soviet spacecraft could be
used to deploy killer satellites, ballistic missile defense weapons
and other military uses.
   The Energia, which can lift a 220,000-pound payload, rivals the
power of America's huge Saturn 5 rocket, which was scrapped for
economy reasons after taking Apollo crews to the moon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
