<HEAD>Dollar Firms Against Yen, Share Prices Hit New High</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS three grafs with closing figures, details. Picks up graf
3 pvs, `Traders said ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar firmed against the Japanese yen
Tuesday while share prices soared to a record high.
   The dollar opened at 123.60 yen, and traded in a range of
123.15-123.72 yen before closing at 123.25 yen, up 0.25 yen from the
previous day's close.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which closed at
a record 28,520.90 points Monday, gained another 308.51 points, or
1.07 percent, to close at 28,829.41, its highest close ever.
   Traders said continued intervention by Japan's central bank early
Tuesday morning helped brake the U.S. currency's recent fall against
the yen.
   The scale of intervention was considered small, but enough to
show monetary officials are determined to stem the dollar's slide,
they said.
   The central bank does not publicly comment on its activities,
although market sources said that on Monday it bought an estimated
$500 million in Tokyo in an attempt to stem the currency's rapid
plunge.
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa told a news conference Tuesday
that there would be cooperative intervention with other major
monetary nations in the currency market if rates again prove
unstable.
   An exchange dealer with a major commercial bank, speaking
anonymously, said market players were keenly awaiting the release of
U.S. monthly trade figures for September, scheduled for Wednesday in
Washington.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which closed at
a record 28,520.90 points Monday, was up 262.15 points from that
close to finish the morning session at 28,783.05.
   Share prices were broadly higher during the morning session on
the Tokyo Stock Exchange, dealers said.
   ``Large capital issues, including steels and shipbuildings, are
heading upward after recent sessions of weakness,'' Seiichiro Kita
of Daiwa Securities said.
</TEXT>
