<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PLO-Excerpts     11-15 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO-Excerpts,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Excerpts of Declaration of Palestinian Independent State</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-PLO, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Following are excerpts of the official
English translation of the ``Declaration of Independence,'' which
was read in Arabic by Palestine Liberation Organization Chairman
Yasser Arafat today:
   ``When in the course of modern times a new order of values was
declared with norms and values fair for all, it was the Arab
Palestinian people who were excluded from the destiny of all other
peoples by a hostile array of local and foreign powers. ...
   ``Despite the historical injustice inflicted on the Arab
Palestinian people resulting in their dispersion and depriving them
of their right to self-determination, following U.N. General
Assembly resolution 181 (1947), which partitioned Palestine into two
states, one Arab and one Jewish, yet it is this resolution that
still provides those conditions of international legitimacy that
ensure the right of the Arab Palestine people to sovereignty and
national independence.
   ``By stages, the occupation of Palestine and parts of other Arab
territories by Israeli forces, the willed dispossession and
expulsion from their ancestral homes of the majority of Palestine's
civilian inhabitants was achieved by organized terror. Those who
remained, as a vestige subjugated in its homeland, were persecuted
and forced to endure the destruction of their national life. ...
   ``The intefadeh (Arabic for uprising) has set siege to the mind
of official Israel, which has for too long relied exclusively upon
myth and terror to deny Palestinian existence altogether. Because
the intefadeh and its revolutionary irreversible impulse, the
history of Palestine has therefore arrived at a decisive juncture.
   ``In pursuance of resolutions adopted by Arab summit conferences
and relying on the authority bestowed by international legitimacy as
embodied in the resolutions of 1947;
   ``And in exercise by the Arab Palestinian people of their right
to self-determination, political independence and sovereignty over
their territory. ...
   ``The Palestine National Council, in the name of God, and in the
name of the Arab Palestinian people, hereby proclaims the
establishment of the state of Palestine on our Palestinian territory
with Jerusalem as its capital.
   ``The state of Palestine is the state of Palestinians, wherever
they may be. The state is for them to enjoy in it their collective
natural and cultural identity, theirs to pursue in it a complete
equality of rights. In it will be safeguarded their political and
religious beliefs and their human dignity under a democratic
parliamentary system, based on freedom of expression and multiple
parties. The rights of the minorities will duly be respected by the
majority, as minorities must abide by decisions of the majority.
Governance will be based on principles of social justice, equality
and non-discrimination in public rights of men or women, on the
grounds of race, religion, color or sex under the aegis of a
constitution which ensures the rule of law and an independent
judiciary.
   ``Thus shall these principles allow no departure from Palestine's
age-old spiritual and civilizational heritage of tolerance and
religious coexistence.
   ``The state of Palestine is an Arab state, an integral and
indivisible part of the Arab nation, at one with that nation in
heritage and civilization. ...
   ``The state of Palestine proclaims its commitment to the
principles and purposes of the United Nations, and to the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights. It proclaims its commitment as well to
the principles and policies of the Non-Aligned Movement. ...
   ``The state of Palestine herewith declares that it believes in
the settlement of regional and international disputes by peaceful
means, in accordance with the U.N. Charter and resolutions ...
   ``Therefore, on this blessed day, November 15, 1988, as we stand
on the threshold of a new dawn ... we humbly bow to the sacred
spirits of our fallen martyrs. ...''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 0249EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PLO-Council     11-15 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO-Council,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Profile of the Palestine National Council</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-PLO, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Palestine National Council is a
450-member bicameral parliament-in-exile with members selected from
Palestine Liberation Organization guerrilla factions and
professional unions.
   The council elects the PLO's ruling 15-man executive committee,
sets out the committee's policy, distributes finances to the
movement's seven departments and regulates relations with
governments and other organizations.
   In short, it is the Palestinians' supreme decision-making body.
   The council is led by Sheik Abdel-Hamid Sayeh, a 78-year-old
Moslem priest who was deported from the Israeli-occupied West Bank
after the 1967 Middle East war.
   The parliament is supposed to convene annually, but the executive
committee may call special sessions for internal, regional or
international developments.
   Another body, the Central Council, meets regularly. Its 70
members, who include the executive committee members, oversee
implementation of PNC resolutions.
   The PLO council first was formed in Jerusalem in 1964.
   After the 1967 war when Israeli took control of the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, 100 additional members were added to allow
representation of the Gaza area, which had been under Egyptian rule.
   When east Jerusalem was occupied, the council moved to Cairo,
Egypt, where it drafted the PLO charter in 1968.
   Arab governments endorsed the guerrilla movement as the ``sole,
legitimate representative of the Palestinian people'' in a summit
the same year.
   After Egypt signed the Camp David peace treaty with Israel in
1979, the council moved out of Cairo. Since then, the PNC has held
sessions in Syria, Jordan and Algeria.
   There are independent council members and those designated by PLO
factions and unions such as those representing students, lawyers and
women.
   Independents occupy 199 seats. The rest are distributed to the 10
unions and guerrilla factions.
   Council decisions also are made by majority vote.
   Fatah, the PLO's largest faction which is headed by Yasser
Arafat, has 55 seats, the largest block in the council.
   About 80 percent to 85 percent of the delegates are aligned with
Arafat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 0252EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Resolution242     11-15 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Resolution 242,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Resolution 242: A Key Statement on Middle East</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-PLO, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Excerpts of U.N. Security Council Resolution 242, which was
unanimously adopted Nov., 22, 1967:
   1. Affirms that the fulfilment of charter principles requires the
establishment of a just and lasting peace in the Middle East which
should include the application of both the following principles:
   (i) Withdrawal of Israel armed forces from territories occupied
in the recent conflict.
   (ii) Termination of all claims of states of belligerency and
respect for and acknowledgement of the sovereignty, territorial
integrity and political independence of every state in the area and
their right to live in peace within secure and recognized boundaries
free from threats or acts of force;
   2. Affirms further the necessity
   (a) For guaranteeing freedom of navigation through international
waterways in the area;
   (b) For achieving a just settlement of the refugee problem;
   (c) For guaranteeing the territorial inviolability and political
independence of every state in the area, through measures including
the establishment of demilitarized zones;
   3. Requests the secretary-general to designate a special
representative to proceed to the Middle East to establish and
maintain contacts with the states concerned in order to promote
agreement and assist efforts to achieve a peaceful and accepted
settlemernt in accordance with the provisions and principles in this
resolution;
   4. Requests the secretary-general to report to the Security
Council on the progress of the efforts of the special representative
as soon as possible.
</TEXT>
