<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Jobs Opened to Women in Military Following Discrimination
Review</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department is opening 11,138 jobs
to women after a year-long review of the military's treatment of its
female personnel.
   ``I think the overall message is that the secretary (of defense)
is firmly committed to opening all positions to women that are
compatible with existing laws and statutes,'' said Dr. David J.
Armor, the principal deputy assistant secretary for manpower.
   The decision announced Monday, when combined with previous moves
by the Navy, Air Force and Marine Corps, brings to more than 24,000
the number of once closed positions opened to women since the review
began in October 1987.
   Women comprise 10.4 percent of the U.S. armed forces, or about
217,400 enlisted personnel and officers of the 2.1 million total.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Educational Testing Organizations Adopt Code of Fair Practices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six educational testing organizations have
agreed to a voluntary code that commits them to strive for fairness
in tests given students of different races, sex or ethnic
backgrounds.
   The Code of Fair Testing Practices in Education announced Monday
was endorsed by six companies whose tests are taken by millions of
American students each year, from first grade to graduate school.
   The voluntary code also commits the test makers to review and
revise questions ``to avoid potentially insensitive content or
language,'' and to offer ``appropriately modified forms of tests''
to the handicapped.
   The signers of the new code are: Educational Testing Service, the
College Board, the American College Testing Program, CTB@McGraw
Hill, the Psychological Corp. and the Riverside Publishing Co.
