<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 0424EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Buran-History 1stLd-Wriththru   11-15 0746</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Buran-History, 1st Ld-Wriththru,a0470,0765</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Space Plane Looks Familiar, But Uses May Vary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to RECAST, ADD byline. Picks up graf 3
pvs, `In appearance ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet officials, who once criticized the American
space shuttle as wasteful and unreliable, joined the shuttle
business today with a craft that looks conspiciously like its U.S.
predecessor.
   The official Tass news agency even acknowledged similarities
between the crafts after its space plane, the Buran, made its maiden
unmanned flight today.
   ``In appearance the Buran resembles the U.S. space shuttle, which
has the same streamlined forms and double-delta wing _ the laws of
aerodynamics are international,'' it said.
   Despite the similarity in appearance and design, however, the
Soviets seem to have settled on different uses for their shuttle,
named the Buran, which is Russian for snowstorm.
   For years, the Soviets wouldn't even admit they were developing
their own shuttle, though Western specialists date the program back
to at least 1982.
   In June 1980, 10 months before the United States launched its
first shuttle, the Columbia, the chief of Soviet cosmonaut training,
Vladimir A. Shatalov, said Soviet officials ``consider that the
employment of these spacecraft is not justified for Soviet research
because present tasks can be solved with the well-tested methods in
an economical way.''
   Former cosmonaut Konstantin P. Feoktistov, writing in 1984 in a
Soviet newspaper, praised the American shuttle as ``an impressive
engineering achievement.'' But, he added, ``this system is not sound
economically and technologically.''
   Soviet officials appeared to become believers after settling on a
different focus for their shuttle than the one NASA chose.
   The U.S. shuttle was designed primarily to ferry satellites into
orbit. But Alexander I. Dunayev, the head of the Soviet space agency
Glavkosmos, said in 1987 that shuttles are not as economical as
single-use rocket boosters for placing satellites into orbit.
   In the clearest hint of the Soviet shuttle's purpose, he said
such craft are valuable for servicing space stations and satellites
and recovering objects from orbit.
   The reasoning seems sound because ever since they pioneered space
flight with the 1957 launch of Sputnik, the Soviets have forged a
proven track record for launching satellites on single-use rockets.
They put up more than 150 satellites a year, more than any other
country.
   In addition, the Soviets have concentrated on maintaining a
permanent manned presence in space aboard the orbiting space station
Mir. While Soviet officials have not said whether the shuttle is
capable of doing so, the shuttle might be able to ferry supplies and
cosmonauts to Mir.
   The Buran might also have the capability to retrieve and repair
potentially dangerous satellites in orbit.
   The Soviets have repeatedly criticized the military use of the
American shuttle, and the next American flight, of the Atlantis in
late November, is a mission for the Pentagon.
   But as with the American shuttle, the Soviets might use the Buran
for military missions. The U.S. Defense Department says the Soviet
shuttle could be used to deploy anti-satellite and ballistic missile
defense weapons.
   It isn't clear whether the Soviets will try to market their
shuttle's services to foreign customers, as they have done with
their Proton rocket boosters. If foreign customers are sought,
competition will come not only from the United States but from
Western Europe.
   The European Space Agency hopes to have its version of the
shuttle, the Hermes, on the launch pad in the late 1990s.
   The Buran clearly has advantages over its American cousin. Its
separate booster rocket, the Energia, is powered only by liquid
fuels, which can be extinguished in an emergency. It has no
solid-fuel boosters like the one that failed on the Challenger,
killing seven crewmembers.
   In addition, the Soviet shuttle can use jet engines in its tail,
giving it more maneuverability in landing than its American
counterpart.
   The Buran can also carry far heavier payloads than the American
shuttle. Energia can hoist more than 100 tons, and the orbiter
itself can carry about 66,000 pounds. The U.S. shuttle can carry
about 55,000 pounds.
   While Soviet officials maintain they did not copy the American
shuttle, the Pentagon has a different view.
   ``By using U.S. propulsion, computer, materials and airframe
technology and design, the Soviets were able to produce an orbiter
years earlier, and at far less cost, than if they had depended
solely on their own technology and engineering,'' the Defense
Department said in its 1988 report Soviet Military Power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 0431EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ArtAuction     11-15 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Art Auction,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Picasso Painting Brings Record Price For 20th Century Art</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private Latin American collector paid nearly
$25 million at auction for an early Pablo Picasso painting of a
mother kissing her son's upturned face, setting a record for a 20th
century work of art.
   ``Maternity,'' from the artist's blue period, sold Monday at
Christie's for twice its estimate, making it the third-highest price
ever paid for a work of art, behind Vincent Van Gogh's ``Irises''
and ``Sunflowers.''
   The 1901 oil on canvas was one of 28 post-Impressionist and
modern works on sale from the collection of William Goetz, a
Hollywood motion picture executive, and his wife Edith, the daughter
of film mogul, Louis B. Mayer.
   The 28 lots, all of which sold, fetched $85,024,500 _ a record
for a single owner's sale at auction.
   ``This may well be the sale of the century,'' said Christie's
president Christopher J. Burge, who presided over the auction.
   ``Tonight's auction was ripe for success _ unsurpassingly
beautiful works of art, a fiercely competitive market, and a
renowned provenance,'' he said.
   Earlier, Burge had predicted that the sale would fetch about $50
million.
   The Goetzes built their collection _ generally considered one of
the best of its kind _ during the 1940s and 1950s. Until this
summer, their paintings hung in their Holmby Hills mansion in
California, where the couple once entertained lavishly. He died in
1969; she died in June at the age of 82.
   After intense bidding, ``Maternity'' sold to an unidentified
Latin American collector, whose winning bid was placed by telephone.
The painting was expected to sell for $10 million.
   It depicts a blue-robed mother in a high-backed chair, with a
scissors and sewing basket at her feet. The child, standing next to
her, has a ball in his hands.
   The auction house described the painting as a ``majestic, tender
but unsentimental affirmation of maternal love.''
   ``It's a great, very rare picture,'' Burge said. ``It was a
unique opportunity to buy an early blue period picture'' of
Picasso's, who painted it when he was 20, he added.
   When Burge brought the hammer down on the $24.75 million bid, the
crowd broke into applause.
   ``Irises'' sold for $53.9 million in November 1987. A few months
earlier, Van Gogh's ``Sunflowers'' sold for $39.9 million.
   The second-highest priced work sold at Monday's auction was
Claude Monet's ``The Beach at Trouville,'' an 1870 oil on canvas,
which went for $10.78 million.
   The third-highest priced piece was Edgar Degas' ``Little Dancer
At 14 Years,'' a statue that sold for $10,175,000, a new record for
the artist. The statue depicts a dancer in polychromed bronze; she
wears a muslin skirt and her hair is tied with a satin ribbon.
   Eight artist's records were set during the auction; they were for
Picasso, Degas, Pierre Bonnard, Henri Fantin-Latour, Marie
Laurencin, Alfred Sisley, Chaim Soutine and Edouard Vuillard.
   All prices include a 10 percent commission paid by the buyer to
the auction house.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 0434EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SkinheadsBeating     11-15 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Skinheads Beating,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Community Leaders Outraged By Beating Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY CARPENTER HALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Community leaders and civil rights
activists expressed outrage at the beating death of a black man by
white youths believed to be ``skinheads,'' and one group called on
citizens to take direct action.
   Sunday's slaying was the nation's third linked to the bands of
young toughs who promote white supremacy. Skinheads, whose name is
derived from their shaved heads, have been linked to numerous
criminal acts against blacks, Asians, Jews and homosexuals
nationwide.
   Two other black men were injured in the attack by three young
men, who had shaved heads and wore military jackets. The three
victims were Ethiopian immigrants.
   Mayor Bud Clark said in a statement Monday he was ``saddened and
disturbed'' by the beatings, and urged citizens and public officials
to find a constructive solution to racial violence.
   ``A cowardly act against any one of our citizens is a cowardly
act against every one of our citizens,'' City Commissioner Bob Koch
said at a news conference. ``But let us not react out of hatred. Let
us react with love and understanding.''
   The militant Jewish Defense Organization mailed letters to
Portland synagogues asking them to arm their congregations.
   ``Violence will be met with violence,'' said Mordechai Levy, head
of the 3,000-member group based in New York.
   He said a $10,000 reward was being offered for information about
the beatings, or to anyone who physically restrains a neo-Nazi from
doing violence against a minority group.
   Police spokesman Dave Simpson said Monday that investigators had
no leads in finding the men who attacked Mulugeta Seraw, 27,
Wondwosen Tesfaye, 24, and Tilahule Antneh, 31. He said they may be
skinheads.
   Seraw was pronounced dead at Emanuel Hospital & Health Center,
where the two survivors were treated and released.
   Portland's African community planned a memorial service for
Seraw, who emigrated from Ethiopia seven years ago and worked at a
car rental agency.
   ``This is really kind of sad, for somebody to be looking for
someone with dark skin,'' said Abdi Hassan, who teaches a course on
southern Africa at Portland State University. ``No one is safe,
really, and it's a scary thought.''
   About 2,000 skinheads are active in 21 states, according to a
report issued last month by the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai
B'rith, which surveys race- or religion-motivated crimes.
   The Northwest Coalition Against Malicious Harassment last month
identified Oregon as a ``hotbed'' of skinhead activity. In Portland,
skinheads have been linked to various acts of vandalism and at least
two assaults, including the beating of an Asian man in March.
   Portland and the Northwest are ripe for such activity because so
few members of minority groups live here, said Herman Brame,
executive assistant for the Black United Fund. The Northwest has
been targeted by white supremacist groups as the site for an Aryan
``homeland.''
   Asked if Portland police were tracking skinhead activity, Simpson
would say only that the police intelligence unit ``is aware of some
of their activities.''
   ``Being a gang member isn't against the law. We deal with people
who violate the law,'' he said.
   Antneh and Tesfaye told police they were dropping Seraw off at
his apartment in a primarily white neighborhood early Sunday when
three men and two women pulled up in a car.
   The three men beat Seraw with a baseball bat and kicked him,
Antneh said, and beat the other two when they tried to intervene. He
said the attack lasted no more than two minutes.
   ``The women inside the car were shouting. They were saying `Let's
kill him. Kick him,''' Antneh told The Oregonian newspaper. ``They
(the men) never said anything. They just jumped us.''
   Skinheads were suspected in the beating death last December of a
41-year-old black man in Tampa, Fla., and the stabbing death in
February of a 24-year-old white man who took a black friend to a
party in Santa Clara County, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 0439EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-InsuranceCuts     11-15 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Insurance Cuts,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Attorney General Seeks Enforcement Of Insurance-Cutting
Proposition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ballot question that cuts insurance rates
20 percent should take effect while the state Supreme Court
considers insurance industry lawsuits seeking to void it, says state
Attorney General John Van de Kamp.
   California voters passed Proposition 103 last week, but lawsuits
filed immediately by insurance companies claim the rate rollback for
car, home and business insurance is unconstitutional.
   Van de Kamp asked the court Monday to withdraw the order it
issued last Thursday blocking enforcement of the initiative.
Residents who voted for the proposition believed they would see
immediate insurance rate relief, he said in papers filed with the
court.
   ``That expectation should not be frustrated without giving the
initiative a fair chance to work,'' he said.
   The attorney general's brief said insurers are unlikely to win
their suits against the initiative and have not shown that they
would suffer ``irreparable injury'' if Proposition 103 were allowed
to take effect while the insurance suits were pending.
   But if the court did not want to go as far as withdrawing its
order, Van de Kamp said, it should let all Proposition 103's
provisions take effect except for the rate rollback and require
insurance companies to set aside enough money to lower their
premiums if they lose their case.
   Members of Voter Revolt, a group that backed Proposition 103,
said Monday they didn't have enough money to enter the case now but
were starting a fund-raising drive to pay for a later court
intervention.
   Proposition 103, which was fiercely opposed by insurers and
passed by a narrow margin, requires insurance rates to be reduced to
20 percent below their November 1987 level. It also requires a
freeze at that level until November 1989, when auto insurance rates
would be cut an additional 20 percent for motorists with good
driving records.
   In addition, the measure includes an exemption from the rollback
for insurers who could show a ``substantial threat of insolvency,''
and conversion of the state insurance commissioner from an appointed
to an elected office in 1990.
   The measure allows the insurance commissioner to consider an
insurer's financial situation in granting exemptions from the 20
percent rollback and in reviewing future rate increase applications.
   Insurance companies argue that the rollback violates their
constitutional property rights by denying them the ability to make a
fair profit.
   Insurers spent at least $60 million fighting Proposition 103 and
other rate reduction initiatives on the ballot and promoting an
unsuccessful no-fault auto insurance initiative. It was the most
costly state proposition fight in the nation's history.
   Since the election, several insurers said they would no longer do
business in California. In the latest announcement, State Farm
Mutual Auto Insurance Co., the state's largest home and auto
insurer, said it has stopped issuing new policies in the state.
   Meanwhile, in Massachusetts, Allstate Insurance Co. said Monday
it would become the third major insurer in two years to stop writing
new auto insurance policies in that state, where insurers say strict
regulation of rates prevents them from making a profit.
   Allstate lost $115 million in Massachusetts over the past five
years, largely as a result of the ``unique regulatory environment''
for auto insurance, said Kevin Sullivan, director of Allstate's
Group Auto division.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
