<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     11-15 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Eases, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar this morning eased against many
foreign currencies in European trading as traders said they were
withdrawing from the market ahead of Wednesday's release of U.S.
trade figures for September. Gold prices rose.
   ``We expect the (trade) report to show a gap of $10 billion to
$11 billion,'' said a dealer at a major West German bank in
Frankfurt. The August U.S. trade deficit was 12.18 billion dollars.
   Meanwhile, Bank of England Governor Robin Leigh Pemberton said
foreign exchange markets were ``unjustified'' in expecting an
instant response or meeting from the Group of Seven industrialized
nations in the aftermath of the U.S. presidential elections.
   Leigh Pemberton said in an interview broadcast on the
Zurich-based European Business Channel that he does not favor a
lower dollar. He said there has been no change in the G-7's policy
of stable exchange rates since the group last met in Berlin in
September.
   ``The policy statement that flowed from our most recent meeting
is still valid and in my opinion there has been no change from the
stance expressed in that statement,'' he said.
   ``There was no reason why the dollar should be talked down and it
would be better if it shouldn't go down.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.25 yen to close at 123.25. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 123.45 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.7457 West German marks, up from 1.7452
   _1.4620 Swiss francs, down from 1.4645
   _5.9605 French francs, down from 5.9615
   _1.9663 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9735
   _1,298.25 Italian lire, down from 1,303.50
   _1.2328 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2297
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8090, unchanged from late
Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $422.70 a troy ounce, up
from $420.95 bid late Monday. At midmorning Tuesday, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $422.80.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $422.90, up from $420.00 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.56 to close at a bid $424.07.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.42 a troy ounce,
up from Monday's $6.39.
</TEXT>
