<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Amtrak-Return     11-15 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amtrak-Return,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Passenger Train Service Returns for First Time in 30 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLLEGE STATION, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The arrival of Amtrak's Texas
Eagle, wheels clicking and whistle sounding, marked the return of
passenger service between Dallas and Houston after more than 30
years and put the ``station'' back in this city's name.
   The Texas Eagle stopped briefly for ceremonies in College
Station-Bryan and in Corsicana, along its 265-mile route Monday from
Dallas to Houston. Passenger service for the public begins today.
   About 500 people watched the train arrive at a temporary depot at
the stop some 80 miles northwest of Houston. The Joe Azcona Band
performed Mexican mariachi music in the lounge for the inaugural run.
   For the special trip, Amtrak included its ceremonial office car
on the train as its caboose. The office car contains its own
kitchen, a sleeping area and a work-conference room.
   The car was most recently used by presidential hopeful Michael
Dukakis when he campaigned in California's San Joaquin Valley, said
Jim Larson, Amtrak's assistant vice president for operations.
   ``The car was used by three presidents,'' Larson said. John
Kennedy, Richard Nixon and Gerald Ford all used the Amtrak car, he
said.
   Many who toured the sleek, silver Texas Eagle in its inaugural
run were reminded of earlier train-travel experiences.
   ``I think it's great,'' said J.E. Loupot, a bookstore owner who
remembered arriving in College Station in 1928 as a Texas A&M
University freshman.
   ``We've been looking forward to it for a long time,'' said
Loupot, one of more than 100 Bryan-College Station residents who
took the train's inaugural ride. ``They'll (A&M students) use it,
too.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
