<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     11-15 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the international attention drawn to
the recent rescue of two trapped whales near Barrow, perhaps it was
inevitable that someone would put the saga to music.
   Paul Candide, a New York composer, recently sent Gov. Steve
Cowper a tape recording of his song, ``Gentle Creatures,'' with a
letter asking Cowper to share it with those who helped free the
California gray whales from the Arctic ice last month. A sampling of
the lyrics:
   ``Have you heard of the tale of the whales who got stuck
   and the people who helped set them free?
   They were swimming alone when they got down on their luck
   underneath the deep blue sea ...
   Eskimos brought saws to open the sea
   as they joined in to set them free
   And the Russians brought icebreakers through the sea
   as they joined in to save those three.''
   Candide told Cowper that the whales' story touched him so ``that
I had to put it into words and music.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Springfield couple whose dog
disappeared last week were reunited with the hound after it was
pictured in news reports with Gov. James R. Thompson.
   ``The governor's very happy that the dog is back with its
owners,'' Thompson spokesman Jim Bray said Monday. ``Anybody who
owns a dog knows the heartsick feeling when the dog leaves the yard
for any extended period.''
   Thompson had decided Sunday to keep the black-and-tan coon hound
after troopers found it Friday tied to a gate of the Governor's
Mansion with a note that read: ``Please give pup a good home, we
can't. We will miss him dearly, please take care of him.''
   The governor, who already has two dogs, named his new-found pet
Trooper in honor of the state police guards who found him.
   Bray speculated that when the dog left its owners' home, it may
have come into the hands of someone else, who left it at the mansion
rather than taking it to an animal shelter.
   ``Maybe they thought there would be plenty of room at the
mansion,'' he said.
   The dog's owners asked not to be identified, Bray said, but there
was no doubt that it was their pet.
   One of the owners described the 4-year-old dog in detail,
including a scar on its right ear and a scar on its left hip. And
when she called the dog's real name, Maximilian, he came running and
jumped into her arms, Bray said.
</TEXT>
