<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GirlSurvives     11-15 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Girl Survives,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>12-Year-Old Girl Survives Being Shot, Beaten, Left To Burn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TONASKET, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old girl who survived by playing
dead after she was shot, beaten and left in a burning house is ``one
of the bravest, strongest little girls I know,'' says the county
sheriff.
   The girl, Brook Rottinghaus, finally sneaked from the burning
house, which contained the bodies of her mother and stepfather, and
was able to get help early Sunday, authorities said.
   Okanogan County Sheriff Jim Weed said the girl awoke about 2 a.m.
Sunday to the sound of gunfire. She called downstairs from the loft
where she slept and a man she later identified as Lawrence R.
Sullens told her the noise was a propane stove popping, Weed said.
   Weed said the child saw her mother double over from a wound to
the abdomen.
   The man then climbed the stairs leading to the loft, shot the
girl, kicked her in the face and went back downstairs and started
two fires, police said.
   Brook went downstairs and hid, but the man found her, pulled her
into the living room, and kicked her in the face again.
   ``When she landed that time, she played dead with fires going on
each side of her,'' Weed said.
   Brook apparently waited a few minutes to be sure the man would
not come back, then ran about a quarter mile through snow in the
rural area in north-central Washington for help.
   ``This little gal was just exceptionally brave and had
unbelievable presence of mind in dealing with this situation,'' Weed
said.
   The girl was listed in good condition today at North Valley
Hospital in Tonasket, said Okanogan County Undersheriff Mike Murray.
He said she was shot in the upper right arm, then the bullet grazed
her chest and struck her upper left arm.
   The girl's father joined her from California, authorities said.
   Sullens, 25, was arrested Sunday night at his apartment in
Everett. He remained in jail early today, but no charges had been
filed, authorities said.
   Killed were Charles Glanville, 45, and his wife, Betty, 40.
   Weed said police did not have a motive for the shootings, but
added that the suspect was being questioned and was cooperative.
   ``We feel really bad,'' Weed said. ``It's so bizarre and she lost
so much.'' He said police have visited the girl at the hospital, and
some have taken teddy bears.
   ``I spent an hour with her. She's pretty upset but I don't think
the shock has hit her yet,'' Weed said.
   Sheriff's deputies say Sullens, a martial arts expert, had
purchased a tae kwon do studio near Everett from the Glanvilles and
had been to their home once before.
   Tonasket is a town of 1,000 residents about 20 miles from the
Canadian border.
</TEXT>
