<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 0703EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AbortionProtest     11-15 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion Protest,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Chief: Abortion Activists Must Pay Costs Of Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 102 anti-abortion activists
arrested for trying to block the doors of a women's clinic may end
up paying the Police Department for costs incurred in handling the
protest, the police chief said.
   Police Chief Joe Gerwens said Monday he had asked City Prosecutor
Scott Walker to try to recover the estimated $3,800 the Nov. 4
protest cost the department.
   ``They chose civil disobedience to make a point and they should
be willing to pay the consequences,'' Gerwens said. ``They planned
on being arrested.''
   Demonstrators planted themselves before the entrance to the Sigma
Women's Center, which advertises abortions, waiting to carried to
paddy wagons and booked on trespassing charges.
   It took 26 Fort Lauderdale police officers, plus eight from
nearby Oakland Park and the Broward County Sheriff's Office, to
quell the disturbance, Gerwens said.
   In addition to the officers' time, police cars had to be diverted
from their assigned zones to handle the protest. Other costs
included transportation, two portable toilets, film for booking
prisoners, an emergency medical truck and an ambulance, he said.
   Bonnie Callahan, a spokeswoman for the anti-abortion organization
Rescue South Florida, which was among several groups at the protest,
called the plan to seek reimbursement unfair.
   Ms. Callahan, whose 13-year-old daughter was among those
arrested, said the demonstration ``was not for the purpose of
getting arrested or getting publicity. Our main reason was to save
babies and save women from being exploited.''
   All those arrested were charged with trespassing, and all but one
were immediately released and given notice to appear in court.
   Gerwens said that by seeking reimbursement, the city was not
taking a position on the protest, only that taxpayers should not
have to pay for a deliberate disturbance. He said the department
will further pursue the idea of making those convicted of a crime
pay the police costs involved.
</TEXT>
