<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     11-15 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0766</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wintry Storm Sweeps Rockies, Northern Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy snow and high winds struck the Rocky Mountains and northern
Plains, with more than a foot of snow falling at Jackson, Wyo., and
in the northern Utah mountains.
   The storm left snow in the mountains of Southern California on
Monday and battered the region with high winds and rain, downing
tree limbs and power lines.
   A rogue wave in seas churned up by the storm swept over a jetty
next to Morro Rock, 180 miles northwest of Los Angeles, killing two
fishermen, according to the Morro Bay Police Department. A third
fisherman managed to cling to the jetty but suffered a broken arm.
   In Salt Lake City, a 17-year-old girl died Monday when she lost
control of her car on a snow-slickened road and it slid into the
path of a school bus.
   In Wyoming, strong winds accompanying the snow created
near-blizzard conditions in some areas. Winds up to 61 mph were
reported in Laramie, with winds up to 55 mph in Casper.
   Ski operators in western Wyoming were happy at the possibility of
early openings. ``We love it,'' said Jim Sullivan, mountain manager
at the Snow King ski area in Jackson.
   With the storm moving across the Plains, heavy snow and high
winds were developing from eastern Colorado and eastern Wyoming to
the Nebraska Panhandle and parts of the Dakotas. Winter storm
warnings were posted for portions of northern Arizona, southern
Utah, the Colorado mountains, southeastern Wyoming, northwestern
South Dakota, eastern North Dakota and the northwest corner of
Minnesota.
   Snow advisories were in effect over western North Dakota,
northeastern Montana, much of Wyoming and northwestern New Mexico,
and winter storm watches for heavy snow were issued for northeastern
Colorado, northwestern Nebraska, portions of South Dakota,
southeastern North Dakota and much of northwest Minnesota.
   Unseasonably mild air to the southeast of the storm raised
temperatures to the mid 60s this morning as far north as Kansas
City, Mo.
   Rain fell over portions of the Pacific Northwest, especially in
western Oregon, while densefog developed again this morning across
parts of the Southeast.
   Clear skies prevailed from southern New England across the
central and southern Appalachians and the Ohio and middle
Mississippi valleys.
   A number of cities reported record-high temperatures for the date
Monday, including Albuquerque, N.M., where 72 broke the 1967 record
of 70; Dodge City, Kan., where 82 was 4 degrees higher than the 1897
record; and Houston, where it reached 87, breaking the 1978 mark of
86.
   The high in the nation Monday was 92 degrees at McAllen, Texas.
   Today's forecast called for snow from the central and southern
Rockies to the northern Plains; showers and thunderstorms from the
central and southern Plains to the middle and upper Mississippi
Valley, and rain in the Pacific Northwest. Stiff winds were expected
from the Rockies across the Plains to the Mississippi Valley,
causing blowing and drifting snow from eastern Colorado to the
northern Plains.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 20s and 30s from the
northern and central Rockies across western Nebraska and the
northern Plains to northern Minnesota; in the 40s and 50s from New
England across the Great Lakes to the upper Mississippi Valley and
central Plains, and in the southern Rockies to the Pacific
Northwest; in the unseasonably warm 70s in eastern Kansas, Missouri
and the lower Ohio Valley; and in the 80s from Florida across the
Gulf Coast to much of Texas. Elsewhere, highs were forecast for the
60s and 70s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 10
degrees at Helena, Mont., to 78 degrees at Corpus Christi (Texas)
Naval Air Station.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 56 fair; Boston 48 fair; Buffalo 32 fair;
Charleston, S.C., 48 fair; Cincinnati 47 fair; Cleveland 38 fair;
Detroit 42 fair; Miami 75 partly cloudy; New York 50 fair;
Philadelphia 46 cloudy; Pittsburgh 39 fair; Portland, Maine, 41
fair; Washington 42 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 26 snow; Chicago 49 partly cloudy; Dallas-Fort
Worth 75 windy; Denver 41 showery; Des Moines 57 cloudy;
Indianapolis 46 fair; Kansas City 67 windy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 39
cloudy; Nashville 48 fair; New Orleans 70 foggy; St. Louis 57 cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 40 windy; Anchorage 25 cloudy; Las Vegas 49
fair; Los Angeles 55 fair; Phoenix 52 fair; Salt Lake City 34
cloudy; San Diego 56 fair; San Francisco 52 partly cloudy; Seattle
44 drizzle.
   _Canada: Montreal 37 fair; Toronto 30 fair.
</TEXT>
