<HEAD>Palestinians Declare Independent Homeland</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-PLO, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today's developments concerning the Palestinian declaration of
independence:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ALGIERS, Algeria _ The PLO's parliament-in-exile proclaims an
independent Palestinian state, approving a new, moderate political
program that indirectly recognizes Israel and renounces terrorism.
The move, a victory for moderates in the Palestine Liberation
Organization, is largely symbolic but could add impetus to
Palestinian efforts to achieve self-rule.
   Israel's leaders oppose a Palestinian state, and authorities said
they would quash unilateral Palestinian steps toward self-rule.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   BETHLEHEM, Occupied West Bank _ The army seals off the West Bank
and Gaza Strip to squelch celebrations of the Algiers declaration,
but Arab youths defiantly take to the streets. Gaza is under curfew
for a fourth straight day and a curfew is imposed in Bethlehem for
the first time since 1967.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ The Reagan administration reacts cautiously to the
PLO move. President Reagan says before the declaration in Algiers
that the Palestinians' implicit recognition of Israel's right to
exist ``would be some progress'' toward achieving lasting peace in
the Middle East.
   The United States has long insisted that the PLO accept Israel's
right to exist and denounce terrorism if it wants to be recognized
by Washington.
</TEXT>
