<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StudentLockup     11-15 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Student Lockup,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teacher Will Not Be Disciplined For Prison Simulation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHEATON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school teacher will not be
disciplined for arranging a field trip in which students were
strip-searched, hog-tied and forced to eat fish-head soup in a
simulation of Third World prison conditions, officials said.
   ``Some of the learning activities that were conducted went beyond
what was really necessary to accommodate the objectives of the
program,'' said Denie Young, spokeswoman for the Wheaton-Warrenville
school district, at a school board meeting Monday.
   Superintendent Richard Short ``supports the program, the prison
simulation,'' she said. ``The administration just feels that parts
of it were carried to an extreme.''
   Last month's voluntary field trip to Wheaton College by 34
juniors and seniors from Wheaton North High School was intended to
give students a taste of criminal-justice systems, included one that
might exist in a Third World country ruled by a despot.
   The field trip included strip-searches, a meal of potato soup
with a fish head floating in it, blindfolds, handcuffs and nude
``duck-walking'' involving some of the boys, Ms. Young said.
   The students who participated had no complaints, but afterward,
some parents said they were outraged by the field trip, and the
school board asked Short to evaluate the program.
   Short told about 50 parents that there would be no disciplinary
action against Wheaton North teacher David Oliphant, a popular
American government instructor who arranged the field trip.
   But Short said the consent form parents were asked to sign was
inadequate.
   ``We would want to see to it that the communication with parents
would be a lot more effective'' in the future, he said. ``There was
a need for parents to have a greater understanding of what they were
signing.''
   The field trip was supervised by Don Smarto, director of the
college's Institute for Prison Ministries, who acted as the
``warden.'' Two college students were ``guards.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
