<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Politics     11-15 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Politics,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Invites Peres To Coalition Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, entrusted with
forming Israel's next government, said today that he will try to
coax the left-leaning Labor Party into his rightist-religious
coalition.
   Labor leader Shimon Peres accepted Shamir's invitation to attend
coalition talks today, but expressed doubts his party would join a
Shamir-led government. Labor and Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc are
sharply divided on how to end the Arab-Israeli conflict.
   Shamir issued his invitation to Peres after being told by
President Chaim Herzog that the president's office had been flooded
with thousands of calls urging a Labor-Likud government.
   ``I said many times that I prefer a broad-based government
including the two large parties,'' Shamir said on Israel television.
``I'm looking for a way to bring this about.''
   A unity government would blunt the power of Shamir's other
coalition partners _ four religious parties that seek to impose
changes on Israel's secular majority and three extreme right-wing
parties that demand annexation of the occupied lands.
   ``The public is worried. There is a wish for unity to confront
the dangers from outside and the separation threatening us from
within,'' Herzog told Shamir on Monday after asking him to form the
next government.
   Shamir has six weeks to form a ruling coalition, and is expected
to get the needed 61-seat majority in the 120-member Parliament.
   In the Nov. 1 elections, Likud won 40 seats, Labor 39 and the
religious parties 18, putting the smaller parties in the position of
kingmaker.
   In issuing his invitation to Labor, Shamir ruled out an equal
partnership such as the uneasy one formed between Labor and Likud
after the inconclusive elections of 1984. Shamir also hinted Labor
could help formulate a peace strategy if it joined the government.
   But Peres appeared skeptical. ``I don't think there are many
chances for it (a national unity government),'' Peres said on Israel
radio without elaborating.
   Labor's secretary general, Uzi Baram, said his party would not
accept a junior position and demanded parity in the distribution of
Cabinet posts, including senior jobs for Peres and Labor's No. 2,
Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin.
   But Israel radio quoted Rabin as saying Labor should join the new
government even as a junior partner to prevent a narrow
rightist-religious coalition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
