<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-PLO     11-15 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-PLO,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Rejects PLO Declaration As `Double Talk'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-PLO, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Israeli Foreign Ministry today rejected a
PLO declaration of independence for Palestinians in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip as ``double talk.''
   Similarly, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir rejected the PLO
announcement of a Palestinian state as another step in the ``war by
Arab terror organizations'' to destroy the Jewish state.
   Despite moderate language implictly recognizing Israel, the PLO
document approved Monday in Algeria was also rejected by Foreign
Minister Shimon Peres, leader of the left-leaning Labor Party.
   ``There is no chance ... that any declaration of theirs will be
accepted before negotiations,'' said Peres. ``Our problem now is not
solving the Palestinian issue but how to open negotiations because
without negotiations there will be no solution to the problem.''
   Hours after the declaration was announced, Israel's official
response came in a Foreign Ministry statement that criticized the
Algiers declaration as ``double talk'' employed to excuse PLO
support for violence and terror.
   ``No gimmick can mask the tragedy inflicted upon the Palestinian
people time and again by the absence of reasonable, realistic and
peace-seeking leadership,'' said the statement, which called on
other nations not to recognize the PLO state.
   Shamir, addressing his remarks to Palestinians in the occupied
territories, predicted there would be ``political war'' with the
Palestinians over international recognition of the PLO state.
   Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Algeria, Kuwait and Malaysia have already
recognized the Palestinian state declared in Algiers.
   ``This is not the way to a life of peace, security and
coexistence with the Jewish people in the land of Israel,'' Shamir
said. ``This is another step in the war of Arab terror organizations
against Israel's existence and independence and we shall respond
accordingly.''
   Both Peres and Shamir spoke at the Negev Desert communal farm of
Sde Boker, where Israeli leaders gathered to pay tribute to Israel's
first prime minister, David Ben-Gurion, on the 15th anniversary of
his death.
   Left-wing Israelis welcomed the more moderate language of the PLO
and the declaration's recognition of the Jewish state.
   But hard-line politicians called for annexation or a massive
drive to settle Jews in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip where
1.5 million Arabs and 70,000 Israels live.
   Trade Minister Ariel Sharon, a leading member of Shamir's
right-wing Likud bloc, called the declaration a ``dangerous
development'' and said Israel should assert its claim by annexing
part of the occupied land in response.
   He said the security situation in the occupied lands could
further deterioriate. At least 312 Palestinians and 11 Israelis have
been killed in the 11-month uprising.
   In an interview with the daily Yediot Ahronot, Shamir called for
negotiations under the U.S.-Soviet sponsorship as an alternative to
a U.N.-sponsored international conference favored by the Arabs.
   Negotiations would take place with Egyptian, Jordanian and
Palestinian delegations but not the PLO, Yediot Ahronot reported.
   Israel's major dailies headlined the PLO's new political program
announced in Algiers, focusing on its acceptance of U.N. Security
Council Resolution 242 that implicitly recognizes Israel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
