<DOCNO> AP881115-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 0825EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Sudan     11-15 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudan,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Agree on Cease-Fire, Relief Deliveries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of southern Sudan's rebels has
agreed to a cease-fire in his 5{-year rebellion and to allow relief
to reach starving war refugees, the official Sudan News Agency
reported today.
   In return, the agency said, renegade army Col. John Garang
expects a national state of emergency to be lifted and a
constitutional conference convened.
   The agreement was reported in dispatches from the Ethiopian
capital of Addis Ababa, where it was to be signed today, and from
Nairobi, Kenya. It does not commit the government, but Prime
Minister Sadek Mahdi gave the talks his blessing and said he would
follow up on any agreements reached.
   Garang negotiated the agreement with Mohammed Osman Mirghani,
patriarch of the Democratic Unionist Party, the second partner in
Mahdi's governing coalition.
   Garang organized the Sudan People's Liberation Army in early 1983
and began his fight for southern autonomy and political, economic
and administrative reforms. Then-President Gaafar Nimeiri's
proclamation of Islamic law exacerbated the war six months later,
and Garang has vowed not to lay down arms until Sudan's civilian
government abrogates Sharia.
   Traditionally, the country's Moslem majority dominates the
central government. Most of the southerners are Christian or animist.
   Relief workers say the accumulated effects of more than five
years of war have brought widespread famine to much of the south
this year. They estimate that 1.3 million of the region's 6 million
inhabitants have fled this year alone, with starvation killing more
than 250,000 people.
   There was no immediate reaction to the agreement from the
government. Foreign Minister Hussein Suleiman Abu-Saleh attended the
talks as a member of the Democratic Unionist leadership.
   Defense Minister Abdul-Maguid Hamid Khaleel has said the military
would welcome any peace agreement.
   ``We are the people most concerned about peace, because we suffer
more than the others from war,'' Khaleel said. ``We are with the
strategy of peace (but) will continue defending the territorial
integrity of Sudan.''
   The Addis Ababa talks have drawn fire from another coalition
partner, the fundamentalist National Islamic Front, which saw them
as a ploy to force the Moslem party from the government. Any
agreement between Mirghani and Garang would make future talks
involving the government ineffective, the front's political affairs
secretary, Ali Haj, said.
   The Sudan News Agency gave few details on the agreement. The
agency said Mirghani described his discussions with Garang as
``serious and frank.''
</TEXT>
