<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ComputerVirus     11-15 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Computer Virus,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students At University Campus Warned Of Computer Virus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warnings about a rapidly spreading computer
virus have been issued to students at California State University,
Northridge, following reports the virus is disrupting functions of
Macintosh computers.
   ``In general, this thing is spreading like mad,'' Chris Sales,
the university's computer center consultant, said Monday. ``It
originated in West Germany, found its way to UCLA and in a short
time infected us here.''
   School officials say at least a dozen of the Macintosh computers
at the suburban San Fernando Valley campus have been affected by a
virus that was discovered last week.
   A computer virus is akin to a living virus, and can spread from
terminal to terminal and even computer system to computer system by
``infected'' discs. It can disrupt such functions as word processing
and printing.
   Some viruses can even destroy valuable files, but Cal State
officials said the bug found there does not erase data. It does
stall computers, though, and removal requires hours of
reprogramming, officials said.
   Students' computer discs are being tested for the virus before
they are able to rent a Macintosh at the university bookstore.
   Earlier this month, another virus duplicated itself in university
and government research computers nationwide, slowing the computers'
processing speeds and filled up their memories. A graduate student
is under investigation in that case.
</TEXT>
