<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 4th Ld-Writethru,a0500,0748</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Closes West Bank, Gaza Strip To Squelch Independence
Celebration</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with prisoner slain, Israeli
reax to declaration. Pick up 12th pvs, `Shamir, who</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HAITHAM HAMAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army sealed off the
occupied lands today to block celebrations of Palestinian
independence, but Arab youths defiantly took to the streets,
shooting off firecrackers and singing a nationalist anthem.
   Underground leaders of the Palestinian uprising called a general
strike in the West Bank and Gaza Strip today to mark what the PLO's
parliament-in-exile, meeting in Algeria, proclaimed as independence
day.
   In Bethlehem, under curfew for the first time since 1967, dozens
of teen-agers ignored threats of fines and jail terms to run through
streets lighting fireworks and singing the nationalist song, ``My
Homeland, My Homeland.''
   Army jeeps blocked town entrances and soldiers ordered residents
to stay indoors. ``Everybody who goes out will endanger his life,''
one soldier announced over a loudspeaker.
   At Dheishe refugee camp, several cars belonging to Jewish
settlers were stoned, their windows smashed. Smoke from burning
tires rose from the camp, and Israeli soldiers could be heard firing
rubber bullets for riot control.
   In the Gaza Strip town of Khan Yunis, an 18-year-old Palestinian
was shot by soldiers but the circumstances were not clear, hospital
officials said.
   In Israel, a 30-year-old Palestinian prisoner from Gaza was found
strangled to death in his cell in the Ashkelon Jail, and police
suspect he was slain by an Arab cellmate for allegedly collaborating
with the Israeli authorities.
   The army extended a curfew over the Gaza Strip's 650,000
residents for a fourth day and sealed the West Bank. The orders
blocked residents of the territories from entering Israel and
reporters from going to either occupied area without an army escort.
   Police forces were deployed within Israel, where leaders of the
720,000 Israeli Arabs ordered a general strike to protest recent
house demolitions.
   In Israeli-annexed Arab east Jerusalem, an additional 1,000
police officers were deployed to prevent pro-PLO demonstrations, and
authorities banned gatherings of more than 10 people.
   In Israel's first official response to the declaration of
independence, a Foreign Ministry statement called it ``double
talk.'' Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir predicted ``political war''
with the Palestinians over the declaration.
   Shamir was quoted by the daily Yediot Ahronot as saying he would
propose a new peace plan to Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
   Shamir, who opposes a U.N.-sponsored international conference
endorsed by the Arabs, wants peace negotiations with Palestinians
and Arab states to be under the auspices of the United States and
Soviet Union.
   Zeev Hever, a settlers' leader from Hebron, said the Algiers
declaration has ``totally no meaning. Israel rules over the
territory and decides what happens.''
   Sheik Mohammad Abu Teir, a Moslem religious leader, criticized
the declaration's implicit recognition of Israel and repeated the
fundamentalist stand that all of Palestine should be an Islamic
state.
   ``We have been offering sacrifices for many years and now they
recognize the state of the Jews. Where is the land of this state?''
he said by telephone from Umm Touba village, near Bethlehem.
   The fireworks, graffiti splashed on walls and raising of outlawed
Palestine flags came despite an army announcement that Palestinians
could face prison sentences of five years and fines of $10,000 for
such actions.
   In Bethlehem, a map picturing Palestine before the Jewish state's
creation was painted on one wall, with this slogan:
``Congratulations, Palestine.'' The map contradicted the
independence declaration, which was based on a 1947 U.N. plan
calling for creation of Jewish and Arab states side-by-side in
Palestine.
   The Algiers declaration was expected to fuel the revolt against
Israel's 21-year rule in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. The 11-month
uprising has cost the lives of at least 312 Palestinians and 11
Israelis.
   But the declaration will have little immediate impact on life in
the occupied lands. Israeli leaders oppose a Palestinian state, and
authorities said they would quash unilateral Palestinian steps
toward self-rule.
   Palestinian leaders expressed hope the declaration would get the
stalled peace process moving by implicitly recognizing Israel.
   ``This is the beginning of a new era for the Palestinians,'' said
lawyer Fayez Abu Rahme, a prominent PLO supporter in the Gaza Strip.
``It shows the Palestinians are ready to co-exist with Israel, that
they want a state side-by-side with Israel.''
</TEXT>
