<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Greece-Palestinian     11-15 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Palestinian,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Postpones Extradition Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The supreme court today postponed its
decision on the extradition of a Palestinian wanted by the United
States for the 1982 bombing of a Pan Am jetliner.
   Panayiotis Theodoropoulos, president of the five-member panel,
said the decision to extradite Mohammed Rashid would be issued after
the United States supplies key documents needed to make a ruling.
   The 39-year-old Palestinian is charged with planting a bomb
aboard a Pan Am Jumbo jet flying from Tokyo to Hawaii. A Japanese
teen-ager was killed and 15 other people were injured in the blast.
   Rashid may also be linked to the bloody July 11 attack aboard the
City of Poros cruise ship off Athens that killed nine people and
injured 98. Police theorize the attack may have been a failed
attempt to take the ship hostage and force Rashid's release.
   On Oct. 10, a lower court approved the extradition of Rashid, but
the decision must be approved by the Areos Pagos, the supreme court.
   Before today's decision was announced, hundreds of police
officers and sharpshooters with automatic weapons guarded the court
building near the city center.
   Rashid's defense lawyers contested the postponement, arguing that
lower courts had requested the same documents in the past and failed
to get them.
   ``The documents have been requested ... twice in the past. What
makes you think they'll send them now?'' defense lawyer Spyros
Fitrakis asked the court.
   The high court asked the United States to supply an official copy
of a Japanese visa application allegedly filled in by Rashid in
Baghdad, Iraq, in July 1982.
   It also asked for official transcripts of testimony given by an
FBI agent that was used to draw up the extradition request.
   ``These are the documents we need. It they can't send them, they
have to explain why,'' Theodoropoulos said.
   According to the extradition request, Rashid received a visa in
Baghdad to visit Japan.
   ``It is obvious that the judges are not convinced by the American
evidence. If they had the documents they would have sent them
already,'' Rashid told the court.
   Rashid was arrested at Athens airport on May 29 on a tip from the
U.S. Embassy in Athens.
   U.S. officials have said they view Rashid's extradition as a test
of Greece's determination to combat international terrorism.
   American officials have said Rashid was also involved in the 1986
bombing of a TWA jetliner over southern Greece that killed four
Americans. The blast is not mentioned in the extradition request.
</TEXT>
