<2ND_LINE>PM-Synagogue Arson,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stolen Torahs Find New Home In Burned Out Synagogue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Brooklyn synagogue that lost holy Torah scrolls
in an arson fire received two replacement scrolls from an unlikely
source: a police department warehouse.
   Police said the Torahs had gone unclaimed and unused for years
after being recovered from thieves.
   ``Today is a very special day,'' Rabbi Hillel David said in
accepting the Torahs on Monday.
   Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward, whose mother was an orphan
adopted by a Jewish family in Brooklyn, said the ceremony held a
special significance for him.
   ``Today I repay a little bit of a major debt that I always felt I
owed the Jewish community,'' Ward said.
   David's Orthodox Congregation Rabbinical Institute Shari Torah
was heavily damaged and five Torah scrolls were destroyed in a fire
set on the Sabbath between the holiest days on the Jewish calendar _
Rosh Hashana, the New Year, and Yom Kippur, the day of repentance.
   Two boys, ages 12 and 15, from the neighborhood where the
synagogue is located, were charged with arson for the Sept. 7 blaze.
   Police say the two boys broke into the Orthodox synagogue in the
racially mixed neighborhood, spray-painted swastikas on the walls,
set a fire and unrolled and burned the Torahs.
   Ward, who made the presentation with Mayor Edward Koch, said the
two Torahs _ Judaism's most holy objects _ originally belonged to a
police officer who died years ago. The unidentified officer received
the Torahs when a synagogue he attended in Brooklyn was disbanded;
when he died, they were passed on to his family.
   In 1983, burglars took the Torahs from the family home but they
were recovered by the police, said Deputy Inspector John Higgins,
who is in charge of the property room.
   The family members, who asked to remain anonymous, made no effort
to reclaim the Torahs. Ward said that when he contacted them
recently, they agreed to donate the scrolls to David's congregation
of about 300.
</TEXT>
