<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     11-15 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Kills Five Sinhalese Demonstrators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army opened fire on thousands of
people protesting the massacre of Sinhalese bus passengers by
suspected Tamil rebels, killing five and injuring 17, police said
today.
   Soldiers began shooting at 3,000 Sinhalese who were demonstrating
today in Matala, 65 miles northeast of Colombo, after tear gas
failed to disperse the crowd, a senior police official said.
   Two people were killed and 11 wounded, said the official,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   On Monday, soldiers and police killed three other people and
injured six when they broke up demonstrations in the central towns
of Anuradhapura, Polonnaruawa, Horawapatana and Kekirawa, police
said.
   They said the demonstrations were to protest the government's
failure to prevent a massacre of 27 Sinhalese bus passengers by
Tamil rebels.
   The rebels ambushed a bus on Monday near the village of
Pinkatiya, about 140 miles northeast of Colombo, and killed 27
Sinhalese passengers, according to police and military sources, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Police blamed the largest Tamil rebel group, the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam, denied they were responsible.
   In a statement issued by their London office and telexed to news
agencies and newspapers, the Tigers said: ``This is malicious
propaganda carried out by the Sri Lankan government to tarnish the
image of our organization.''
   The police and military sources said the killings were part of a
continued Tamil effort to drive away the Sinhalese from the
northeast, where the Tigers have been waging a five-year war for an
independent homeland.
   Tamils, who form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people,
claim they are discriminated against by the majority Sinhalese, who
form 75 percent of the population and control the military and the
government.
   The government's peace overtures to the Tamils have sparked a
backlash among radical Sinhalese, who claim too many concessions
have been offered to the minority community.
   The government has set up local administrative councils to grant
limited autonomy to the Tamils, but the Tigers rejected the plan in
1987 because they said it did not meet their expectations.
   The Tigers have vowed to disrupt a provincial council election
scheduled for Saturday in the northeast.
   Last week, Sinhalese radicals called a four-day strike to demand
the resignation of President Junius R. Jayewardene. The government
ordered soldiers to open fire at anti-government demonstrators and
decreed the death sentence for people convicted of starting strikes.
</TEXT>
