<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush's Soviet Challenge, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0425,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Sakharov's Warning for the New President</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf with Gorbachev trip to New York after 4th graf
pvs, Bush has</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A warning by Soviet human rights activist
Andrei D. Sakharov that the West has more to fear from the failure
of Kremlin reforms than from their successes goes to the heart of a
dilemma facing George Bush as he prepares to lead American policy.
   ``The threat of perestroika doesn't consist of its success but of
its bloody failure. This would be a total calamity,'' said Sakharov,
conjuring up an image of a newly militant Kremlin again embracing
the totalitarianism and expansionism of the Stalin era.
   With Sakharov's words still ringing, Bush must ask himself how to
deal with Gditions to cooperative ventures. If we
don't, we may one day find ourselves the odd man out, economically
and militarily,'' wrote Hough, an outspoken Gorbachev enthusiast.
   Other analysts believe Gorbachev is already in domestic political
trouble, that there is little the United States can do to help or
harm him, and that he is interested in good relations with America
as well as with the rest of the West.
   ``The biggest problem that the United States faces now is being
blamed by our allies if Gorbachev fails,'' said John Van Oudenaren,
a RAND Corp. expert on Soviet relations with the West.
   While it is true that Gromyko is out and Dobrynin is down, they
are no less hostile to the United States than the sometimes
acid-tongued Yakovlev and Falin.
   Moreover, ``the actual impact that we can have on the Soviet
Union is limited,'' said Van Oudenaren. ``The biggest challenge is
to avoid being blamed for a failure of Gorbachev.'' Such blame can
be avoided by being responsive to his initiatives and having a very
active diplomacy toward him.''
   ``The chances are that Gorbachev will fail in some way, or enjoy
at most a partial success. The wildest expectations that people in
the West have for him are not likely to come to pass,'' said Van
Oudenaren, echoing a view that is widely held by U.S. government and
academic experts on the Soviet Union.
   ``The Reagan administration had a hyperactive policy toward
Gorbachev,'' said Van Oudenaren. And that policy bore fruit in the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty, signed last December, and
in talks toward a Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty.
   Those negotiations helped convince the presidential electorate
that a vote for Bush was a vote for peace. Bush may have to keep the
same pace if he wishes to make the same argument in 1992.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Bryan Brumley covers national security issues for
The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
