<DOCNO> AP881115-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1008EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AeromexicoTrial     11-15 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Aeromexico Trial,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Declares Mistrial in Aeromexico Liability Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new trial must be held in the Aeromexico
jetliner disaster because the first jury was tainted by speculation
that the pilot of a small plane may have died before slamming into
the jetliner, a judge ruled.
   A pool of prospective jurors was ordered to begin the selection
process again today in the trial to determine the blame for the
August 1986 accident that killed 82 people.
   ``I see some prejudice, some very genuine prejudice, to certain
parties,'' said U.S. District Judge David V. Kenyon, who declared a
mistrial Monday in the civil suit.
   The new panel cannot hear any allegations that pilot William
Kramer was dead or incapacitated before the accident, ruled Kenyon.
   ``It's nothing more than a guess,'' he said at one point.
   Kramer's private plane entered restricted airspace and hit an
Aeromexico airliner over Cerritos on Aug. 31, 1986. The pilot was
killed along with his wife and daughter, as well as 64 people on the
jet and 15 on the ground.
   In opening statements last week, Kramer lawyers said the pilot
may have died of heart failure two minutes before his plane collided
with the jet.
   That suggestion tainted the jury, alleged Justice Department
lawyer Steven J. Riegel, who sought a mistrial. Riegel is defending
the government in more than 70 lawsuits.
   Although Kenyon denied the mistrial motion last Thursday, he did
rule the Kramer family lawyers couldn't raise the death or
incapacitation issue because it was purely speculative and the
evidence couldn't support the scenario.
   Riegel raised the mistrial motion again Monday. Kenyon granted
the motion after several hours of argument.
   The judge noted that the trial had just begun and no evidence had
been presented.
   ``It seems to me much cleaner'' this way, Kenyon said, adding he
didn't want to take objecting parties ``kicking and screaming'' into
the rest of the trial, which is expected to last at least through
January.
   The trial will decide how to apportion liability in the crash so
attorneys representing more than 75 plaintiffs can proceed with
lawsuits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
