<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MonitorResignations 1stLd-Writethru a0486 11-15 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Monitor Resignations, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0486,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christian Science Monitor Editor, Aides Step Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf to CORRECT that Fanning's term as head
of American Society of Newspaper Editors ended this spring, sted
that she `recently was named' to the post.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The editor of the Christian Science Monitor has
resigned, saying her decision was in part a protest of a plan to
trim the size of the church-owned paper and ``drastically cut'' its
staff.
   Katherine Fanning and two of her top assistants, David Anable,
managing editor, and David Winder, assistant managing editor of the
paper, announced their resignations Monday.
   Fanning said her resignation also came after a decision to allow
business manager, John Hoagland, control over content, which she
said ``threatens the editorial independence.''
   ``The increasing diversion of church funds from the Monitor to
other media, the decision to downsize the paper and drastically cut
its staff means the serious weakening of its editorial substance,''
she said after stepping down from her post.
   But Hoagland said the changes were positive. ``We expect that
this new alignment, plus revenues from our new products, will help
support our daily newspaper,'' he said of the 80-year-old paper that
has a Monday through Friday circulation of 170,000. ``We continue
with an unwavering commitment to offer both print and broadcast
services.''
   Fanning, 61, said in a statement that the church had decided to
cut the daily size of the newspaper to 16 pages from its current
average of 28 pages and to eliminate advertising.
   ``I leave this superb editorial staff with great sadness and
profound respect,'' she said.
   The paper has lost money for years but is widely respected by its
readers and by the newspaper industry. Hoagland said redesign and
other changes to be implemented in February of next year would be
revealed in the next few weeks.
   Directors of the church named Richard Nenneman, general manager
of print publishing for the church, as editor in chief in charge of
editorial content for the newspaper and all of its print and
broadcast enterprises. Richard Cattani, editor of the editorial
page, was named editor.
   Fanning became the first woman editor of the Monitor in 1983
after leaving the Daily News in Anchorage, Alaska, where she served
as publisher and editor for 12 years. After starting out at the
paper as a $2-per-hour librarian, she and her late husband, Larry
Fanning, bought the News in 1967.
   She served as president of the American Society of Newspaper
Editors from April 1987 to April 1988.
   Supporting the newspaper reportedly has cost the church $20
million a year, while the church seeks to establish a monthly
newsmagazine, radio and television programs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
