<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Germany-MeinKampf     11-15 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Mein Kampf,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hitler's Autobiography Banned At U.S.-Operated Bookstores</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. military officials have
ordered a bookstore chain catering to American soldiers to stop
selling Adolf Hitler's anti-Semitic book ``Mein Kampf,'' an official
said today.
   Hitler's book has been banned at the 158 Stars and Stripes
bookstores in Germany, said Deane McDermott, circulation manager for
the U.S. government organization in Darmstadt.
   ``Mein Kampf'' and other Nazi literature have been banned in
Germany for decades, McDermott said, but Stars and Stripes stores
had been selling about 70 copies a month of the book.
   ``It is against German law even to display the book,'' McDermott
said. ``We're guests in Germany and I think we should show certain
respect to our hosts.''
   McDermott said the subject of Nazism has become increasingly
sensitive in recent days following last week's 50th anniversary of
Kristallnacht and former German parliament speaker Philipp
Jenninger's controversial speech marking the occasion.
   Kristallnacht, meaning Crystal Night, was a night of terror when
Nazi sympathizers burned and looted Jewish businesses and synagogues
in what is considered the beginning of the Holocaust. Under the
Holocaust, 6 million Jews were systematically killed.
   Jenninger was forced to resign as president of the Bundestag, or
parliament, after an awkward and inflammatory explanation of
Hitler's appeal to the German people. Jenninger said many Germans
considered Hitler's march through Europe ``triumphal'' and he
bluntly referred to the widespread anti-Semitism among Germans that
allowed Hitler's repression of Jews.
   Vandalism at Jewish cemeteries by presumed neo-Nazi groups also
has been reported over the past few days in Wiesbaden, Bad Buchau
and Berlin.
   Sales of ``Mein Kampf,'' ``My Struggle'' in English, at Stars and
Stripes stores came to the attention of American military officials
in Berlin last week when a television program, ``Abendschau,''
showed one of its reporters purchasing the book at the store in
Berlin's Truman Plaza.
   The book is filled with anti-Semitic outpourings and describes a
struggle for world domination.
   Heinz Galinski, West Germany's Jewish community leader, was
interviewed during the TV program and expressed dismay that the U.S.
stores were selling Hitler's book.
   McDermott said patrons are supposed to show their military
identification cards when shopping at the stores. He said the German
TV crew had received special permission from Stars and Stripes to
enter the Berlin store.
   ``There has been an awful lot of publicity on the Kristallnacht
anniversary and Philipp Jenninger's speech, and I think this all
came about because of that,'' McDermott said.
   About half of Stars and Stripes' 199 bookstores in Europe had
been selling Hitler's publication since about 1983, McDermott said.
   The order to remove ``Mein Kampf'' from the stores came on Friday
from Gen. Raymond Haddock, the U.S. commander in Berlin.
   On Monday, about 600 copies of the book were removed from the
German-based stores.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1031EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LiverTransplant     11-15 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Liver Transplant,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boy Doing Well After Receiving Liver Slated for Girl</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who agreed to let another mother's
child have a liver transplant ahead of her own daughter because the
boy needed it more says she is confident her daughter will get a
transplant eventually.
   ``Believe you me, I'm not any special person,'' said Penny
Thomas, whose 6-year-old daughter, Candi, was listed in fair
condition today at Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh.
   Five-year-old Jason Point, who received the liver originally
intended for Candi, also was listed in fair condition today at the
hospital.
   ``I'm sure anyone would have to do it. I do have faith and I do
believe that in turn, Candi will get hers in time,'' Mrs. Thomas
said.
   Mrs. Thomas' daughter was lying outside the operating room
waiting for her transplant on Nov. 1, when doctors discovered that
Jason's liver was gangrenous. Doctors predicted that the boy would
live only another day or two without a transplant.
   Mrs. Thomas and Jason's mother, Nancy Point, were in a waiting
room at the hospital renewing a friendship established because both
of their children had already undergone one transplant shortly after
birth, Mrs. Thomas said.
   Doctors had placed the girl under aesthesia to give her a new
liver when the children's surgeon appeared, Mrs. Thomas said. Mrs.
Point was awaiting test results on Jason.
   ``Dr. (Thomas) Starzl came up. He told us that Candi needs the
liver ... but Jason is going to die in 24 to 48 hours because he has
gangrene of the liver,'' Mrs. Thomas recalled.
   ``He said, `What do we do?' and that's when we offered to give
Jason the liver,'' said Mrs. Thomas, adding that the doctors then
sent the girl back to her room.
   ``It was wonderful. Penny didn't hesitate for an instant,''
Jason's mother said.
   ``Circumstances brought us all together at the same time,'' Mrs.
Point said. ``All those circumstances fitting together ... a movie
script couldn't be more bizarre than this.''
   ``At the time my body was numb,'' said Mrs. Thomas. ``There was
just no other way to do it.''
   Jason was born with intrahepatic hypoplasia, which means the
liver was too small for his body and functioned at only 2 percent.
   Candi was also born with a birth defect. Both children had
received their first liver transplants in their first year of life.
</TEXT>
