<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Pakistan 1stLd-Writethru   11-15 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0524,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Watch Over Cities on Election Eve</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with president's remarks, MOVE
up
troop patrols. Pick up 4th graf pvs, `A similar ...' Minor editing
to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops in armored personnel carriers
today patrolled cities on the eve of national elections, and
President Ghulam Ishaq Khan made a national appeal for peace during
the balloting.
   In Rawalpindi, a bomb hidden under wooden carts exploded in a
market, killing one person. Nobody immediately claimed
responsibility for the explosion and authorities refused to
speculate whether it was related to Wednesday's polls.
   Khan went on national television to urge Pakistan's voters to go
to the polls Wednesday and to accept the results peacefully. The
race is expected to be close between left-leaning populist leader
Benazir Bhutto and a nine-party conservative alliance.
   Ishaq Khan said heavy military and police security would be used
to prevent anyone from creating ``an atmosphere of fear or danger.''
The government has said it is deploying hundreds of thousands of
troops.
   ``A healthy tradition of respect for the public verdict through
the polls will, God willing, be established this time,'' Ishaq Khan
said. ``Gratitude and humbleness for the winners and patience and
tolerance for the defeated ones should be the hallmark of behavior
after the polls.''
   An undetermined number of people were injured by the Rawalpindi
bomb, which was planted under some wooden carts in a market, police
said.
   A similar device failed to explode an hour earlier in the same
city, adjacent to the capital, Islamabad. The bomb, concealed in an
empty cannister at a bicycle stand, only gave off sparks, police
said.
   Pakistani officials blame a wave of terrorist bombings over the
past two years on agents of neighboring Afghanistan's communist
government. Pakistan backs Moslem insurgents fighting to oust the
Marxists.
   Election officers have prepared 33,500 polling stations for
Wednesday's vote.
   Leaders of some 30 political parties contesting the National
Assembly polls conferred with their aides after the campaign
officially ended midnight Monday.
   The election promises to be Pakistan's first polls open to
political parties in more than a decade.
   A 25-member international delegation sponsored by the
Washington-based National Democratic Institute for International
Affairs will monitor polling unofficially.
   Troops in armored personnel carriers and sandbagged bunkers
watched over the southern cities of Karachi and Hyderabad, scene of
a bloodbath in September that killed almost 300 people.
   Both Ms. Bhutto's left-leaning Pakistan People's Party and the
center-right Islamic Democratic Alliance predicted a sweep of the
vote. No reliable public opinion polls were published.
   At stake Wednesday are seats in the 217-member National Assembly.
On Saturday, voters elect 483 legislators to the four provincial
assemblies.
   Official statistics indicate there are about 48 million eligible
voters in this Moslem nation of 107 million people. The Federal
Election Commission ordered voters to present state identity cards
at polling stations to prevent fraud.
   The last open elections in Pakistan were held in 1977 under Ms.
Bhutto's father, Prime Minister Zulfikar ali Bhutto.
   However, Gen. Zia seized power in a military coup shortly
afterward and nullified the results, alleging they were rigged. Two
years later, Zia ordered Bhutto hanged, allegedly for complicity in
a murder plot.
   Zia ruled under martial law for eight years before holding
national elections in 1985 on a non-party basis. Opposition parties
boycotted the polls.
   Zia, U.S. Ambassador Arnold Raphel and 28 others were killed in
an Aug. 17 crash of Zia's C-130 transport plane. Officials suspect
sabotage as the cause, but investigations are continuing.
</TEXT>
