<1ST_LINE>u i PM-HamadiTrial     11-15 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hamadi Trial,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Hostage Tells Court Hijacking Still Haunts Her; Trial
Adjourned</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Marypat cq throughout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former U.S. hostage testified
today at the trial of confessed hijacker Mohammed Ali Hamadi that
she still suffers nightmares more than three years after the ordeal.
   ``I have had nightmares and I'm scared of flying on planes,''
said Marypat Weber, a 21-year-old student. Under court guidelines to
protect witnesses, she did not state her hometown in the United
States.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, is charged with murder and air
piracy in the June 1985 hijacking of TWA flight 847 from Athens to
Rome. U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem was killed during the hijacking
and 39 Americans were held hostage for 17 days.
   Hamadi interrupted the trial today, saying ``I am very exhausted.
I feel very dizzy.''
   The session was adjourned for nearly an hour while a doctor
examined him and told the court he was suffering dizzy spells,
headaches and could not concentrate.
   The doctor, who was not identified, gave Hamadi an injection of
glucose for circulation irregularities.
   She also said Hamadi had been eating very little, but was not on
a hunger strike. She said medicine he was taking to counter low
blood pressure may have accentuated his weakened condition.
   Hamadi interrupted testimony by Ms. Weber's father, Dr. Burton
Weber, 48.
   Asked by the judge if he could return to Frankfurt to conclude
his testimony, Weber replied: ``My daughter and I felt that it was
unsafe for us to remain in Germany after the testimony.''
   The trial was adjourned until Monday, but Weber still was
negotiating a return date.
   His daughter, Marypat, who was returning from a Greek vacation
with her parents and sister when the jetliner was seized, told the
court she thought Hamadi directed the hijacking.
   ``I personally felt that Hamadi was more in charge and that he
was the leader,'' she said.
   Hamadi says the hijacking was directed by his accomplice,
fugitive Hassam Ezzeddin.
   Hamadi admits he was one of the hijackers but denies killing
Stethem and testimony by several passsengers that he stole money and
jewelry.
   ``He took three rings and three chains from me,'' Ms. Weber said.
``One wouldn't come off, so he kept trying to rip it off.''
   Asked to comment by the court, Hamadi said: ``This is not
correct. I never stretch my hand for something like this. I never
did anything like this.''
   Describing her fears during the hijacking, Ms. Weber said, ``the
longer it continued, the more I was afraid. I didn't know if I was
going to live or die.''
   Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt airport in January 1987 when
customs officials found liquid explosives in his luggage.
   The United States requested Hamadi's extradition last year, but
the West German government turned it down, fearing for the lives of
the German hostages held in Beirut at the time.
   The hostages since have been released.
</TEXT>
