<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Emperor     11-15 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Emperor,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito Gets First Transfusion In a Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors gave Emperor Hirohito a blood transfusion
today to combat anemia, a palace official said. It was the emperor's
first transfusion in a week after two months of almost daily
transfusions.
   ``The transfusion ... was to combat acute anemia and loss of
vital force,'' Imperial Household Agency spokesman Kenji Maeda said.
``No signs have been found that His Majesty discharged blood since a
week ago.''
   Hirohito, 87, the world's longest-reigning monarch, coughed up
blood on Sept. 19 and has since been bedridden with internal
hemorrhaging from the upper intestinal area where he underwent a
bypass operation in September 1987.
   His received his last transfusion Nov. 8 when his blood pressure
suddenly plummeted and his temperature soared.
   The frail emperor has received 42 pints of blood since the onset
of his crisis. He is being fed intravenously, and news reports say
his weight has fallen to about 77 pounds, down from 110 pounds when
he was healthy.
   ``Except for anemia, the emperor remained in stable condition. It
wouldn't mean, however, His Majesty's condition is improving. He
talks less and falls into sleep more often,'' Maeda told reporters
in a daily briefing.
   The monarchs's temperature dropped to 99.1 degrees following the
transfusion, compared to 99.7 this morning, palace officials said.
His normal temperature is about 95.9.
   Hirohito's blood pressure was 134 over 60, against 138 over 50 in
the morning. A healthy person normally has a reading of around 120
over 80, the palace reported.
   Palace officials have refused comment on reports that Hirohito
has pancreatic cancer.
</TEXT>
