<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ElectionCost     11-15 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Election Cost,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Agrees To Pay $15,000 Cost Of Special Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gainesville's daily newspaper has agreed
to pay the expected $15,000 cost of a special county referendum
because its omission of a legal advertisement made the special vote
necessary.
   The referendum on Nov. 29 will be on establishment of an enhanced
911 emergency telephone system.
   ``We have acknowledged forthrightly that the omission of the
legal advertisement created a problem, an expensive one,'' said
Denise Bannister, publisher of The Times. ``We made a mistake and we
will pay the cost of the special election.''
   Ms. Bannister's statement Monday came after the Hall County
Commission voted to ask The Times to pay for the election.
   The ad announcing a referendum was omitted from the Oct. 11 issue
of the newspaper, making it illegal for the county to place the
question on the Nov. 8 ballot. The newspaper agreed that county
employees were not at fault in the omission of the ad.
   In the referendum, voters will be asked if they want to pay
$160,000 for the enhanced 911 system, which proponents say would
speed up the response to emergency calls and allow faster tracing of
victims who need help.
</TEXT>
