<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Canada-Johnson 1stLd-Writethru   11-15 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Johnson, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0410,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Formal Inquiry Starts on Olympic Scandal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with start of hearing and
justice's comments; PICKS up 5th graf pvs, ``Canadian euphoria...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada today opened a sweeping general inquiry
into the use of illegal drugs in athletics after sprinter Ben Johson
was stripped of his Olympic gold medal for using steroids.
   Ontario Associate Chief Justice Charles Dubin, appointed by the
federal government, said the investigation would examine drug abuse
in all Canadian athletics except professional sports.
   ``This is not an inquiry merely into the conduct of one or more
individuals,'' said Dubin, referring to the issue of whether Johnson
used anabolic steroids, as drug tests showed after his Olympic
victory.
   Johnson maintains that he never knowingly used drugs to enhance
his performances, capped by the world record 9.79 second, 100-meter
race at Seoul, South Korea, on Sept. 24.
   Dubin said the inquiry also would examine if too much pressure
was being placed on Canadian athletes to encourage them to cheat.
   ``Are Canadian athletes being exploited by others ... who would
risk reputation or health?'' he asked.
   Canadian euphoria at Johnson's victory over Carl Lewis of the
United States quickly turned to sadness and disgrace as he was
stripped of the medal.
   ``I would never embarrass my family, my friends, my country and
the kids who love me,'' Johnson said after his return from Seoul.
   Some remained loyal, and T-shirts appeared with the slogan, ``Ben
Didn't Do It.'' They have slipped out of store display windows as
the weeks since the Olympics passed.
   Ironically, the hearings start at a time when Canadians are
enmeshed in an unusually passionate debate on their national
identity as part of the campaign for next Monday's national election.
   At stake is the free trade agreement with the United States
scheduled to take effect Jan. 1.
   Opponents of the pact argue that Canada faces a tremendous threat
to its national identity and could be overwhelmed by the more
populous and wealthier United States.
   They point to a sense of fairness and community as being central
to the concept of Canadian nationality.
   In the other incident this year of total national absorption in
sports, hockey hero Wayne Gretzky abandoned Edmonton, Alberta, to
pursue a more lucrative, flashier career in Los Angeles.
   Susan Butt, a sports psychologist at the University of British
Columbia, said Canadians ``have that tendency'' of placing the
national ego on the line over an athletic event.
   ``Hopefully, we can all educate ourselves to become more
realistic and mature about sports,'' she said in a phone interview,
adding that the hearings on drug abuse are ``a wonderful opportunity
for Canada to lead instead of being burdened with it.''
   Harold Minden, a psychologist from Toronto's York University who
traveled to Seoul with the Canadian Olympic team, said he was
surprised by the tremendous response to Johnson's victory and the
subsequent rush to judge him in public opinion.
   ``They really were a little overwhelmed and ecstatic when he won,
then went down in the basement of emotion when he lost (the
medal),'' Minden said.
   Burt Konzak, an expert in sports psychology at the University of
Toronto, said the hearings should examine the competitive pressures
put on Johnson and the excessive push for Canada to win a gold medal
in a high-profile event.
   ``Why were we so lax in testing our own athletes? It was because
we wanted a winner,'' he said.
   Dubin led a federal inquiry into airline safety several years
ago. He can call witnesses, require testimony, hire expert advisers
and take the hearings anywhere in Canada or out of the country.
   Among the most eagerly awaited witnesses are Johnson; his coach,
Charlie Francis; and Dr. Jamie Astaphan, the physician who treated
the athlete.
   Johnson has been banned from competition for two years by the
International Amateur Athletic Federation, which governs world track
and field.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
