<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Blindman'sBluff     11-15 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Blindman's Bluff,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Calls `Blind Man's' Bluff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who successfully sued the government for
medical malpractice, blaming it for what he said was near total
blindness, has been convicted of fraud and perjury.
   Friends and neighbors testified they had seen Lowell Hedgecorth
mowing his lawn, reading, playing cards and even driving a car.
   Hedgecorth, 54, of St. Ann, was awarded $825,000 in 1984 when he
sued the government, claiming he lost nearly all of his vision when
he suffered a stroke in a stress test administered at the John
Cochran Veterans Adminstration Hospital here.
   The damage award was later overturned after the judge in the case
learned of Hedgecorth's activities. Hedgecorth was indicted on four
counts of conspiracy to commit mail fraud and three counts of
perjury stemming from his testimony in the civil suit. One charge of
mail fraud was later dismissed.
   In closing arguments Monday, Assistant U.S. Attorney James Steitz
noted that Hedgecorth had passed a vision test when renewing his
driver's license.
   Steitz recounted testimony of a radiologist who testified that
Hedgecorth's brain showed no evidence of the kind of stroke it would
take to blind him.
   Thomas Cotter, Hedgecorth's attorney, said his client had simply
adapted to his impairment. He cited the testimony of several blind
and visually impaired witnesses, all of whom said they knew of
legally blind people who occasionally drove cars.
   Hedgecorth faces up to 30 years in prison and $1.5 million in
fines. Sentencing was set for Dec. 23.
</TEXT>
