<1ST_LINE>r w PM-JobInjuries     11-15 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Job Injuries,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rate of Job-Related Injuries and Illnesses Increased By 18 Percent
Last Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rate of job-related injuries and illnesses
increased by 5 percent last year, with 351,000 more injuries and
53,000 more illnesses reported, the government said today.
   The Bureau of Labor Statistics said 83 of every 1,000 workers
experienced some kind of job-related illness or injury last year
compared with 79 of every 1,000 workers in 1985 and 1986.
   Meanwhile, job-related fatalities in surveyed private businesses
with 11 or more employees dropped from 3,610 in 1986 to 3,400 last
year. BLS officials called the decline ``statistically
insignificant.''
   The increase in injury and illness rates was the first since 1984.
   A total of 5,843,100 workers were injured on the job last year
compared with 5,492,000 in 1986, the bureau said.
   Nearly half of the injuries were so severe that employees lost a
full day or more of work and the number of work days lost totaled
48.8 million, compared with 45.4 million work days lost to injuries
in 1986.
   Some 190,000 workers suffered new illnesses for the first time,
most of them involving noise-related hearing losses, skin diseases
and repetitive motion ailments such as carpal tunnel syndrome
prevalent in the meatpacking industry.
   That is a 28 percent increase over the 136,900 new cases of
job-related illnesses reported in 1986.
   The bureau said chronic and long-term latent cases that are often
difficult to recognize or relate to the workplace are included in
the illness statistics ``but are clearly understated.''
   Labor Statistics Commissioner Janet L. Norwood said the increase
in the job injury and illness rates may be due to better
recordkeeping due to new government guidelines and intensive efforts
to improve the statistics.
   The National Academy of Sciences last year questioned validity of
the government's job health and safety data because of ``severe
underreporting'' by employers to avoid workmen's compensation claims
or government inspections.
   An academy panel said the actual number of job-related fatalities
could be as much as triple those reported by the bureau.
   The Occupational Safety and Health Administration has placed a
new emphasis on accurate records, levying hundreds of fines, some of
them in the millions of dollars, against employers for not reporting
job-related injuries or illnesses.
   Of the 3,400 reported on-the-job fatalities last year, two-thirds
occurred in the construction, manufacturing, transportation or
public utility industries. As in previous years, the single biggest
cause was traffic accidents, accounting for about one-third of the
deaths, the government said.
</TEXT>
