<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SouthernAfrica-Talks     11-15 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Southern Africa-Talks,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiators Reportedly Agree on Basis for Peace Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators for Cuba, Angola and South Africa today
agreed on a proposal that could be the basis of a regional peace
package for southern Africa, a South African official said.
   ``All parties have agreed to take a document home to their
governments,'' Pretoria's chief negotiator Neil Van Heerden told
reporters. He said the document would be the basis for a final
agreement ``if the parties accept it.''
   ``This could open the door to Brazzaville,'' he said, referring
to the Congolese capital which is the proposed site for the final
meeting in a U.S.- mediated peace effort.
   There was no immediate, independent confirmation of Van Heerden's
comments.
   Van Heerden met reporters after a plenary meeting led by U.S.
Assistant Secretary of State Chester Crocker on the fifth day of
talks. He said no deadlines had been set for finishing the process.
   The main issue remaining in the peace effort, begun in May, is
setting a timetable for the withdrawal of an estimated 50,000 Cuban
troops backing Angola's Marxist government in their fight against
U.S.- and Pretoria-backed UNITA rebels. Also to be resolved is a
framework for ending South Africa's 73-year control over South-West
Africa, or Namibia.
   A U.S. plan put forth in October reportedly calls for a gradual
two-year withdrawal of Cuban troops. Cuba has sought a 2{-year
timetable.
   The target date for the start of the pullout is said to be Jan.
1, the same day on which a U.N.-supervised process for bringing
independence to South-West Africa would begin.
   South African officials have tried to link the withdrawal of
Cuban troops to independence in South-West Africa.
   South-West Africa, also known as Namibia, lies between South
Africa and Angola.
</TEXT>
