<1ST_LINE>r a PM-UndergroundFire     11-15 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Underground Fire,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Declare War on Stubborn Landfill Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS CAROLA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILTON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pungent smoke from an underground landfill
fire spread for miles today as firefighters spent a fifth day
battling a blaze that is keeping 25 families from their homes.
   ``This morning, when people got up in Saratoga Springs, they
awoke to clouds of steamy, smelly smoke,'' said Paul Lent, Saratoga
County emergency services director.
   A temperature inversion kept cloud cover low overnight, and smoke
from the unlicensed landfill about three miles west of Saratoga
Springs couldn't dissipate, Lent said.
   ``The smell that people complained about doesn't mean that it's
getting worse. It actually means that we're making headway,'' Lent
said.
   Overnight, workers continued their ``wet and smother'' strategy
against the blaze, which started Thursday night.
   Water and air sample results should be available later today,
which would determine if the evacuated residents can go home, Lent
said. While the dump owner has claimed there was nothing toxic in
the landfill, low levels of PCBs were found in the smoke. State
Health Department officials said the level of the chemicals did not
exceed federal safety standards.
   The city of Saratoga Springs kept in effect a health alert for
residents of its west side, and Lent said all residents bothered by
the smoke were being advised to stay indoors.
   Bulldozers and dump trucks dug trenches Monday on two sides of
the smoldering area while acrid smoke poured from about two acres of
the 17-acre landfill.
   One trench, 30 feet wide by 30 feet deep and 400 feet long, was
filled with dirt Monday to form a firebreak similar to those used in
forest fires, Lent said. The other was to be filled in today, he
said.
   It might take days to extinguish the fire, he said.
   Saratoga Hospital reported 35 people, most of them firefighters,
had been treated for respiratory problems from the smoke. No serious
injuries have been reported.
   Lent said the dump contains plastic piping, gypsum board, wood
and other building materials placed there by its owner, John Rock,
who has been charged with operating a dump without a permit.
</TEXT>
