<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MallCrash     11-15 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mall Crash,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Opens in Sunvalley Mall Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Sunvalley is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MARTINEZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of a small plane that crashed
into a shopping mall filled with Christmas shoppers and killed seven
people covered up serious medical problems, a jury was told.
   About 70 people are seeking $35 million in damages in connection
with the Dec. 23, 1985, crash at the Sunvalley Mall in Concord.
Opening arguments began Monday.
   Beech Aircraft, which built the plane in 1962, and General Air
Services, which inspected and maintained it, are defendants in a
civil trial to determine whether they should bear any liability for
the crash.
   Beech Aircraft Corp. lawyer William Owen said the crash was
caused solely by pilot error when James Graham, 67, became
disoriented in heavy fog. Graham and his two passengers were among
those killed. In addition, more than 70 people were injured.
   Owen said Graham lied to doctors who examined him for annual
flight physicals in 1983, 1984 and 1985 by saying in answer to a
questionnaire item that he hadn't seen any doctors during the
previous year.
   Graham also stated in 1985 that he was not using any medication
when he was taking blood-pressure medicine that can cause
drowsiness, Owen said.
   ``There is no way in the world,'' Owen said that Graham could
have passed his 1985 flight physical if he had disclosed his high
blood pressure.
   Owen said Graham had been taking an amphetamine daily, was
receiving injections of testosterone, a steroid, at least twice a
month, suffered from a sleeping disorder called early narcolepsy and
sometimes fell asleep in his car or at his desk.
   Gerald Sterns, an attorney for the plaintiffs, contended that the
plane had a defectively designed left engine that performed
improperly.
</TEXT>
