<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Baltics     11-15 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Baltics,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legal Affairs Chief Chastises Estonian Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party's chief of legal affairs
chastised Estonian leaders for encouraging nationalism and
increasing political tension in their tiny republic, Tass said today.
   Politburo member Viktor M. Chebrikov said the Central Committee
of the Estonian party had ``committed serious miscalculations in the
areas of inter-ethnic relations,'' the official news agency said.
   Chebrikov, whose visit likely was meant as a message to Estonians
to tread cautiously, made the remarks in a speech Monday to Estonian
party, government and economic officials.
   ``It is necessary to seek what unites rather than divides,'' said
Chebrikov, who was head of the KGB until September, when Gorbachev
appointed him to his present post.
   The growth of ethnic tensions in the Baltic republics of Estonia,
Lithuania and Latvia, as well as the southern republics of Armenia
and Azerbaijan have become a severe test of Soviet President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev's program of greater openness and economic reforms.
   Party and government officials in Estonia have joined activists
in demanding greater economic and political autonomy from Moscow.
   Last week, they said in a meeting with Gorbachev in Moscow that
the Soviet leader's intended reform of the political system would
take away many of their republic's rights rather than increase local
control.
   On Monday, Chebrikov assured Estonian leaders that the Kremlin
was pleased more people were getting involved in public issues and
gaining a stronger ethnic identity. But he said ethnic feelings were
going too far.
   Chebrikov told the Estonian officials ``the situation in the
republic is characterized by a growing political tension,'' Tass
said.
   He described as especially alarming the division of the
population along ethnic lines, Tass said.
   Chebrikov went to Estonia on Friday, the same day two other
Politburo members were sent to the Baltic on similar missions. Vadim
Medvedev, the Kremlin ideology chief, went to the republic of Latvia
and Nikolai Slyunkov, chief of social and economic development,
visited the republic of Lithuania.
   Tass reported the Medvedev and Slyunkov visits, but their
speeches to officials were not as sharp as Chebrikov's in Estonia,
where the reform movement has been the most active and organized.
</TEXT>
