<HEAD>Small Fire Put Out In Bathroom Aboard Eastern Jetliner</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS one graf that smoking was allowed on the flight.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ROMULUS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire that broke out in a bathroom aboard
an Eastern Airlines jetliner was quickly extinguished and the plane
landed safely at Detroit Metropolitan Airport, authorities said.
   None of the 73 passengers and five crew members aboard the Monday
night Flight 52 from Miami to Detroit was hurt, said Eastern
spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak.
   A attendant and the first officer put out the fire with a fire
extinguisher before the plane landed, Ceremsak said.
   ``It was no big deal. Someone apparently was smoking in the
bathroom,'' said Cpl. Glen Hudson of the Wayne County Sheriff's
Department's Airport Division. Ceremsak said she couldn't confirm
the cause of the fire.
   Karen Ceremsak, spokeswoman for Easter Airlines in Miami, said
the flight was longer than two hours and therefore smoking was
allowed in the plane's smoking section. Federal law bans smoking on
shorter flights.
