<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Brazil-Elections 1stLd-Writethru a0485 11-15 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brazil-Elections, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0485,0629</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with polls opening, other
details. PICKS up 5th graf pvs, ``Although the ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE HANDLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of Brazilians voted today
for mayors and city councilors in nationwide elections considered a
popularity test of President Jose Sarney's beleaguered government.
   Some campaign workers were arrested for violating a law that
prohibits campaigning within 100 yards of polling stations. They
tried to hand out sample ballots with their candidate's name written
in.
   However, no serious incidents were reported by early afternoon.
   People waitied patiently in lines up to four blocks long after
polls opened at 8 a.m. (5 a.m. EST). They were to close at 5 p.m. (2
p.m. EST).
   President Jose Sarney voted in his home state of Maranhao, in far
northern Brazil, then returned to Brasilia.
   Election results, not expected in full before Sunday, could
indicate how Brazilians will vote next November in the first
presidental elections in 29 years in Latin America's biggest and
most populous country.
   Voting is mandatory, and Brazilians who don't vote face trouble
getting a passport and obtaining a government loan or a civil
service job. But polls show voter apathy is high. Campaigns urging
voters to protest through voided ballots or to vote for nonsense
candidates _ such as a popular chimpanzee in Rio Zoo _ have
attracted national attention.
   At stake are mayorships and council seats in 4,307 cities and
towns.
   Campaigning by candidates from 29 parties has been unrestricted
in Brazil, which in 1985 returned to civilian government after 21
years of right-wing military rule. Parties ranged from Communist
groups to supporters of the former military government.
   Although the voting is based largely on local matters, political
analysts say Brazilians will also be voicing their opinion on
Sarney's conservative-to-centrist Brazilian Democratic Movement
Party.
   Polls indicate that the party _ which in 1986 swept elections for
state governors, state assemblies and Congress _ will be lucky to
win the mayoral seats in three of Brazil's largest cities.
   The governing party has been blamed for the soaring inflation and
a 40 percent dip in workers' buying power. It has also faced charges
of corruption and nepotism.
   Last week, soldiers killed three workers at the state-run
National Steel Co. in a clash with strikers. Protest signs at the
workers' funerals said, ``Enough of Sarney.''
   Federal troops have been assigned to 207 cities in 13 states to
maintian order during voting.
   Sarney, a 58-year-old politician and poet, gained office as the
running mate of Tancredo Neves, who was chosen in a
military-controlled electoral college vote. Neves died shortly
before taking office.
   The leading mayoral candidates according to Brazilian polls were:
   _Sao Paulo, the country's largest and richest city: Paulo Salim
Maluf, 57, wealthy industrialist and the defeated military-backed
candidate for president in 1985. An appointed state governor and
mayor under the military regime, Maluf belongs to the former
regime's official Social Democratic Party.
   _Rio de Janeiro, the second-largest city: Marcello Alencar, 63, a
lawyer, journalist and former appointed mayor of Rio. He is from the
leftist Democratic Workers Party and an ally of Leonel Brizola, the
leading left-wing candidate for president in 1989.
   _Belo Horizonte, the No. 3 city: Joao Pimenta da Veiga Filho, 41,
of the left-of-center Brazilian Social Democracy Party, a rebel
breakaway group from Sarney's Democratic Movement.
   _Porto Alegre, largest city in Brazil's south: Olivio Dutra, 47,
militant bank workers union leader, federal congressman and member
of the far-leftist Workers' Party.
   _Fortaleza, largest city in Brazil's poor north: Ciro Gomes, 31,
a lawyer and constitutional law professor, from the Democratic
Movement.
</TEXT>
