<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland     11-15 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Trade Unions Chief Challenges Walesa to TV Debate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa today
accepted a challenge from the head of Poland's official trade union
alliance for a nationally televised debate on trade unions in Poland.
   Alfred Miodowicz, Politburo member and chairman of the OPZZ, the
All-Poland Alliance of Trade Unions, made the challenge in an
interview in today's edition of the Communist Party newspaper
Trybuna Ludu.
   Publication of Miodowicz's offer in the official press appeared
to indicate the proposal already had official approval.
   ``All members of the government will be glad to sit in front of
their TV sets and listen to such a discussion,'' government press
spokesman Jerzy Urban said at his weekly news conference.
   The debate would be Walesa's first appearance on state television
since 1983, when he challenged then-Deputy Prime Minister Mieczyslaw
F. Rakowski after Rakowski gave a televised speech at the Lenin
Shipyard in Gdansk. Rakowski became prime minister in September.
   Walesa accepted the invitation to debate in a statement today. No
date was announced.
   Poland's official trade unions were set up by the government in
1982 after the banning of Solidarity, the East bloc's first
independent union. Solidarity supporters say more than one union
should be allowed to exist in each workplace because official unions
are too tame and do not adequately represent workers' interests.
   Also today, Walesa addressed a rally of 3,000 workers in Gdansk
and told them he will support management plans to restructure and
save the Lenin Shipyard, Solidarity's birthplace. The government has
announced plans to liquidate the shipyard beginning Dec. 1.
</TEXT>
