<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EcclesiaDeath     11-15 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ecclesia Death,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Defendants in Ecclesia Child's Death Released Without Bail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has released two defendants and
reduced bail for the other two held in the beating death of the
daughter of Ecclesia Athletic Association founder Eldridge J.
Broussard Jr.
   The four face a joint manslaughter trial Dec. 12 in the Oct. 14
death of 8-year-old Dayna Lorea Broussard. She was among more than
50 children living at the association's religious-athletic camp near
Sandy.
   The four adults were supervising the children at the time.
   Her father, who was not charged, was then in Los Angeles, where
the group was founded. Broussard had said that his goal was to train
inner-city youth from the Watts area of Los Angeles to compete in
future Olympic Games.
   Neighbors in Oregon complained when the group moved there that
they saw children exercising for long periods of time and in
extremely hot weather.
   After the girl's death, the 53 remaining children, ages 1{ months
to 16 years, were taken into custody by Children's Services Division
officials.
   On Monday, Clackamas County Circuit Judge John Lowe granted
defense motions for the release of Willie K. Chambers, 35, and
Constance Z. Jackson, 37. Lowe ordered them to remain in Oregon
until the trial, to contact their attorneys in person weekly and not
to be in charge of children under 18.
   Lowe reduced bail to $25,000 from $250,000 for Brian J. Brinson,
30, and Frederick P. Doolittle, 28.
   Ron Thom, a court-appointed attorney representing Brinson, told
Lowe that it was unlikely the defendants could post the reduced bail.
   In releasing Chambers and Jackson, Lowe said ``it appears that
they have substantial family relationships and ties to the
community,'' and said the lack of ties prompted him to only reduce
bail for Brinson and Doolittle.
</TEXT>
