<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NuclearWasteMeeting     11-15 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Waste Meeting,290</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department said today it had
canceled a meeting scheduled Wednesday of Deputy Secretary Joseph
Salgado and three western governors on low-level nuclear waste
issues because one governor could not be there.
   Doug Elmets, spokesman for Energy Secretary John S. Herrington,
said the department intends to send lower level officials to meet
with Colorado Gov. Roy Romer, who insisted on such a meeting.
   The governors of Colorado, Idaho and New Mexico had been
scheduled to meet Wednesday with Salgado in Salt Lake City.
   But Gov. Garrey Carruthers of New Mexico has to be in Washington
Wednesday to meet with members of President-elect George Bush's
transition team.
   Elmets said the department will try to reschedule the meeting
`hopefully, soon.''
   Herrington sought the meeting after Idaho Gov. Cecil Andrus
refused to permit a boxcar of low-level waste such as contaminated
clothes and tools to unload at the department's Idaho National
Engineering Laboratory on Oct. 19.
   The waste originated from the department's weapons plant at Rocky
Flats, Colo. Romer allowed the car to come back to Rocky Flats,
where several carloads have accumulated.
   The waste has been stored at the Idaho installation for years,
pending opening of an underground storage repository in New Mexico.
   That opening has been delayed because Congress did not approve
legislation transferring the land from the Interior Department to
the Energy Department.
   Romer and Andrus complained about cancellation of the scheduled
meeting with Salgado, with Andrus calling it ``the latest instance
in a long line of indecision and delay'' by the Energy Department.
   ``As I suspected almost a month ago, DOE in Washington doesn't
have the slightest idea of what they are going to do to solve this
problem,'' Andrus said.
</TEXT>
