<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Prostitutes     11-15 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Prostitutes,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prostitutes Stage Protest March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOMBAY, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of prostitutes marched out of the
city's biggest red light district Tuesday night, demanding free
health care, education for their children and an end to police
harassment.
   The women, including aging brothel keepers who grew up in the
profession and supervise younger prostitutes, marched for four miles
through the streets of Bombay. A small delegation also met state
officials.
   About 800 women started the march, participants said, but by the
time they reached their rally site in south Bombay four hours later,
the number had dwindled to about 400.
   One marcher, Rukmanibai Bansode, 58, complained that some
prostitutes were starving. She said schools refused to admit their
children, and money lenders charged interest rates as high as 50
percent.
   The marchers were escorted by men from the Dalit Panthers, a
group formed in the 1970s to fight for the rights of the downtrodden.
   Other demands included protection from thugs and an end to
exploitation by money lenders.
   After a meeting with Maharashtra state Chief Minister Sharad
Pawar, the delegation announced to a cheering crowd that all their
demands had been granted. The government had no immediate comment.
   Bombay, a port city of 8 million people, has an estimated 100,000
prostitutes. About half live in central's Bombay's Kamathipura area.
   They do business openly, charging as little as $1.35, but
business has slacked off in recent months after one prostitute died
of AIDS.
   Minoo Irani, an assistant police commissioner, said a woman
engaging in prostitution does not violate a 1986 law that defined
prostitution as ``sexual exploitation for commercial gain.'' He said
it was illegal to solicit customers.
   ``We normally do not raid red light areas unless citizens
complain that minors are being detained,'' he said.
</TEXT>
