<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Relics     11-15 0128</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Relics,0131</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Confiscate Collection of 45,000 Relics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have confiscated a private collection of
more than 45,000 prehistoric relics, fossils and artworks, officials
said Tuesday.
   The collection was found on the property of Piero Ceruleo, an
engineer from Tivoli, who told investigators that he had collected
the works in Italy and abroad in the past 20 years, according to
Italy's internal revenue and customs police.
   He was under investigation for suspicion of violating a law
requiring the registration of such relics. The law is aimed at
preventing their sale abroad.
   The relics, some of which date to the 5th century B.C., are being
studied by government archaeologists. They include various fossils,
prehistoric teeth, bones and arrowheads, and Etruscan and Roman
coins and sculpture.
</TEXT>
