<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan-Glance     11-15 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Glance,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pakistan Election at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pakistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Facts and figures about Wednesday's election in Pakistan:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE CONTEST _ Candidates are running for seats in the 237-member
National Assembly. Voters will choose 207 Moslem members and
non-Moslems will elect 10 members. Twenty seats reserved for women
will be filled later by vote of the assembly. President Ghulam Ishaq
Khan will choose an assembly member, probably the leader of the
strongest party, to be prime minister and form a government.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ELECTORATE _ About 48 million of Pakistan's 107 million people
are eligible to vote. Only those carrying identity cards issued by
the government will be allowed to cast ballots.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   VOTING _ About 33,500 voting stations will be open from 8 a.m. to
5 p.m. (6 p.m. EST Wednesday to 4 a.m. EST Thursday).
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PROMINENT CANDIDATES _ Benazir Bhutto, 35, leader of the populist
Pakistan People's Party founded by her father, former prime minister
Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, who was ousted in a 1977 coup and executed two
years later.
   Nawaz Sharif, 40, a protege of the late Mohammed Zia ul-Haq and
acting chief minister of Punjab, the most populous province. He has
become a leader of the conservative Pakistan Moslem League, the main
group in a nine-party alliance challenging Ms. Bhutto.
   Mohammad Khan Junejo, 56, who was prime minister for three years
until Zia fired him in May and dissolved the National Assembly. He
once was undisputed leader of the Moslem League.
   Ghulam Mustafa Jatoi, 57, who formed the National People's Party
in 1986. He could emerge as a power broker if neither Ms. Bhutto nor
the conservative alliance wins decisively.
</TEXT>
