<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Arms     11-15 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Arms,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Shows Off Arms For Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China opened an international exhibit of its
arsenal Tuesday complete with scale models and videos of the weapons
in action.
   The China Precision Machinery Import and Export Corp., one of the
country's largest arms manufacturers, said it was putting six new
missiles on the market during the four-day Asian Defense Technology
Exposition, or Asiandex 88.
   They included several medium-range coastal defense missiles
intended to replace the Silkworm, which Vice President Shen Rengui
said used outdated technology and was being phased out.
   The Silkworm became China's most famous missile when Iran used
one in October 1987 to attack a Kuwaiti oil tanker flying the
American flag. China denied selling Silkworms to Iran and said it
did not know where Iran bought them.
   But Western experts said the new missiles and other weapons shown
at Asiandex already were being promoted to potential buyers, and
that the show contained no surprises.
   The exhibit demonstrated China's determination to increase its
arms sales despite criticism from the United States and other
Western countries that Chinese sales to primarily Third World
countries are destabilizing.
   China does not release figures on its arms sales, but the U.S.
government estimates China sold sold about $2 billion in weapons
abroad in 1987. It is the fourth-largest weapons seller to the Third
World after the Soviet Union, United States and France.
   China began taking part in international arms shows in 1984, and
held the first show of its own, Asiandex 86, two years ago.
   Nearly 100 foreign companies also had booths at the exhibition,
including the U.S. companies Boeing and Lockheed, Britain's Marconi
Group, Hungary's Technika Foreign Trading Co. and Chile's Cardoen.
Arms manufacturers from France, West Germany, Italy, the Netherlands
and other countries also were represented.
   One Western manufacturer said his company attended not in hopes
of making an immediate sale to China, but simply to keep up contacts
with the Chinese military. ``We've talked with them and they sent a
team to tour our plant at one point but _ nothing,'' he said.
   A Western source noted China has been uninterested in importing
large quantities of weapons.
   ``What they want is joint ventures, so they can learn the
technology and reverse-engineer and make it themselves,'' he said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Many of China's current weapons were derived in this way from
1950s Soviet models. In recent years China has entered into
agreements with Western companies to use their advanced technology
to upgrade its obsolete arsenal.
   Aeritalia of Italy supplied avionics technology for China's new
A5-M fighter plane, which recently had a successful test flight.
U.S. and British companies also have cooperated in updating Chinese
tanks and planes.
   China's strategy has been to use arms exports to subsidize
improvements in its domestic arsenal that it could not otherwise
afford. Its biggest market has been the Middle East, where it has
sold to both Iran and Iraq during their 8-year-old border war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1252EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Thatcher 1stLd-Writethru a0466 11-15 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thatcher, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0466,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Prime Minster To Bid Farewell To Reagan, Hello To Bush</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Thatcher departing; PICKS
up
3rd graf pvs, `Let us ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Margaret Thatcher, with at least four more years
ahead of her as prime minister, flew to Washington today to bid
goodbye to President Reagan and welcome President-elect George Bush
to the ranks of Western leaders.
   The prime minister left Heathrow Airport under tight security at
4 p.m. (11 a.m. EST), bound for Andrews Air Force Base near
Washington.
   Thatcher, who has marched in ideological step with Reagan since
he took office eight years ago, thanked him in a speech Monday for
what she said has been his main contribution to the West:
   ``Let us above all thank President Reagan for ending the West's
retreat from world responsibility, for restoring the pride and
leadership of the U.S., and for giving the West back its confidence
_ confidence not only in the success of free enterprise but also in
the values which guide our societies.'' Speaking at the annual Lord
Mayor's banquet in the City, London's financial area, she added:
``He has left America stronger, prouder, greater than ever before
and we thank him for it.''
   In the speech, Mrs. Thatcher also announced that Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev would visit Britain Dec. 12-14. Around Dec. 7,
Gorbachev is to visit the United Nations as well as meet with Reagan
for a fifth time and possibly see Bush, U.S. officials say.
   Mrs. Thatcher also welcomed Bush as ``a worthy successor'' to
Reagan. ``We know him as a friend, we admire him as a man of
unrivaled experience and we respect him because he stands for all
that is best in America,'' she said.
   Reagan said Monday that Mrs. Thatcher was the best statesman he
had met. Asked by a group of schoolchildren at the White House if he
thought the United States would ever have a woman president, he
said: ``I am certainly not against (a female president)...
   ``As a matter of fact, the statesman in the world that I have
met, that I respect the most, is the prime minister of England,
Margaret Thatcher, and she has done a remarkable job for England.''
   Reagan came to office 1{ years after Mrs. Thatcher, and together
they have reinvigorated the long-standing special relationship
between the two countries.
   But while Reagan must step down, Mrs. Thatcher, 63, who is now
the West's longest serving leader, faces no such constraints.
   Her present tenure lasts another four years, and she has said she
will seek a fourth term in the 1990s. If the Conservative Party
leader wins that means she will be working with Bush right up to
1992.
   Reagan and Mrs. Thatcher have shared a deep anti-Communist
ideology, distaste for welfarism, faith in free markets and belief
in negotiating from strength.
   They have helped each other at critical movements, sometimes at
great political risk _ Reagan by approving arms supplies and
intelligence to Britain in the 1982 Falklands War against Argentina,
and Mrs. Thatcher by letting Reagan use U.S. bombers based in
Britain to bomb Libya in 1986.
   Mrs. Thatcher played a role in the Reagan-Gorbachev thaw. She was
the first major Western leader to visit Gorbachev after he came to
power in 1985. And on his way to Washington to sign the
arms-reduction treaty in 1987, Gorbachev stopped in Britain for
talks with the prime minister.
   Mrs. Thatcher arrives in Washington tonight, and will have talks
with Reagan on Wednesday, followed by a state dinner. On Thursday,
she will have talks with Bush, returning home early Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
