<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     11-15 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Culture Minister Calls For Review of Dissident Policy, Past</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Slovak culture minister on
Tuesday called on leaders to correct mistakes that have pushed
people away from the Communist Party and into the embrace of
independent groups and churches.
   Miroslav Valek's unusually critical analysis of Czechoslovakia's
political situation was published by the Communist Party daily
newspaper Rude Pravo.
   He said the country's leaders must right mistakes made since the
1968 ``Prague Spring'' reforms were crushed.
   ``We must analyze the past period properly and expose errors and
mistakes not only in the economy but also in politics,'' he wrote.
   ``On the one hand, there were anti-socialist and ... unrealistic
tendencies. On the other hand, there were rational political and
economic pressures, the need for reform, and those should have been
seen and differentiated.''
   Moscow installed the conservative Czechoslovak leadership after
the Aug. 21-22, 1968, invasion that crushed the reforms of Alexander
Dubcek. While embracing some economic reforms, it has been reluctant
to follow Moscow's example in initiating wide-ranging political
reforms.
   The Slovak official said the purge of 500,000 people from the
Communist Party was perceived, especially by the young, ``as an
all-embracing condemnation of opposition, as a political trauma.''
   This ``trauma ... hasn't passed yet and is not going to pass all
by itself.''
   An analysis of the past was imperative, he said, to regain
people's confidence.
   ``It is necessary to analyze continuously the cause of the birth
and development of Charter 77'' human rights group, young people's
apathy toward the official Communist Youth Union and increasing
interest in religion, the minister said.
   ``All these are facts to which realistic policy can neither
surrender nor close its eyes naively,'' Valek wrote.
   The leadership's apparent unwillingness to re-evaluate the spirit
of 1968 was highlighted by the police quelling of an Aug. 21
demonstration to mark the 20th anniversary of the invasion and
official articles condemning Dubcek and his reforms.
   Last week, up to 25 activists were taken into preventive custody
in Prague to stop a symposium to examine Czechoslovakia's role in
history.
   On Tuesday, the United States strongly denounced Czechoslovak
authorities for thwarting the symposium and served notice it will
irrevocably block consensus on any Helsinki follow-up meeting in
Prague.
   In a statement to the Vienna meeting of the 35-nation Helsinki
review conference on human rights, U.S. Ambassador Warren Zimmermann
said, ``The contempt they (Prague authorities) displayed for the
rights of Czechoslovak citizens amounts to contempt for the Vienna
meeting and the ... process in which Czechoslovakia pledged to
respect those rights.''
   He said Czechoslovkia's poor human rights record disqualified it
from hosting a follow-up meeting. ``A prospective host should have a
credible record on the subject to be discussed,'' he said.
   The Dutch Foreign Ministry called in Czechoslovak Ambassador
Frantisek Chlad to condemn the crackdown as a ``violation of the
fundamental principles of human rights,'' a ministry spokesman said
Tuesday.
   ``The government also stated that it deplores the attitude of the
police against foreign guests,'' said the spokesman, referring to
reports that one of a dozen Western participants in the symposium,
former Dutch Foreign Minister Max van der Stoel, was manhandled by
Czechoslovak police Friday.
</TEXT>
