<1ST_LINE>u a PM-HospitalKidnapping 2ndLd-Writethru a0550 11-15 0847</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hospital Kidnapping, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0550,0869</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Reunited With Abducted Newborn; Forgives Woman Charged</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with baby arriving home,
preliminary hearing date set, other detail. Picks up 13th graf pvs,
`I wouldn't...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FREEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mother reunited with her premature
baby says she forgives the woman who allegedly posed as a nurse and
took the 3-day-old boy from her arms at a hospital two weeks ago.
   ``If she took the baby because of a loss in her own life, I hope
that she will have the opportunity to get some help,'' 32-year-old
Annette Thomas-Jones said Monday, minutes after police returned her
son.
   ``I forgive her.''
   Mrs. Thomas-Jones and her husband, Willie Jones, 39, showed off
the child, Christopher Michael Jones, at a news conference at
Doctors Hospital, where the baby was kidnapped Nov 1. Today, they
took the child home.
   Police retrieved the infant Monday and arrested Acqunetta Rushon
Smith, 32, at Ms. Smith's Hot Springs home, 50 miles away, following
a tip to a hot line. The child was well cared for, authorities said.
   Ms. Smith, an unemployed nurse's aide with four children, was
charged with kidnapping. She pleaded innocent at arraignment today
in Little Rock Municipal Court, and a preliminary hearing was set
for next Tuesday.
   As she left the hospital today, Mrs. Thomas-Jones said that when
she got home with her baby, the youngster would be put to bed for a
nap first.
   ``Then his sisters will probably say, `Mamma, we're hungry,' so
we'll get something for them,'' she said. ``We'll just start our
lives with baby Christopher.'' The couple have two older daughters.
   As the family arrived at the house, a man brought a plant that
included blue ribbons and a foil balloon on a stick. On the balloon
was the word, ``Congratulations.''
   The infant was wearing a tiny white T-shirt reading ``Welcome
Home'' at the news conference Monday. He appeared no worse for the
ordeal.
   ``The baby obviously was well taken care of,'' said Terry
Jefferson, a pediatrician. He said Christopher weighed 5 pounds, 6
ounces Monday, up from 4 pounds when he was kidnapped.
   ``She took very good care of the baby,'' said Mrs. Thomas-Jones.
   Mrs. Thomas-Jones said the prosecution of the kidnapper would not
make the family feel any better, but that they would cooperate with
authorities.
   ``I wouldn't feel better, because I have Christopher,'' said Mrs.
Thomas-Jones, a secretary at the state teachers' union headquarters.
``She (Ms. Smith) needs help. ... (She should) just ask the Lord to
forgive her for what she's done.''
   The tip that led police and FBI agents to Ms. Jones came from ``a
concerned citizen'' who said the baby might be at the woman's home,
said Little Rock Detective Ronnie Smith.
   Detectives continued to question Ms. Smith late Monday but
released no details on a motive.
   A positive identification of the infant was made through a
footprint, said FBI agent Ron Wolfe.
   Applause broke out from a crowd of about two dozen neighbors and
reporters when Mrs. Thomas-Jones and her husband, a real estate
agent, emerged from their house on their way to the hospital to be
reunited with the infant Monday afternoon.
   ``Praise the Lord, praise the Lord, hallelujah!'' Mrs.
Thomas-Jones shouted.
   ``I just want to thank the media,'' she said, tears filling her
eyes and her voice breaking.
   Local broadcasts and newspapers carried repeated appeals by Mrs.
Thomas-Jones, her minister and others for information leading to the
baby's return. The reports noted that Christopher needed continued
medical attention because he was six weeks premature at birth Oct.
29.
   Three days after his birth, Mrs. Thomas-Jones handed the baby
over to a woman posing as a nurse who said she needed to weigh the
boy, authorities said.
   A couple who lives across the street from Ms. Smith, Andrew
Tucker and his wife, said their daughter, Barbara Ann Tucker, knew
Ms. Smith in high school and held the baby last week.
   They said Ms. Smith told their daughter she had the baby and was
released from the hospital the same day. Tucker said he didn't
believe the story because she didn't look like she had lost weight.
   Another neighbor, Stella Kidd, said Ms. Smith looked pregnant in
May, when she moved to the area. But she said she never saw a baby.
   On Monday, a banner at Doctors Hospital read ``Welcome Home,
Christopher'' in baby blue letters, and small baby blue ribbons were
handed out to employees and visitors.
   Mrs. Thomas-Jones said her son ``looks like $250 million wrapped
up _ not just a million, but $250 million. He looks fantastic. He
looks like his daddy.''
   When she first was reunited with Christopher, she said, ``I held
him and I looked at him and I checked his fingers out and his toes
out and his legs and his stomach and his head and everything's there.
   ``I feel relieved, joyful, thankful,'' she said. ``I knew the
Lord was going to bring Christopher home for us.''
</TEXT>
