<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru   11-15 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0489,0604</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Say Several Thousand Soviets Help Gov't Forces Retake Border
Post</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Soviet denial of chemical
weapons use, Afghan radio claims, U.N. developments. Pick up 3rd
pvs, `Western diplomats.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firing chemical shells that caused
victims to vomit blood, Soviet and Afghan government soldiers
recaptured a key border post and road link with Pakistan from
anti-communist guerrillas, insurgents said.
   Mohammad Shuaib of the Jamiat-e-Islami rebel group said thousands
of government and Soviet troops were involved and that hundreds of
guerrillas died in the battle before it ended Sunday.
   In Moscow, Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov
denied the charge of chemical weapons use, saying neither Soviet nor
Afghan government forces have such weapons in Afghanistan.
   In a state radio broadcast, the Soviet-backed government in Kabul
said security forces had retaken the Torkham post on the
Afghanistan-Pakistan border.
   The broadcast, monitored in Islamabad, said 140 guerrillas were
killed and 150 injured at Torkham Monday. Large quantities of
weapons and ammunition were also captured, it said. It gave no other
details.
   In another development, Afghanistan today requested an emergency
meeting of the U.N. Security Council to stop Pakistan's arming of
anti-government rebels and warned it may be forced to use military
force in self-defense. The request was made in a letter from Abdul
Wakil, Afghanistan's foreign minister.
   Western diplomats on Monday confirmed the presence of Soviet
soldiers in the battle for the Torkham post and the highway linking
Jalalabad in eastern Afghanistan to Pakistan.
   Diplomats said Soviet soldiers were flown in to join the
offensive, presumably from Kabul, the Afghan capital about 70 miles
to the west. They and most guerrilla informants spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   Insurgents who reached Peshawar, about 30 miles inside Pakistan,
claimed Soviet and Afghan forces used chemical weapons. They said
explosive shells fired by artillery contained a chemical that caused
victims to blister and vomit blood.
   Moslem rebels began fighting after a Communist coup in April 1978
and the Soviet Union sent military forces into Afghanistan in
December 1979. In April, the Soviets accepted a U.N.-mediated
agreement to withdraw their about 100,000 troops.
   About half the force has gone home, but the Soviets said last
week they were suspending the withdrawal and sending new weapons
into Afghanistan because of continuing guerrilla attacks. They
added, however, that they still intend to complete the pullout as
scheduled on Feb. 15.
   The U.S.-backed guerrillas captured Torkham Nov. 2 and had
claimed they were closing in on Jalalabad.
   Both diplomats and rebels said Soviet commandos supported by
helicopter gunships moved out of Jalalabad on foot, moving along the
road to Torkham, according to insurgent sources.
   The official Afghan radio said high military officials visited
the post Monday.
   Insurgents and diplomats said the guerrillas retreated into
Pakistan, where about 3 million Afghan refugees live.
   Earlier this month, the government displayed SS-1 Scud missiles
in Kabul. Advanced MiG-27 ground-attack jets and sophisticated
helicopter gunships have been reported in action against the
guerrillas.
   Arrival of the new weapons prompted a guerrilla offensive along
the strategic Salang highway that links Kabul with the Soviet border
to the north.
   Ahmad Shah Masoud, Jamiat-e-Islami's commander in the Panjshir
Valley, claims to have closed the highway but Shuaib of the Jamiat
said reports from units along the road were sporadic and there was
no recent confirmation that it remained closed.
   The Salang highway is the only overland route to the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
