<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Film     11-15 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Film,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Bans Controversial Film in Greek Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court Tuesday banned ``The Last
Temptation of Christ'' from movie theaters in the capital where
Nikos Kazantzakis, who wrote the book on which the film is based,
lived for more than 20 years.
   The ban came after eight Orthodox Christian organizations claimed
the movie insulted religious feeling and defamed the head of the
church, said a court spokesman.
   The court's injuction orders theaters and the film's distributor,
United International Pictures, to suspend screenings or face a fine
of nearly $700 for each violation, the spokesman said.
   Last week, a court in the northern city of Salonica banned the
film before its first showing.
   Both injuctions will be appealed in higher court. The Salonica
appeal hearing is set for Nov. 24. No date was set for the Athens
hearing.
   ``We were surprised by the decision. Of course we will fight
these kinds of decisions,'' said Nick Kalogerakis, a spokesman for
the distributor.
   The Martin Scorsese film, which opened in Athens on Oct. 23, is
being shown at four movie theaters in the capital area.
   At its first screening, hundreds of Greek Orthodox priests and
faithful slashed movie screens and clashed with riot police.
   ``The Last Temptation of Christ,'' which has been called
``horrifyingly vulgar'' by the Orthodox Church of Greece, also has
been denounced by other church groups in Europe and the United
States.
   Kazantzakis, who died in 1957, was threatened with
excommunication by the Orthodox Church when the book was published
in 1954.
   Kazantzakis studied law at Athens university from 1902 to 1906.
He lived in the Greek capital for more than 20 years and served in
Athens as a minister without portfolio shortly after World War II.
His first work was published in Athens in 1906.
</TEXT>
