<HEAD>Conductors Shut Down New York Suburban Rail Line</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf to add that trains expected to resume running
at
midafternoon; SUBS last graf to delete incorrect reference to
earlier strike being a `wildcat' strike.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA ROSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conductors struck the Metro-North Commuter
Railroad this morning in a dispute over pensions, stranding 95,000
suburbanites, but a federal judge ordered the strikers back to work
and the union said it would comply.
   It was the second surprise strike in as many months at the
nation's second-largest commuter railroad, which serves the city's
northern suburbs extending into Connecticut.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Sweet signed a temporary restraining
order at 10:15 a.m. and ordered the United Transportation Union to
post a bond of $30,000. The railroad is seeking $1 million in
damages from the union.
   ``I will not defy it. I'm a law-abiding citizen,'' said James
Phelan, the union chief. The UTU represents 770 Metro-North
conductors.
   After the strike broke out, all trains were canceled and the
entire railroad was shut down as other unions honored the picket
lines set up by the conductors. The dispute also disrupted some
Amtrak service.
   Metro-North President Peter Stangl, who had called the strike
``outrageous and illegal,'' said that the trains should begin
running again at midafteroon. ``We'll have an evening rush (hour),''
he said.
   Phelan said the union struck because of a dispute about the
calculation of pension contributions and the timing of deposits.
``On such a sensitive issue as pension, strict compliance is
essential,'' he said.
   But the railroad insisted it was in compliance.
   At normally bustling Grand Central Terminal, no trains were
arriving, ticket counters were closed and people hoping to leave New
York City stood staring at the cancellation notices on the schedule
board.
   ``I've come all the way from Long Island,'' said Grace Giusto,
who was supposed to attend a 9 a.m. business meeting in north
suburban White Plains. ``I'm really stranded.''
   On the morning of Sept. 9, 780 Metro-North track workers from the
Teamsters union staged a surprise strike, but the railroad obtained
a court order within hours that ended the walkout. That strike was
prompted by the suspension of 37 employees for refusing to work
overtime, union officials said.
</TEXT>
