<HEAD>Gorbachev Expected To Meet The Queen</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev Visit, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Queen Elizabeth II expects to meet with Soviet
President Mikhail Gorbachev during his visit to Britain next month,
Buckingham Palace said Tuesday.
   No details of the meeting have been confirmed, a palace
spokeswoman said, but she noted the queen's meetings with world
leaders ``often take the form of a lunch.''
   The spokeswoman, speaking anonymously in keeping with British
custom, said there were no plans for a visit by the queen to Moscow.
If an invitation came, the queen would act on the advice of
government officials, who must approve all foreign travel by the
monarch, she said.
   No British sovereign has visited the Soviet Union since World War
I, when members of the Russian royal family, who were related to the
British monarchy, were killed by Bolshevik revolutionaries in 1918.
   Gorbachev and his wife, Raisa, also will meet with Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher.
   British news reports said Gorbachev would arrive in Britain on
Dec. 12 and meet with Mrs. Thatcher on Dec. 13 at Chequers, her
official country residence, before leaving early Dec. 14.
