<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SpaceShuttle     11-15 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Shuttle,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shuttle Managers Meet To Set Atlantis Launch Date</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Space shuttle managers began a
two-day flight readiness review Tuesday to set a date for launching
Atlantis on a classified military mission with a crew of five
astronauts.
   The shuttle's processing director, Conrad Nagel, said Monday the
launch target was Nov. 30, but that Dec. 1 was a more likely date
because of a few outstanding technical problems.
   Rear Adm. Richard Truly, who directs NASA's shuttle program, is
expected to announce a launch date Wednesday afternoon after the
managers review the status of the orbiter, the payload, the global
tracking network and other elements needed to support the mission.
   Most details about the flight are not being made public because
Atlantis will be carrying a secret Defense Department payload which
sources say is a sophisticated intelligence-gathering satellite.
   The launch will be the second for the shuttle since the
Challenger explosion in January 1986 that killed its crew of seven.
Flights resumed last Sept. 29 with the successful launch of
Discovery and a five-man crew on a four-day orbital trip.
</TEXT>
