<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1332EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CartoonSuit     11-15 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cartoon Suit,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Osteopath Who Drew Sex Cartoon on Patient Sued for $125,000</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An osteopath faces a $125,000 lawsuit for
drawing a cartoon depiction of oral sex on a patient's chest,
despite his protest that it was just a joke between friends.
   Wayne Scherr, 35, of Spanaway, accused osteopath Scott Havsy of
Puyallup of battery, outrage, negligence, breach of contract and
breach of fiduciary duty. Scherr claimed the incident awakened
memories of having been molested as a teen-ager.
   A state Department of Licensing investigation of Havsy also is
pending, but Yvonne Braeme, program manager of the health therapies
unit, wouldn't say whether the probe was related to a complaint
Scherr filed with the Medical Society of Pierce County.
   The case concerned Scherr's visit to Havsy's office Feb. 24, 1987.
   A defense memorandum said the osteopath and patient had been
friends over the years and often told each other jokes.
   ``At the conclusion of the appointment and in the privacy of his
office, (Havsy) began the relating of a joke and (Scherr)
participated therein,'' the memo said. ``Subsequently, (Scherr) then
went out and publicly displayed his chest. (He) also went through
elaborate steps to preserve the drawing.
   ``(Scherr's) actions were designated solely to exploit a joke
between friends by turning it into a lawsuit.''
   Neither Havsy nor his attorney returned phone calls, and Scherr
refused to comment.
   In a deposition taken this year, however, Scherr gave a different
account, saying he told Havsy he was in pain.
   ```I've been in a lot of pain all weekend. Something has to be
done. I'm experiencing a lot more pain than I normally have,'''
Scherr recounted in the deposition.
   Havsy then held Scherr down and drew on his chest while laughing,
the document says.
   Scherr said he showed the cartoon to two of Havsy's employees,
then called several attorneys and talked to his father, who
persuaded him to have a picture of it taken at a photography studio.
His father also traced the design before Scherr washed it off his
chest the day it was drawn, he said.
   The case was set for trial March 20 in Pierce County Superior
Court.
</TEXT>
