<2ND_LINE>AM-Finding Vets,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vets Organization Deluged With Calls</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WILKES-BARRE, Pa. (AP) _ More than 250 people in three days
called a computer data base set up to help veterans find friends
from the Vietnam War, the program's coordinator said.
   ``The answering service is threatening to quit because they're
getting too many calls,'' John Sepcoski Jr. said Monday.
   The increased calls to the Find-A-Vet program followed an
Associated Press story that ran nationally in newspapers Friday and
Saturday. Pennsylvania television stations also have done stories on
the program.
   Find-A-Vet has more than 2,000 names in the data base and can
also search the Veterans of the Vietnam War's membership rolls for
more than 32,000 names, said Michael Milne, executive director of
the Wilkes-Barre-based organization.
   Milne said many veterans forgot to swap names and addresses when
they were rotated out of Vietnam.
   Find-A-Vet allows vets to search the data base, even if all they
remember is a military unit or a nickname. Sepcoski sends the person
making the request a list of people who fit the description. A $1
donation is asked.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Veterans of the Vietnam War, 2090 Bald Mountain Road,
Wilkes-Barre, Pa., 18702-9609. The telephone number at Veterans of
the Vietnam War is (717) 825-7215.
