<2ND_LINE>AM-Huerta,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Indictments in Huerta Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury has decided against issuing
indictments in the beating of farm worker leader Dolores Huerta,
whose spleen was removed after she was injured during a
demonstration in September.
   Although the panel found the injuries were not the result of
criminal wrongdoing by police or protesters, it recommended
extensive changes in police crowd-control methods, grand jury
foreman Luther Jones said Monday.
   ``We feel that by better monitoring of the crowd, the whole
situation could have been avoided,'' Jones said of the Sept. 14
incident that took place outside the St. Francis Hotel where George
Bush was campaigning.
   Huerta, 58, suffered two broken ribs in addition to the ruptured
spleen and was in the hospital for almost two weeks.
   The jury, Jones said, found that police policies ``were
inadequate to deal with what happend.''
   Huerta was passing out leaflets about a grape boycott when
officers ordered a crowd of nearly 1,000 people to disperse. Union
workers claimed the 120-pound woman was struck and jabbed with a
police baton.
   Jones said the jury's findings were based on testimony from
witnesses, including Huerta, and a review of police and television
videotapes.
   ``It is disappointing that there is apparently going to be no
serious action on the part of the city to discipline the officer
responsible for nearly killing Dolores Huerta,'' said her attorney,
Dianna Lyons.
</TEXT>
