<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1334EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Planetarium     11-15 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Planetarium,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>University Offering A Star-Studded Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A planetarium whose original projector made
viewers dizzy and ill is opening nine years late with a 68-foot-wide
dome and a projection system intended to simulate space travel.
   The Arnim D. Hummel Planetarium officially opens Wednesday at
Eastern Kentucky University.
   ``I always thought it would actually happen, but I didn't think
it would take as long as it did,'' said Jack Fletcher, who was hired
11 years ago as planetarium director.
   Equipment installed in 1979 projected images so blurred that
people who watched test programs became dizzy and nauseated.
   The university sued the manufacturer of the projection equipment,
Spitz Inc. of Chadds Ford, Pa. Two years ago, Spitz agreed out of
court to replace the original equipment with a new system called
Space Voyager.
   In most planetariums, the same projector produces images of the
stars and planets. That makes the planetariums ``Earth-bound,'' only
able to project the sky as it appears from the Earth.
   With the Space Voyager system, the projectors are separated,
making possible the illusion of space travel.
   The star-ball projector is 4 feet in diameter and projects 10,164
stars. Each star has a separate lens. There are five planet
projectors and a sun projector. Also part of the system are a
multiimage slide projector and a six-channel stereo sound system.
   The system is the third of its kind in the world. The others are
in Paris and Singapore.
   The planetarium is named for the first chairman of Eastern's
physics department. During World War II, Hummel was instrumental in
developing a radar-activated fuse.
   The university's planetarium is the 10th-largest of the 985
planetariums in the United States. The largest is the Reuben H.
Fleet Space Theater in San Diego, which has a 75-foot dome.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1335EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-PLO 4thLd-Writethru a0582 11-15 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-PLO, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0582,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-PLO</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration today rejected a PLO
proclamation of an independent Palestinian state, asserting that the
Arab-Israeli conflict must be settled by negotiations and not by
unilateral acts.
   Spokesman Charles Redman said the status of the West Bank and
Gaza Strip ``cannot be determined by unilateral acts of either side
but only through a process of negotiations.''
   ``A declaration of independent Palestinian statehood is such a
unilateral act,'' Redman said. A similar statement was issued by
White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   Fitzwater said that despite U.S. opposition to the proclamation
of an independent Palestinian state, the administration sees
``positive elements'' to the Palestine National Council meeting in
Algiers, most notably its support for U.N. Security Council
resolutions 224 and 338. These lay the groundwork for a
comprehensive settlement to the Arab-Israeli conflict.
   Redman said the administration has not yet seen the final text of
the resolution approved by the PNC but promised it would receive
serious study.
   ``Our objective is a comprehensive peace,'' Redman said. ``Direct
negotiations must be at heart of the negotiating process.
Palestinian partiicpation is required at every stage of
negotiations. All participants in the negotiations must renounce
terrorism and violence and each must agree on the accepted
international basis of U.N. Security Council resolutions 224 and
338.''
   Fitzwater said it ``still is not clear just how specific'' the
Palestine Liberation Organization has been about extending an olive
branch to Israel by implicitly recognizing the Jewish state's right
to exist.
   At the Algiers meeting, the PLO's quasi-legislature voted to
accept Security Council Resolution 242, which established the
principle that all states in the region _ including Israel _ are
entitled to exist in peace.
   President Reagan said Monday that PLO acceptance of the
resolution, which long has been the cornerstone of international
efforts to secure a lasting peace in the Middle East, ``would be
some progress.''
   But Reagan said ``there are other problems that remain to be
solved'' before there is a breakthrough in the PLO's stance toward
Israel. He was not more specific.
   Reagan spoke before the Palestine National Council proclaimed a
new independent Palestinian state in the Israeli-occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip with Jerusalem as its capital.
   Apart from accepting the 1967 U.N. resolution, U.S. policy
requires the PLO to renounce terrorism and to nullify the provision
in its covenant calling for the destruction of the Jewish state.
   Otherwise, U.S. officials are not supposed to negotiate with the
PLO or support its participation in any Mideast peace talks.
   The State Department on Monday released a ``fact sheet''
detailing attacks on Israelis attributed to the Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestine.
   The group, which has its headquarters in Syria, is believed to
have opposed approval of the U.N. resolution in Algiers.
   ``Apparently there has been an indication they're willing to
abide by 242,'' Reagan said of the Palestine National Council's
approach to the U.N. resolution, adopted after the 1967 Mideast war,
that implicitly recognized Israel's right to live within secure
borders.
   ``I hope that is true because that would be some progress,'' he
said during a picture-taking session in the Oval Office with Andrei
A. Sakharov, the Soviet human rights activist.
   The resolution, which was adopted by the Security Council again
in 1973, at the end of the Yom Kippur war, also calls on Israel to
relinquish territory lost by the Arabs in 1967.
   Asked Monday whether an international peace conference on the
Middle East could represent a solution to the Arab-Israeli dispute,
Reagan replied, ``I'm still not sure that that is the answer.''
   Earlier this year, the United States cautiously supported efforts
to arrange such a peace conference. However, officials stressed that
any settlement depended on direct negotiations between Israel and
its Arab neighbors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
