<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Newton-NBC     11-15 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newton-NBC,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers Argue Scope of New NBC-Wayne Newton Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for singer Wayne Newton and NBC-TV
returned to federal court to argue over the scope of a new trial in
Newton's libel suit against the network.
   Newton's attorney, Morton Galane, urged U.S. District Judge Myron
D. Crocker on Monday to limit the new trial to damages only, while
NBC's lawyers argued for a complete rerun of the original trial won
by Newton.
   Floyd Abrams, NBC's lead lawyer, said the jury that gave Newton a
record $19.2 libel verdict in 1986 failed to pinpoint a reason for
its action and that a new jury should hear the case.
   Galane, however, contended the issue of liability was decided
fairly in the original trial, when the jury ruled that Newton was
defamed by NBC during broadcasts in 1980 and 1981 that linked the
singer to organized crime figures.
   Crocker, who presided over the first trial, reduced the initial
jury award to $5.3 million last year and gave Newton the option of
accepting the smaller award or going back to court. Newton rejected
the smaller award.
   Crocker took Monday's arguments under submission. He has
scheduled the new trial for May in Los Angeles.
   Newton was in court Monday, flanked by his girlfriend, aides and
bodyguards.
   He sued NBC over three broadcasts in which NBC reported that
sources said Newton had gone to a reputed organized crime figure for
help with a problem. Newton testified at the 1986 trial that he was
seeking help in stopping death threats against his daughter.
   Newton contended the report left the impression that his October
1980 purchase of the Aladdin Hotel was linked to organized crime.
</TEXT>
