<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AbortionRights     11-15 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Rights,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women's Groups Vow `No Honeymoon' for Bush on Abortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vowing there will be ``no honeymoon on the
issue of abortion'' for the Bush administration, leaders of
pro-choice and feminist groups on Tuesday outlined a plan of action
that will culminate in a march for women's rights next April.
   ``We are determined that not one woman in America wll die or be
maimed from a back-alley abortion because George Bush was elected
president of the United States,'' said Molly Yard, president of the
National Organization for Women.
   ``Mr. Bush may intend to make abortion illegal again, but he has
to understand that if he tries, he will be awakening a `sleeping
giant''' _ the millions of women who have had abortions, both before
and after the landmark 1973 Supreme Court decision legalizing
abortion, Yard said.
   ``There will be no honeymoon period,'' said Eleanor Smeal,
president of the Fund for the Feminist Majority and a former
president of NOW. She said ``the election results indicate both
political parties continue to lock women and minorities out.''
   Smeal said politicians who ``talk family'' but vote against
pro-choice alternatives and the proposed Equal Rights Amendment to
the Constitution are ``hypocrites.''
   Yard said the groups' activities will ``turn the spotlight'' on
members of Congress and state legislators who don't represent the
views of their constituents as indicated by recent polls showing a
majority of Americans support a woman's right to a safe, legal
abortion.
   NOW outlined plans that include:
   _Setting up phone banks immediately to urge supporters to flood
Bush, Attorney General Dick Thornburgh and Chief Justice William
Rehnquist with mailgrams and public opinion messages demanding that
the abortion-rights ruling, Roe vs. Wade, be left standing.
   _Conducting vigils and pickets directed at leaders and
institutions financing and organizing anti-abortion efforts such as
``Operation Rescue,'' in which hundreds of protesters nationwide
have been arrested.
   _Holding an ``Inaugural Watch'' designed to give the issue
visibility in Washington during the inaugural parade and other
related activities.
   _Forming a committee to help make RU-246, a French-developed
``morning after'' pill, and other contraceptions available in the
United States.
   _A nationwide effort to organize activities commemorating the
16th anniversary of the Roe vs. Wade decision on Jan. 22.
   _Coordinating ``The March for Women's Equality'' on April 9 that
will enlarge an already-planned march to revitalize the movement for
the ERA.
</TEXT>
