<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     11-15 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa Accepts Official Trade Unions Chief Offer for TV Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa on Tuesday
promptly agreed to a nationally televised debate on the issue of
union pluralism with the head of Poland's official trade union
alliance.
   Alfred Miodowicz, member of the ruling Politburo and chairman of
the OPZZ, the All-Poland Alliance of Trade Unions, had challenged
Walesa to the debate in an interview in Tuesday's edition of the
Communist Party daily newspaper Trybuna Ludu.
   ``In connection with Alfred Miodowicz's proposal ... concerning a
public meeting, I state that I accept it,'' Walesa said Tuesday.
   Walesa said he had authorized Solidarity national spokesman
Janusz Onyszkiewicz and historian Adam Michnik, a veteran adviser to
the banned union, to make the arrangements.
   Although all the parties involved seemed to agree on the idea of
holding the debate, it was unclear who would take the next step.
   ``All members of the government will be glad to sit in front of
their TV sets and listen to such a discussion,'' government
spokesman Jerzy Urban said at his weekly news conference.
   The developments appeared to catch senior television officials by
surprise.
   Jerzy Slabicki, deputy chairman of the state Radio and TV
Committee, said he knew nothing about the proposal, but did not
exclude the possibility that the debate would take place.
   ``If there is to be a round table in Poland, such things are not
out of the question,'' Slabicki said, referring to talks promised by
the authorities during the August strikes to discuss the future of
Solidarity. The talks are stalled over government objections to the
proposed participation of Michnik and Solidarity adviser Jacek Kuron.
   Another broadcast official appeared excited about the possibility
of a TV encounter between Walesa and Miodowicz.
   ``It would be great. Two good partners would meet,'' said Marek
Tumanowicz, deputy news director for state television.
   ``It would be very exciting. If we announced for example that on
Friday after the news we were going to broadcast such a debate, I am
sure the streets would be totally empty.''
   Miodowicz has headed the official unions since they were set up
by the government in 1982 after the authorities banned Solidarity,
the Soviet bloc's first independent trade union.
   Solidarity and the OPZZ hold opposing views on the number and
organization of trade unions within factories and on the shop floor.
Solidarity supporters say more than one union should be allowed to
exist in each workplace because the OPZZ unions don't adequately
represent workers' interests.
   It would be Walesa's first appearance on state TV since 1983,
when Walesa challenged then-Deputy Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F.
Rakowski during a televised speech at the Lenin Shipyard in Gdansk.
Rakowski became prime minister in September.
   Walesa said a public discussion Miodowicz was long overdue.
   ``I do want to talk about trade union pluralism, but without any
adjectives. But I've been asking for a public debate for seven
years. ... Please don't attribute this to Mr. Miodowiz. It's me who
has been asking for it.''
   Walesa on Tuesday told 3,000 workers in the Lenin Shipyard he
will support management plans to restructure the yard and he is
satisfied the plans will save most of its jobs.
   The government had announced that the shipyard, the birthplace of
Solidarity, would be liquidated beginning Dec. 1, but now concedes
it will take 1{ years to close it.
   The government has said the closure is needed for economic
reasons, but Solidarity has said there should have been greater
consultations with the workforce and the announcement was a veiled
attack on Solidarity.
</TEXT>
