<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BuriedBodies 2ndLd-Writethru a0609 11-15 0869</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Buried Bodies, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0609,0890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Search For Victims Expands As Two More Bodies Found At Rooming
House</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to recast, moving up detail from
affidavits. Picks up 12th graf pvs, `The Sacramento...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SC2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The woman sought in the deaths of seven
elderly people whose bodies were dug up from the yard of her rooming
house had told police she ``never killed anybody'' when she was
questioned last week, court documents say.
   Police who found the sixth and seventh bodies in shallow graves
Monday were expanding a search for bodies beyond the yard of the
rooming house. Digging resumed this morning, and officers also
searched the house.
   A warrant charging the boarding home's landlady, Dorothea
Montalvo Puente, 59, with one count of murder was issued late
Monday, said police Capt. Sam Somers. Police questioned her Friday,
the day the first body was discovered, and released her Saturday
morning for lack of evidence.
   ``Our first priority is to get her into custody,'' Burns said.
   According to sworn statements that police filed to obtain the
warrant, Puente twice denied killing her missing tenants, saying,
``I have never killed anybody.''
   But the affidavits said that one of her tenants, John Sharp,
handed a detective a note that said, ``She's making me lie.''
   Sharp later told police that one resident disappeared after he
had caused a drunken ruckus and ``Dorothea told him that she would
take him upstairs and make him better.'' About four days later,
police said, Sharp ``smelled a very strong odor of what he thought
was death in the kitchen area.'' Puente told him the stench was
caused by some faulty sewers.
   Investigators using shovels, steel probes and a tractor found the
two bodies wrapped in cloth or clothes in the yard of the two-story
Victorian house, said police Sgt. Bob Burns.
   The bodies found Monday, one unearthed in the front yard under a
flower bed and the other in the side yard under a shed, are
unidentified, like the five others.
   ``We'll continue to dig, and we won't stop digging until we've
dug up every square inch of this yard,'' Burns said.
   The arrest warrant charged Puente only with the slaying of Alvaro
Montoya, a mentally disabled transient who lived in the boarding
house. A search warrant for the house was also issued Monday.
   The Sacramento Bee reported today that police in Las Vegas had
been told Puente may be there.
   Investigators planned to excavate the rest of the yard at the
rooming house and comb an adjacent lot that Puente gardened when it
was vacant several years ago, Burns said.
   In 1982, Puente was convicted of drugging and robbing three
people in a bar, and sentenced to five years in prison, authorities
said. She was paroled after 2{ years, said Christine May, a state
Corrections Department spokeswoman.
   Police said they were uncertain about the cause of death or even
the sexes of the victims found Monday. No cause of death was
determined for the other victims, police said.
   The list of possible victims lengthened during the day.
   ``There are a lot more than eight names,'' Burns said, referring
to the original list of occupants supplied by a social worker.
``There's a big list of names. We've got detectives scurrying all
over this city.''
   Puente also ran a board-and-care home up to nine years ago about
eight blocks away. A separate team of investigators was interviewing
tenants at that address but there were no immediate plans to dig
there, Burns said.
   Police Lt. Joe Enloe said investigators believed the elderly
victims were killed for their Social Security checks. Payments
continued to be sent after the disappearances and someone else
cashed the checks, he said.
   Police went to the house after neighbors reported a friend had
been missing since August and a social worker said some of her
clients were missing.
   A social worker familiar with the rooming house described the
residents as elderly people on fixed incomes and with few relatives.
   The case worker, Peggy Nickerson, told police Puente came to her
in 1986, offering lodging. Nickerson said she took up Puente's
offer, and during the past two years referred 19 clients to Puente.
   ``She was the best the system had to offer,'' Nickerson said.
``She said she was a widow and had a big house, and she said it was
her time to give back to other people. ... That was her story and I
didn't have any reason to doubt her.''
   Puente's daughter, Linda Bloom, described her mother as someone
who had a ``terrible childhood'' and was raised in orphanages.
   Bloom, of South Pasadena, met her mother for the first time two
years ago after being put up for adoption herself at birth. She said
Puente was ``not animated at all'' and spoke in a monotone.
   On Sunday, police arrested John McCauley, a 59-year-old resident
of the boarding house, on suspicion of being an accessory after the
homicides. He was being held at the Sacramento County jail.
   Authorities believe McCauley assisted Puente after the slayings,
and that she may have arranged for others to dig the graves, police
said.
</TEXT>
