<2ND_LINE>AM-City-County Book,290</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 6:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<HEAD>New Census Book Shows Loving By The Numbers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Los Angeles county leads the nation in
population gains this decade, Wayne County, Mich., has lost the most
people, and the scattered residents of Loving County, Texas, make
the most money and the fewest babies, the Census Bureau says.
   More than 10,000 communities are profiled in the new ``City and
County Data Book: 1988'' published Wednesday by the bureau.
   The 964-page book, selling for $36, offers a wide range of data
about the nation's cities and counties, including government
finances, employment, vital statistics, social welfare programs,
income and other factors.
   In addition to information collected by the bureau, the volume
incorporates information collected by 15 other public and private
organizations including the National Center for Health Statistics,
Bureau of Labor Statistics, American Medical Association and
Elections Research Center.
   Here is a brief rundown of some of the county findings:
   _Most populous county, 1986: Los Angeles, 8,296,900.
   _Smallest county population, 1986: Kalawao, Hawaii, fewer than
100.
   _Most population growth, 1980-86: Los Angeles: 818,700.
   _Largest population decline, 1980-86: Wayne, Mich., 173,500.
   _Most people per square mile, 1986: New York county (Manhattan),
67,181.8.
   _Fewest people per square mile, 1986: 0.1 in Loving, Texas; North
Slope, Yukon-Koyukuk and Dillingham, all in Alaska.
   _Lowest percentage of whites, 1984: Macon, Ala., 13.2.
   _Highest percentage under age 5, 1984: Unita, Wyo.: 15.7.
   _Highest percentage aged 25 to 44, 1984: Juneau, Alaska: 43.6.
   _Highest percentage 65 and over, 1984: Pasco, Fla.: 32.7.
   _Highest birth rate, 1984: Wade Hampton, Alaska: 41.9 per 1,000.
   _Lowest birth rate, 1984: Loving, Texas and Yellowstone National
Park, Mont.: too low to calculate.
   _Highest per capita income, 1985: Loving, Texas: $34,173.
   _Lowest per capita income, 1985: Logan, Neb.: $2,209.
</TEXT>
