<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Europe 2ndLd-Writethru a0625 11-15 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Europe, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0625,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Calls Berlin Wall Litmus Test of East-West Relations</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs graf 7, Kohl was meeting, with meeting occurring.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan declared the Berlin Wall ``a
litmus test of East-West relations'' today as he held a farewell
meeting with West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
   Kohl, responding through a translator at a departure ceremony on
the White House lawn, thanked Reagan for his efforts to improve
relations with the Soviet Union.
   ``Any kind of worsening in East-West relations will be felt like
an earthquake in our country, and of course first of all in
Berlin,'' Kohl said.
   Reagan, who will leave office Jan. 20, said, ``The divided city
of Berlin remains a powerful symbol of a divided Europe and a litmus
test of East-West relations.''
   The two leaders, who have been close allies, exchanged personal
best wishes along with discussion of issues.
   ``These have been good years,'' said Kohl. ``Both of us have
paved the way for a development that will be pursued by your
successor in office.''
   Kohl met with President-elect George Bush later in the day at the
vice president's residence.
   On Wednesday, Reagan meets with Britain's Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher, whom he said Monday he respects more than any other world
leader he has met.
   Answering a question from a junior high school student as to
whether the United States would ever have a woman president, Reagan
said he thought it was inevitable.
   ``As a matter of fact, the statesman in the world that I have met
that I respect the most is the Prime Minister of England, Margaret
Thatcher,'' he said. ``And she's done a remarkable job for England.''
   In London, columnist George Walden of the conservative Daily
Telegraph wrote, ``We must brace ourselves for a Niagara of mutual
admiration. The personal relationship has indeed been special.''
   Mrs. Thatcher is scheduled to meet on Thursday with Bush, who
will be sworn in as president on Jan. 20.
   There have been reports from London that the prime minister would
bring with her a proposal for an early meeting of Bush with other
NATO leaders.
   A senior administration official, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said, ``We have nothing specific from the British in the
course of planning this visit that said the prime minister would be
bringing along a proposal of this kind, but we certainly wouldn't be
surprised if such a proposal came.''
   April 4 will be the 40th anniversary of the signing of the North
Atlantic Treaty, and such decade anniversaries have been observed in
the past by turning the annual spring ministerial meeting of NATO
into a heads of government meeting.
   ``We had heard that, as London, which is to be the site of the
spring ministerial, considered planning for that spring ministerial
in the 40th anniversary year, that some thought was being given to
that meeting being a summit,'' the official said.
   The meeting will be in late May or early June.
   A West German official who briefed a reporter on condition of
anonymity said Kohl's visit would enable him again ``to congratulate
the president-elect and to see with him what the immediate tasks for
both countries are.''
   Both the U.S. and West German officials said Kohl was expected to
discuss East-West relations with the president and to report on his
own meetings with Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev and other
Kremlin officials last month.
   Reagan last met with both Kohl and Mrs. Thatcher at the
seven-nation economic summit in Toronto last June. Kohl was last in
Washington in February and Mrs. Thatcher in July of 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
