<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hamadi     11-15 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hamadi Becomes Ill, Testimony Interrupted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Confessed TWA hijacker Mohammed
Ali Hamadi fell ill during his trial Tuesday, forcing the judge to
interrupt emotional testimony by a former American hostage.
   The trial was adjourned until Monday after a doctor examined
Hamadi and ruled the defendant was unable to follow the proceedings.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, is charged with murder and air
piracy in the June 1985 hijacking of TWA flight 847, which was
diverted on an Athens-to-Rome route and forced to land in Beirut and
Algiers. U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem was killed and 39 Americans
were held hostage for 17 days.
   Hamadi told the court he was feeling ``very exhausted'' and
``very dizzy.''
   The session was adjourned for nearly an hour while he was
examined by a doctor, who told the court Hamadi was suffering from
dizzy spells and a headache.
   Circulation irregularities were blamed for the symptoms and
Hamadi was given a shot of glucose, said the doctor, who was not
identified by the court. She said Hamadi had been eating very little
and taking medicine to counter low blood pressure.
   The session was interrupted during the testimony of Burton Weber,
a 48-year-old American physician, who said he was returning from a
vacation in Greece with his wife and two daughters when the TWA
plane was seized.
   He described how he got up to go to a restroom and tried to find
his wife among the passengers.
   ``I looked everywhere on the plane but she wasn't there,'' Weber
said, his voice choked with emotion.
   ``First I thought she might have been killed, but then a
stewardess told me she had been released from the plane,'' he said.
Some of the passengers were released while the plane was in Algiers.
   Weber also testified how the hijackers robbed his wife of her
jewelry, which he valued ``in excess of $50,000.''
   Weber said one of the hijackers ``lectured us on the evils of
America, and it went on and on.''
   Like more than a dozen other American witnesses at the trial,
Weber also described the brutal beatings of passengers by the
hijackers.
   He said he had given a woman passenger an insulin shot, but that
the hijackers had refused his request to examine two men who were
severely beaten.
   ``They lay unconscious and looked dead. One had blood on his
shirt,'' Weber said.
   Weber's 21-year-old daughter, Marypat, who testified earlier in
the day, said she still suffers nightmares more than three years
after the ordeal.
   ``I have had nightmares and I'm scared of flying on planes,'' she
said.
   She also told the court she thought Hamadi directed the hijacking.
   ``I personally felt that Hamadi was more in charge and that he
was the leader,'' she said.
   Hamadi admits he was one of the hijackers but denies killing
Stethem or robbing the passengers. He says the hijacking was
directed by his accomplice, fugitive Hassan Ezzeddine, who is at
large.
   Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt airport in January 1987 when
customs officials found liquid explosives in his luggage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
