<DOCNO> AP881115-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1546EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Scotland     11-15 0779</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotland,0803</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Upset Nationalist Poll Victory Reflects Scottish Disenchantment</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stunning election upset by Scotland's
nationalists illustrates deepening Scottish dislike for the London
political establishment and could breathe new life into the campaign
for independence.
   Thursday's election in the Govan district of Glasgow was to fill
a vacant seat in Parliament, and since such by-elections are
traditionally an occasion for registering protest votes, the result
cannot be accurately projected over Scotland as a whole.
   But it is a spectacular victory for the Scottish National Party,
which seeks independence for Scotland, and a humiliation for the
Labor Party, the opposition in Parliament but the dominant force
north of the English border.
   In one of the biggest upsets in 40 years of British politics, the
SNP's Jim Sillars won 14,677 votes aginst 11,123 for Labor's Bob
Gillespie, a 38-percent swing from the June 1987 general election,
when Labor took Govan by a massive 19,509-vote majority.
   It was almost a rerun of 1973, when Sillars' wife, Margo
MacDonald, staged a similar upset in Govan for the SNP. By the
following year, after two general elections, the bandwagon effect
had taken nationalist strength in the 650-member House of Commons
from two seats to 11.
   By last year, however, the SNP was down to three seats. Now the
question is whether the latest result is a freak, or the precursor
of a 1970s-style revival.
   ``The Scottish people will now start marching towards their
destiny as an independent country with an independent economy,''
Sillars, 51, declared to cheering supporters after the result was
announced in the heavily blue-collar constituency.
   ``It's a pretty substantial blip,'' conceded Scottish Laborite
John Home Robertson. He warned Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher that
``If she's not careful, and if this sort of bandwagon gets going,
she could actually split up the United Kingdom.''
   But the Conservatives, having harbored no expectations in Govan,
felt little disappointment with their paltry 2,207 votes, preferring
instead to mock Labor's defeat.
   ``Last night must be the first by-election where the protest vote
has been against the opposition rather than the government,''
taunted Tory government minister Michael Forsyth.
   Scotland's yen to end its 281-year-old union with England ebbs
and flows. Right now, says Professor James Kellas, a political
scientist at Glasgow University, ``there is a trend of Scottish
nationalism rising.''
   One reason is a widespread Scottish perception of Mrs. Thatcher
as a thoroughly English prime minister with no understanding of
Scottish concerns. ``There's a general feeling of Scottish interests
being neglected by the London government,'' Kellas said.
   Another reason is a new property tax that has provoked widespread
hostility in Scotland.
   The poll tax, or community charge, will be calculated per head
instead of on size of property, and is central to Mrs. Thatcher's
crusade against left-wing local authorities who tax the well-off to
finance welfare programs for the needy.
   An opinion poll on election night found 21 percent saying the
poll tax was the most important issue, compared with 19 percent who
cited unemployment.
   The SNP seized the opportunity. Where Labor opted for legal,
low-key opposition to the poll tax, the nationalists promised to
organize a non-payment campaign.
   Thus, says Kellas, ``the Labor Party appears powerless and
doesn't make enough impact. They're seen as playing the game
according to the rules, through peaceful opposition within the
confines of Parliament.''
   He says there's no telling whether the SNP will capitalize on its
triumph. Unlike in 1973, this time no general election is due for up
to four years, and the afterglow of Govan may not last that long.
   But at the same time, the SNP believes it has found a winning
formula _ ``independence within Europe.'' That means an independent
Scotland living alongside England and united with it through
membership in the European Economic Community.
   ``We are talking about freeing Scotland from England within the
context of the European Community, where England would be no more
than a friendly partner and there would be no control of Scotland
from England whatsoever,'' says Sillars.
   With the approach of 1992 and an end to tax barriers and frontier
restrictions within the EEC, that notion ``is looking more palatable
to people than in the past,'' said Kellas.
   Scottish social commentator Tom Nairn said Scots who in the past
would shy away from outright secession see the new formula as a way
of retaining an association with England while going independent.
   ``The formula is appealing,'' he said, ``because it smacks of
having your cake and eating it.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Marcus Eliason, news editor of The Associated
Press London bureau, has reported on Scottish issues since 1984.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
