<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SexAbuse     11-15 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sex Abuse,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Charges Against Great Neck Teen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two teen-agers already charged in incidents
of molesting young boys were charged Tuesday with an additional 302
counts of sodomy and sexual abuse, authorities said.
   The new charges bring to 20 the number of boys allegedly abused
at a home computer school in Great Neck operated by Arnold Friedman,
56.
   Friedman's son Jesse, 19, and his friend, Ross Goldstein, 18,
pleaded innocent to the new charges Tuesday before Nassau County
Judge Abbey Boklan.
   Boklan ordered Friedman continued free on $100,000 bail despite
the objections of Nassau County Prosecutor Joseph Onorato, who urged
bail of $200,000. He argued the additional charges against Friedman,
which bring the total to 250 counts, increase the risk that he will
flee.
   Goldstein was released on $25,000 bail.
   The latest indictment alleges that Friedman and Goldstein
sexually abused seven boys, ages 9 to 12, at the Friedman residence
in 1986 and 1987. The boys were students at the computer school.
   This latest indictment charges Jesse Friedman with 198 counts of
sodomy, sexual abuse, use of a child in a sexual performance and
endangering the welfare of a child.
   Goldstein had previously been arrested and charged with various
sex-abuse charges in connection with purported child sex orgies at
the Friedman residence in 1986 and 1987.
   Tuesday's indictment accuses Goldstein of 118 counts of
sex-related crimes.
   Friedman's father pleaded guilty last March to 42 sex-related
charges involving 13 boys who attended his home computer courses. He
is serving 10 to 30 years in prison. The sentence is concurrent with
a federal sentence that Friedman received for sending child
pornography through the mails.
   Goldstein and Jesse Friedman are scheduled for trial Jan. 4.
</TEXT>
