<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-PLO Bjt   11-15 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-PLO, Bjt,0724</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In Occupied Territories, Palestinians Celebrate Despite Curfews</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JRL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NABLUS, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jubilant Palestinian youths set
off fireworks and chanted ``My Homeland, My Homeland'' Tuesday
despite tight security measures aimed at quelling fanfare over the
newly declared Palestinian independence.
   The celebrations in the West Bank and Gaza Strip took on a
cat-and-mouse style, as youths violated curfews to send balloons
aloft with outlawed Palestinian flags or sing patriotic songs, then
ran and hid when army patrols arrived, Arab witnesses said.
   At least seven people suffered gunshot wounds in Gaza, where
650,000 Arab residents were under orders to stay in their homes,
hospital officials said. Military spokesmen had no reports of bullet
wounds.
   The army sealed the territories, setting up checkpoints on major
highways and barring Palestinians from entering Israel. Reporters
were allowed into the territories only with military escorts.
   A reporter escorted into Ramallah was told by a Palestinian woman
who gave only her first name, Marlin: ``Today we are very happy
because the PLO says we have an independent state. No matter that we
do not celebrate today. We will celebrate tomorrow or the next day.''
   The declaration of independence was announced early Tuesday by
PLO chief Yasser Arafat at a meeting of the Palestine National
Council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile, in Algiers, Algeria.
   Curfews were in force throughout Gaza and in at least 25 towns
and refugee camps in the West Bank, the army reported.
   Soldiers patrolled communities in jeeps and on foot. Armored
personnel carriers mounted with machine guns drove through the
streets of Bethlehem, and metal-plated gravel throwers used in riot
control were seen in downtown Nablus.
   In Arab east Jerusalem, 1,000 additional police and army troops
were brought in. An army officer who insisted on anonymity said
troop strength in some areas north of Jerusalem had been increased
three-fold.
   Israel has occupied the West Bank and Gaza Strip, home to 1.5
million Palestinians, since the 1967 Middle East war. For the past
11 months, the army has been battling an uprising against Israeli
rule.
   Israel's Foreign Ministry issued a statement saying the PLO
declaration issued Tuesday in Algiers was ``double talk'' that did
not clearly recognize Israel or renounce terrorism.
   ``We still see the PLO as a terror organization,'' said ministry
spokesman Alon Liel.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said of the PLO declaration: ``This
is another step in the war of Arab terror organizations against
Israel's existence and independence.''
   Some Palestinian leaders welcomed the declaration. ``It shows the
Palestinians are ready to co-exist with Israel, that they want a
state side-by-side with Israel,'' said Gaza Strip lawyer Fayez Abu
Rahme, a moderate among PLO supporters.
   But fundamentalist Moslem leaders opposed the move.
   ``We have been offering sacrifices for many years, and now they
recognize the state of the Jews,'' complained Sheik Mohammad Abu
Teir, a Moslem religious leader associated with the Hamas (Zeal)
movement.
   In Gaza City, hundreds of small colored balloons, each bearing a
tiny Palestinian flag, were released over the Shati refugee camp and
the city's Remal neighborhood, witnesses said. Soldiers fired tear
gas, they said.
   Tear gas also was used to disperse 50 youths who marched through
downtown banging on kitchen pots, dancing and shouting ``PLO, Israel
No!'' When the soldiers went away, the partying resumed, the
witnesses said.
   In Bethlehem, which was put under curfew for the first time since
1967, the night sky was lighted with firecrackers launched by bands
of youths.
   At the nearby Dheishe refugee camp, passing cars of Jewish
settlers were stoned.
   Nablus, the West Bank's largest city, was under curfew and
streets were deserted. Still, the voices of children could be heard
as they played on rooftops, and chanting of the Palestinian anthem
``My Homeland, My Homeland'' could be heard through windows.
   Arabs who live in Israel staged a one-day strike to protest
recent demolitions of houses in an action aimed to coincide with the
PLO declaration.
   A man in an army uniform and driving an army truck fired an Uzi
submachine gun at reporters covering the strike in the Israeli town
of Taibe, but no one was hurt. Police took the man away.
</TEXT>
