<1ST_LINE>r w AM-B-1BGrounding     11-15 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-B-1B Grounding,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two-thirds Of B-1 Fleet Cleared</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force has inspected and cleared more
than two-thirds of its B-1B bombers following a crash last week that
destroyed one of the long-range planes in Texas, officials said
Tuesday.
   Lt. Col. George H. Peck, a spokesman for the Strategic Air
Command, said 63 of the 85 B-1B's located at SAC bases had been
inspected as of Tuesday without any problems being detected.
   The remaining 13 planes in the B-1B fleet are currently assigned
to other Air Force units for such things as equipment testing and
minor modifications, Peck added, but at least four of those planes
also have been inspected and cleared.
   The latest totals mean 67 of the 98 bombers, or 68 percent, have
been checked since the Nov. 8 accident near Dyess Air Force Base,
Texas.
   In that accident, a B-1B crashed and burned in a field near the
base _ the second accident to claim one of the new bombers in 14
months. The crew of four managed to eject and survived the accident.
   The Air Force has refused to speculate on the cause of the
accident, although a fire was observed by witnesses around the
plane's left two engines before the crash. SAC's grounding order
specified a mandatory inspection of electric, fuel and hydraulic
fluid lines.
   SAC, which is responsible for land-based nuclear bomber and
missile forces, has described the grounding and inspection order as
a ``normal precaution'' in the wake of a major accident.
   The bombers have been deployed to four operational bases: Dyess;
Ellsworth AFB, S.D.; Grand Forks AFB, N.D., and McConnell AFB, Kan.
</TEXT>
