<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Election-Poll 1stLd-Writethru a0588 11-15 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Election-Poll, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0588,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Drew Support From GOP, Disaffected Voters, Survey Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 12th graf pvs, bgng: `In May,' to CLARIFY that ``him''
is
Bush</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush won the presidential election by
solidifying his support with Republicans and successfully convincing
disaffected voters to back him, according to a post-election survey
released Tuesday.
   The poll, conducted by The Gallup Organization for the Times
Mirror Co., also said 44 percent of the respondents thought the
federal budget deficit should be the top priority for the Bush
administration. Other crucial issues for voters are protecting
American jobs and increasing programs for families and children.
   The telephone poll, one of several done for the Los Angeles-based
news company in 1988, measured responses from 2,022 registered
voters. The margin of error was three percentage points.
   Bush, who defeated Democrat Michael Dukakis by 54 percent to 46
percent on Nov. 8, did not entirely recreate the coalition that gave
President Reagan a resounding victory in 1984, the poll found.
   But by the second week in September, the vice president had put
together various elements that gave him a victory in November, the
survey indicated.
   ``While our surveys showed a fair degree of offsetting change
within Democratic groups between September and October, the overall
patterns of support first identified in September persisted through
Election Day,'' the pollsters said in a statement that accompanied
the results.
   Among the trends reflected in the poll are that Bush:
   _Bolstered support among core Republican groups between May and
late October.
   _Increased support among young, moderate voters during the same
period.
   _Seized the backing of disaffected voters, those
lower-middle-income people who feel alienated and tend to be
disgruntled.
   ``Bush could not have won with the disaffecteds,'' said Andrew
Kohut, Gallup's president. That group is estimated to comprise about
10 percent of the voting pool.
   In May, shortly after the end of the primary season, the
disaffecteds were evenly divided between Dukakis and Bush. By
September, their opinions of Dukakis had moved from lukewarm to
highly critical. Ultimately, 68 percent said they voted for Bush,
the survey found.
   Michael Traugott, a Gallup analyst, said Bush attracted the
disaffecteds by stressing his tough crime theme and pinning the
liberal label on Dukakis.
   In fact, the success of the Bush campaign was based on
highlighting the controversies over liberalism, the Pledge of
Allegiance and the prison furlough program.
   Among Dukakis voters, the most important campaign issues were the
allegations about Bush's involvement in the Iran-Contra matter, the
administration's dealing with Panamanian leader Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega and the selection of Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle as the GOP vice
presidential candidate.
   Voters expressed some discontent with the campaign and the
candidates, the survey said. Some 63 percent who backed Dukakis said
they were dissatisfied with the candidates, while 16 percent of
those who voted for Bush expressed dissatisfaction.
   Respondents also were asked to rate others participants in the
political election. The news media and campaign consultants were
given the lowest marks on an A through F rating system. One in six
people gave the press a failing grade.
   Traugott said he thought the low grade given the press reflected
in part a lack of understanding of how reporters do their work.
Other surveys have shown, for instance, that the media as an
institution is evaluated highly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
