<HEAD>Bush Back to Business After Florida Break</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts grafs 2-3, Bush also, with Bush asking Brady to remain
as treasury secretary. Removes pvs graf 11, As speculation, and subs
pvs graf 25, Meanwhile leaders, to update.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush returned to the nation's capital
today after four days of sun and surf in Florida and held his first
meeting as president-elect with a foreign head of government, West
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
   Bush also asked Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady today to remain
in his current post in the new administration.
   Brady is a former investment banker who served briefly as an
appointed member of the Senate. He is a longtime friend of the
president-elect, and was a key member of a circle of advisers that
Bush leaned on during his successful presidential campaign.
   Bush greeted Kohl outside the vice president's residence at the
Naval Observatory after the German's leader's lunch with President
Reagan.
   Asked by reporters if he would give Kohl reassurances on the U.S.
budget deficit, Bush said, ``the chancellor knows how strongly I
feel about doing something about that deficit.''
   Kohl agreed in German.
   Vice President-elect Dan Quayle was also on hand to greet Kohl
and two of his Cabinet members, West German Foreign Minister Hans
Dietrich Genscher and Defense Minister Rupert Scholz.
   Bush told reporters who asked what he hoped for from the meeting,
``Maybe I can get a little advice.''
   He returned to Washington earlier in the day after a four-day
vacation in Gulf Stream, Fla.
   ``Off to work,'' Bush said as he departed on Air Force Two from
Palm Beach International Airport. After landing at Andrews Air Force
Base outside Washington, he was flown by helicopter to his residence.
   Bush was to meet Wednesday with British Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher.
   The White House announced today that Bush and Reagan would meet
with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev next month when he visits
the United States to address the United Nations.
   On the eve of his departure for Washington, Bush was joined at a
beachfront vacation home for dinner by New Hampshire Gov. John
Sununu, a top campaign adviser mentioned as a candidate for White
House chief of staff.
   But Bush laughingly told reporters not to ``read too much into''
the visit by Sununu, who was the only political associate to see
Bush on vacation and who flew back to Washington with Bush.
   Asked by reporters about his prospects for the chief of staff
job, Sununu said, ``I'm still governor.'' Pressed further, he said,
``I'll do whatever he needs.'' He said he and Bush ``discussed
things in general. ...He will talk specifics in about a week or so.''
   Bush told reporters in a beachfront question-and-answer session
that his meetings with Kohl and Thatcher would focus on ``talking
about where we go after I become president, but it should be viewed
as a continuation of existing policy.''
   Bush also sought to reassure a nervous international financial
community that the U.S. budget deficit will be a top priority at the
start of his administration.
   ``It is a matter of great urgency ... and I want to be in the
forefront of trying to do something about it after I become
president,'' he said.
   Bush's campaign promise to reject any tax increases has led some
analysts to question whether he is serious about reducing the
deficit. He was been dogged by reports of a declining dollar abroad
and a dramatic drop in the Dow Jones industrial average after his
election.
   The calming statements had an impact on financial trading Monday
and today, however, as the dollar rebounded on most international
financial markets after its downward spiral last week. Several
traders credited the statements with calming fears that Bush's
advisers want the U.S. currency to fall further.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which took an
election-week loss of nearly 80 points last weeks, fell 1.95 on
Monday to record its fourth consecutive losing session.
   In Washington, the incoming chairman of the House Budget
Committee said tax increases will be needed next year to make
legally required cuts in the deficit.
   ``Anybody who's dealt with budget issues knows the size of the
challenge is too large to exempt any areas,'' said Rep. Leon
Panetta, D-Calif.
   Bush, however, dismissed the financial unrest by saying, ``These
gyrations happen.''
   Bush said he will tackle the deficit ``early on in my
presidency'' but added, ``I do not want to start acting like I am
president of the United States yet.''
   He was expected to name former Deputy Treasury Secretary Richard
Darman as budget director and Stanford University professor Michael
Boskin as White House economics adviser.
   Bush aides said that a list of three to five names is being drawn
up for him to consider for each Cabinet post.
   Bush also was asked about a report suggesting that Baker, his
choice as secretary of state, would wield clout as a ``deputy
president.''
   Bush replied: ``You haven't heard that here.''
   On reports that a three-person chief-of-staff arrangement was
under consideration, Bush said, ``Stay tuned. I'll have
announcements on that pretty soon.''
   On other topics:
   _Bush sidestepped a question about whether he would name a woman
to his Cabinet, coining a new word in the process. ``I will
anticipate there will be female representation in the Cabinet, but
... I don't like to put it like that sounds kind of quotaistic.''
   _ He rejected allegations that government foreclosure warnings to
80,000 farmers were held up until after the election.
   ``I don't believe there's any political motivation related to
agricultural policies at all,'' he said.
</TEXT>
