<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Move,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bushes' Pillows, Bed Will Go Along With Them, As Usual</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The next first lady of the United States is
getting ready for the 29th move of her married life and, as usual,
she is taking her bed and pillows.
   Barbara Bush said she and President-elect George Bush always take
their bed with them as they have moved from city to city during his
public career.
   Their move from the vice president's official residence on the
Washington Naval Observatory grounds to the White House on
Pennsylvania Avenue will be no different in that respect, she told
reporters flying aboard Air Force Two as the couple returned on
Tuesday from a post-election vacation in Florida.
   Mrs. Bush said she will start packing for the move when they
return from their Thanksgiving holiday in Kennebunkport, Maine.
   She said first lady Nancy Reagan already has moved the Reagan
furniture out of the White House residence and found replacements
for the pieces they took. The Reagans are retiring to California.
   Mrs. Bush said she and the president-elect do not have many items
of furniture. But she does anticipate a staggering job of packing.
   ``I have a whole roomful of toys,'' said the grandmother of 10.
   Mrs. Bush said the entire Bush clan, the couple's five children
and spouses, are expected at the inauguration in January, but she
expressed concern that her son Neil's pregnant wife would be up to
the trip.
   In an informal chat with reporters during which she kept a
watchful eye on her dog Millie, who was roaming the plane aisle,
Mrs. Bush also fueled speculation about the political aspirations of
her children.
   ``I think someday a couple of my boys will run for office,'' she
said.
   One prospect is the Bushes' oldest son, George W. Bush, 42, who
is moving his family back to Dallas. They had moved to Washington so
he could work full time on his father's campaign.
   As her husband had indicated a day earlier, Mrs. Bush said she
did not know if son George was planning to run for governor of Texas.
   Mrs. Bush said her son Neil ``is dying'' to run for office. Neil
Bush is in the oil business in Denver.
</TEXT>
