<2ND_LINE>AM-Autism Report,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pennsylvania Legislative Committee Approves Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE McGRAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennsylvania must begin providing autistic
children with the special education and attention their handicap
demands, a House committee said in a report approved Tuesday.
   The House Select Committee to Study Autism voted unanimously to
accept a draft report that outlines ways the state can help autistic
children.
   There are about 15,000 autistic adults and children in the state,
Committee Chairman Joseph F. Markosek estimated.
   The 32-page report will be put into bill form for introduction
during next year's legislative session, Markosek said. The current
legislative session ends Nov. 30.
   As defined in the report, autism is a mental disorder that is a
``severely incapacitating, lifelong developmental disability'' that
usually appears from birth to age 3. Autistic children suffer from
poor social relationships, impaired communication, and persistent
repetitive and restrictive behavior, the report said.
   The state's failure to recognize autism as an illness different
from other mental disorders results in autistic children being
placed in educational courses that do not meet their needs, Markosek
said.
   ``Since there are no formal categories, the children are placed
in the category of being mentally retarded,'' he said, adding that
``a lot of times they get training that is inappropriate for them.''
   Yvonne Husic, a lobbyist for the Association For Retarded
Citizens of Pennsylvania, said because autism is not recognized as a
separate disorder, autistic children are ``falling between the
cracks.''
   The report recommends developing in-service training programs on
autism for professionals who deal with handicapped children,
educating parents on ways to help their autistic children at home,
and implementing programs to help the autistic move into regular
classrooms, vocational training programs or the community.
   Also included in the report is a long-range recommendation that
the state set up two regional centers for helping autistic children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
