<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChurchSharing     11-15 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Church Sharing,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pastor Proposes Churches Share Space</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A minister is suggesting that various
congregations could save money and reduce waste by joining forces to
build a high-rise church, with one floor for each denomination and
shared meeting areas.
   The Rev. Ronald Nevin, pastor of Episcopal Church of the
Ascension in Wilmington, says such partner congregations could sell
their land and put the money into a trust fund to help the needy.
   Nevin, 55, doesn't propose all churches move in this direction.
   But he estimated that six churches within four miles of his
church use their sanctuaries no more than 20 hours a week, and said
the issue of under-used or wasted space needs to be considered.
   ``It is simply outrageous _ not to say un-Christian and a
betrayal of the gospel _ that in those places where unfortunate
people are most to be found, empty buildings and rarely used
buildings are owned by people who call themselves by the name of
Christ, who himself had nowhere to lay his head,'' Nevin said.
   However, he said, ``Whenever I've shared it with other clergy,
they've said, `Yes, it is interesting, but it will never happen.'
They just shrug it off.''
   George F. Cora, executive director of the Delmarva Ecumenical
Agency, who has worked as a Catholic priest in a shared church
building in Columbia, Md., said that sharing a building ``does
promote ecumenism to some extent.''
   ``It doesn't solve all the problems, in the sense that people
still want to be organized in groups small enough so they can know
each other,'' Cora said.
   The Rev. Charles O. Walter, pastor of Holly Oak United Methodist
Church in Wilmington, said he hoped the proposal would be seriously
explored.
   ``Part of me says it's important for historical reasons to
maintain my church, but ... I would probably agree to it a little
bit reluctantly to serve the greater good ...,'' Walter said.
   ``The most attractive part of it is you'd be able to spend more
money on missions and not just on taking care of church property,''
Walter said.
</TEXT>
