<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-Kohl     11-15 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Kohl,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With Transition Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan, Kohl Bid Farewell</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and West German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl, calling each other ``Dear Ron'' and ``Helmut,'' bade
their farewells on the sunlit South Lawn of the White House on
Tuesday after six years of close alliance on the world stage.
   Reagan reaffirmed ``the strong American commitment to Berlin''
and said, ``That divided city ... remains a powerful symbol of a
divided Europe and a litmus test of East-West relations.''
   Kohl thanked the American president for his ``bold and resolute
commitment to improving East-West relations'' and said, ``Any kind
of worsening of the situation between East and West will by felt
like an earthquake in our country ... and, of course, first of all
in Berlin.''
   It was an unseasonally balmy day, and even warmer weather is
forecast for Wednesday, when Reagan holds a similar meeting with
Britain's Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   Neither Reagan nor Kohl broke any new ground in their meeting or
the formal departure statements that followed it.
   Reagan said that the two countries ``continue to seek ways to
share early the risks, burdens and responsibilities, as well as the
benfits, of our common defense.''
   ``We reviewed the difficulties each country faces in doing more,
but pledge we would each do our fair share,'' the president said.
   He congratulated Kohl on the decision of the European Community
member states to take steps toward closer economic integration by
the end of 1992 and expressed ``our concern that this be done in a
manner that promotes fair trade internationally.''
   They devoted much of their closing statements, however, to
reminiscence and farewell.
   ``Helmut, this marks my last meeting as president with you,''
Reagan said. ``Six years ago, we stood together as I announced the
formation of a presidential commission to commemorate the
tricentennial of the first German settlement in the United States.
Six years to the day, I'm proud to announce a product of that
commission _ the dedication of a garden, here in Washington, as a
symbol of the friendship between our two countries.''
   ``In a few months, I`ll be leaving the White House,'' he said.
``But, the garden _ and all it represents _ will remain, to be
nurtured and sustained by the friendship between Germans and
Americans and by the leadership that you have provided.''
   Kohl, speaking through an interpreter, told Reagan, ``I believe
we can say, Mr. President, Dear Ron, we can put it very briefly and
say these have been good years. I think that both of us have paved
the way for development which will be pursued by your successor in
office.
   ... God bless you in all you do.''
</TEXT>
