<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SiameseTwins     11-15 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Siamese Twins,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors Weigh Whether To Separate Siamese Twins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A doctor who delivered Siamese twins said his
first indication of the unusual birth was the sight of three arms
emerging from the incision he made for a Caesarean section.
   ``On the fetal monitor, there was only one heartbeat and it was
perfect. The baby appeared to be of normal size. There was no fetal
distress,'' said Charles Kim, the obstetrician-gynecologist who
delivered the twins Sunday at Frederick Memorial Hospital.
   Shortly after birth they were brought to University of Maryland
Hospital in Baltimore.
   ``We were expecting one baby, not two babies joined together at
the chest and upper abdomen,'' Kim said.
   When Kim made the incision, ``Three arms came out and I knew
definitely that something was going on,'' he said. ``I also knew the
first incision would not work. The baby was trapped. I was afraid we
might damage the baby.''
   Kim said he quickly made another incision.
   ``We could see the baby was not in good shape _ its color was
poor, it was lethargic and not breathing well,'' Kim said. ``Then, I
had a very big, astonishing surprise. We didn't have one baby. We
had two that were conjoined. After I calmed down, I did my surgery.''
   Siamese twins, which result when a fertilized egg fails to divide
completely, occur once every 50,000 to 100,000 live births. About
half of such twins die within 48 hours of birth.
   The parents, who live in Frederick and have one other child, have
asked that their names and details of the twins be withheld,
including their sex and whether dcotors will try to separate them.
   ``I think the parents are still in shock,'' said Karen Harrop,
University Hospital spokeswoman. ``It will be a couple of days
before our physicians can say whether we can do anything for the
babies.''
   Kim said he did not perform a sonogram, or ultrasound test, which
can detect multiple pregnancies, physical abnormalities and
determine fetal age, because the mother did not want one.
   In March 1982, Siamese twins joined from the chest to the abdomen
were successfully separated in a 10-hour operation at Johns Hopkins
Hospital.
   And 14 months ago, Hopkins made medical history when Patrick and
Benjamin Binder of Ulm, West Germany, became the first Siamese twins
ever to survive separation at the head.
</TEXT>
