<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1904EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FrostCrop     11-15 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Frost Crop,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researcher Modifies Bacteria to Protect Crops From Frost</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Embargoed for release by source until 6:45 EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Potato seedlings treated with a genetically
modified bacteria designed to protect plants from frost damage
suffered one-third as much damage as unprotected plants, a
researcher reported Tuesday.
   Two years of small-scale field tests proved the procedure to be
safe and effective, according to Steven Lindow, associate professor
of plant pathology at the University of California at Berkeley's
College of Natural Resources.
   Lindow was scheduled to report his findings Tuesday at the annual
meeting of the American Phytopathological Society in San Diego.
   Similar research by other scientists has shown that genetically
modified bacteria can protect strawberry plants from frost.
   The minor genetic modification was designed to counter the effect
of common bacteria whose structure triggers frost formation on
plants at temperatures just below freezing. Lindow and an associate
genetically modified a strain of the bacteria so it lacked the
frost-promoting gene but was otherwise unchanged.
   The modified bacteria was applied to potato seedlings before
naturally occurring bacteria could gain hold. Monitoring showed that
the modified bacteria could not be detected beyond the experiment's
93-foot buffer zone.
   Lindow's field tests were delayed for almost four years because
of safety concerns about outdoor experiments using genetically
engineered organisms.
   But Lindow said the genetically altered bacteria ``won't thrive
outside of the treated area'' because other bacteria are established
there.
   Established frost-fighting methods such as sprinklers and wind
machines can be more effective but they work in a narrower
temperature range and are more expensive to administer than the
bacteria strategy, Lindow said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1905EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chess     11-15 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chess,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Romania Defeats Peru, Moves into Lead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALONICA, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania defeated Peru 3-1 Tuesday in the
third round of the Chess Olympiad and took first place with 11
points out of a possible 12.
   The Soviet Union is in second place with 9{ points and one
unfinished game.
   England and Bulgaria are tied for third with 9{ points.
   The Soviets lead Argentina 3-0, but on board two, Anatoly Karpov
has adjourned in an equal position against Argentinian Grandmaster
Oscar Panno. On board one, world champion Garri Kasparov, scored a
crushing 36-move victory against Daniel Campora.
   Bulgaria moved up with a devastating 3{-{ win over Singapore,
while England, the second seed, defeated Israel 3-1.
   Hungary, seeded third, placed sixth after a 2-2 draw with
Czechoslovakia.
   A win scores one point and a draw scores a half-point.
   The Olympiad, a biennial world team championship, features 107
teams from 106 nations. The event is held under the auspices of the
127-member World Chess Federation.
   The biggest upset of the day occured when China, seeded only
27th, scored a 3-1 victory over fifth-seeded Yugoslavia. On board
two, Ye Tiangchuan defeated Yuoslavia's Predrag Nikolic. In the
second round Monday, he defeated Larry Christiansen of the United
States.
   In the match between the United States and Canada, grandmaster
Boris Gulko, who emigrated from the Soviet Union in 1986, defeated
Canada's board one, international master Igor Ivanov, a Soviet
defector. Gulko is ``Grandmaster in Residence'' at Harvard
University.
   In an unusual double, Gulko's wife, Anna Aksharumova, playing on
board one for the U.S. women's team was paired with Tatiana
Lematchko, a Bulgarian defector who represents Switzerland. The game
has been adjourned with Aksharumova two pawns ahead in an endgame.
   ``Today was the day the emigrants played against the refugees,''
said Gulko after his 28-move victory.
   The adjourned games will be played out on Wednesday, before the
fourth round. The 14-round contest is scheduled to finish Nov. 29.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
