<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Carlucci-Technology     11-15 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carlucci-Technology,480</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release at 4:45 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<HEAD>Carlucci To Seek More Funds for Military Coporate Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci, warning
that America's security in the next century will depend upon
advanced research being performed now, said Tuesday he wanted to
increase by $300 million the Pentagon's support of independent
corporate research.
   Carlucci, in a speech at American University, said he had been
reviewing Pentagon spending on ``independent research and
development'' and that despite the national budget deficit, could
not support cuts in such spending.
   ``This independent R&D program allows corporations full
flexibility in determining what research and development to conduct,
while at the same time enabling the Defense Department to identify
emerging technologies judged to have important defense
applications,'' Carlucci said.
   ``In 1987, the Defense Department reimbursed contractors for $3.6
billion of the more than $7 billion they spent on IR&D. As a measure
of this program's effectiveness, I want to announce today that I
will submit a 1990 budget request to the president allotting an
additional $300 million to underwrite independent R&D.''
   Carlucci described the move as one of four key steps to
maintaining America's technological lead over the Soviet Union in
military weaponry.
   The other steps include maintaining effective controls against
technology theft and espionage; more cooperation with Western allies
who also are pushing back technological frontiers; and supporting a
healthy defense industrial base of Pentagon contractors.
   In his speech, a copy of which was released in advance at the
Pentagon, Carlucci expressed optimism about each of the four steps
except one: the U.S. industrial base.
   ``This, I am sorry to say, is at present a dark cloud on the
strategic horizon,'' he said.
   ``There are unmistakable signs that right now, our defense
industrial base is shrinking _ the result of a defense budgeting
process and acquisition system that combine chronic instability and
excessive regulation, with predictable results.
   ``We need to put an end to this erosion; streamline and stabilize
the system, and create a more hospitable climate for technological
innovation and growth.''
   Carlucci is expected to step down in January when Vice President
George Bush is inaugurated as president and thus the fate of his
recommendation for increased research spending remains unclear.
   However, the Pentagon had been widely rumored in recent months to
be considering a cut in such funding and thus Carlucci's endorsement
of an actual increase might carry great weight with his successor.
   Earlier in his speech Tuesday, delivered before the Kennedy
Political Union at the university, Carlucci asserted technology had
made it possible for the United States ``to meet its national
security needs without militarizing society.''
   ``Rather than engaging in a contest to match potential
adversaries soldier for soldier, ship for ship or tank for tank, we
have sought to turn our technological superiority to our strategic
advantage. To a large extent, we've offset quantity with quality,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1615EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-L'Ambiance-Settlement Bjt   11-15 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-L'Ambiance-Settlement, Bjt,0701</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$41 Million Settlement Reached in L'Ambiance Plaza Collapse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Families of 28 men killed in the
L'Ambiance Plaza building collapse and the 16 men who were injured
will share $30 million under a tentative $41 million settlement of
all lawsuits, a judge said Tuesday.
   Legal experts said the mediation process that led to the
agreement may have averted years of litigation and was unique
because of the number of lawsuits and potential lawsuits involved.
   U.S. District Judge Robert C. Zampano said he and a state
Superior Court judge, who together mediated talks leading to the
settlement, scheduled a hearing for final approval of the agreement
for Dec. 1.
   If all parties sign, it would end all litigation from the
collapse of the half-finished apartment building in Bridgeport on
April 23, 1987.
   ``I think we have a global settlement of all aspects of the
L'Ambiance building collapse and I feel very, very good,'' Zampano
said. ``All 40 defendants and potential defendants contributed (to
the settlement), which speaks of extraordinary cooperation.''
   ``No amount of money is going to replace what those people lost.
The only good thing is that it was done speedily,'' said Richard
Bieder, lead counsel for the plaintiffs.
   The proposed settlement didn't resolve the question of who was to
blame, although federal investigators placed the primary blame for
the accident on three contractors.
   Lawyers for all sides are reviewing documents drafted to
implement the settlement. Federal, state and probate judges, along
with two members of the state Workers Compensation Commission, also
will be asked to approve it, Zampano said.
   Under the settlement, the children of the men who died will
receive a weekly income until they are 30 years old and money for
college if they choose to go, Zampano said. The mediators wanted
them to be taken care of ``just as if their fathers had lived,'' he
said.
   Widows will receive income from annuities until they are 62 to 65
years old, when they will be eligible for Social Security, Zampano
said.
   Individual payments to victims and their heirs weren't released.
   Several legal experts commended the mediation process Zampano and
state Judge Frank S. Meadow organized.
   There were 92 attorneys involved representing victims' families
and workers, 40 companies involved in the project, the city of
Bridgeport and state and federal agencies.
   ``It's working concurrently to wrap the whole thing up in one
package that seems to me to be quite unusual and commendable,'' said
J.L. Pottenger, adjunct professor of law at Yale Law School.
   ``What is (unusual) is the size and scope of this case and the
potential number of parties and complexity of it,'' said James
Stapleton, president of the Connecticut Bar Association and a
Stamford attorney.
   Zampano and Meadow determined how much each victim should receive
by considering such factors as the age and health of the deceased or
injured, past wage history, earning capacity, age and income of
heirs, severity and degree of personal injuries, and life expectancy.
   In addition to the $30 million for the workers and their
families, the proposed settlement provides $11.25 million to settle
other claims, including those of contractors and insurance carriers
against one another, and to be used as reserve funds.
   A portion of the $30 million would be invested in annuities,
which are expected to generate an additional $20 million.
   The tentative settlement also includes provisions for the
rebuilding of L'Ambiance Plaza and the distribution to the
plaintiffs of some profits from the building for an undetermined
number of years.
   Still unresolved are $5.1 million in proposed federal fines
against five companies that worked on the project and accusations
that they violated federal safety rules.
   Terry Mikelson, an OSHA spokesman in Washington, D.C., said, ``I
can confirm that OSHA is in discussion with the court on a possible
settlement. There is no agreement at this point.''
   Zampano and Meadow said in their report that if OSHA demands full
payment of fines from the five companies, it could ``affect
seriously the contributions to the settlement fund.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1619EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-BradyProfile     11-15 1060</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brady Profile,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Transition Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush, Treasury Secretary Longtime Allies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In asking Nicholas Brady to stay on as Treasury
secretary, George Bush has turned again to a long-time personal
friend to staff a key Cabinet post.
   Last week, Bush announced as his first Cabinet appointment his
choice of James A. Baker III to be secretary of state.
   While Baker is the better known because of his service with Bush
in the Reagan administration, Brady is just as close to the
president-elect.
   Earlier this year, Brady, Baker and another close Bush friend,
Houston oil millionaire Robert A. Mosbacher Sr., were dubbed the Big
Three in the Bush presidential campaign _ the longtime friends whose
counsel Bush listened to most often.
   There is speculation that Mosbacher may become Commerce secretary.
   With Bush's support, Brady, 58, got the nod from President Reagan
to become Treasury secretary when Baker announced in August that he
was leaving the administration to formally become chairman of the
Bush presidential campaign. Brady was sworn in as the nation's 68th
Treasury secretary on Sept. 15.
   In his first two months, Brady has adopted a low-key approach
which emphasized keeping the economy on track and avoiding any
controversy that might stir up financial markets before the Nov. 8
election.
   With the election over, Brady is expected to move just as
cautiously. Many are looking for Baker to continue to play a major
role in setting the economic as well as the foreign policy course
for the new administration.
   Many of Baker's major economic initiatives at Treasury were in
the foreign- policy area. It was Baker who three years ago launched
an initiative with major U.S. allies to coordinate economic policies
in an effort to lower America's huge foreign-trade deficit.
   That coordination had at its heart a sharp devaluation in the
value of the dollar, to stem a flood of foreign products into the
country by making them more expensive while reducing the cost of
American products on overseas markets.
   While the dollar devaluation has shown results, America and its
allies are now concerned that financial markets might push the
dollar down too far in value, raising the specter of higher interest
rates and a possible recession in this country.
   Even the mention last week by sometime Bush economic adviser
Martin Feldstein that the dollar needed to drop further to cure
America's trade problems was enough to send the greenback and the
stock market plunging.
   Brady issued a statement Monday that the administration was not
abandoning its committment to stabilize the value of the dollar and
his comments along with those of Bush during a beachside interview
calmed the markets. Experts are looking for no change from the Baker
policy in this area.
   On another international matter, Brady has voiced support for
Baker's plan to revitalize lending to Third World countries.
   However, the effort has fallen far short of expectations and many
believe that Japan, France and other countries will force the Bush
administration to acknowledge next year that more needs to be done
in the area of debt forgiveness.
   Events are also likely to force Brady to quickly address the
savings and loan crisis, where estimates of the cost of bailing out
hundreds of insolvent institutions have skyrocketed to between $50
billion and $100 billion. Brady has already appointed a Treasury
task force to study the problem.
   Another Treasury study group is looking at the capital gains tax
and this too is likely to be a priority in the new administration.
   Bush campaigned on a pledge to cut the capital gains tax, which
is levied on profits from the sale of stocks, real estate and other
investments. The top rate is 33 percent, the same as for salary
income, and Bush proposed cutting it to 15 percent, prompting the
charge from Democratic presidential candidate Michael Dukakis that
such a cut represented a giveaway to the rich.
   Brady has discussed capital gains tax-reduction proposals with
top aides and reportedly favors the idea of a ``sliding-scale'' tax
that would allow the rate to decline the longer the asset had been
held.
   Brady is a millionaire whose upbringing and Ivy League education
closely resemble those of Bush.
   He entered Yale one year after Bush graduated. He went on to get
a masters degree in business at Harvard and then became an
investment banker in New York, spending an entire career since 1954
at Dillon, Read & Co., where he was known as a rainmaker, someone
who could attract big clients to the firm.
   Brady was appointed to serve out the Senate term of New Jersey
Democrat Harrison A. Williams Jr., who resigned in March 1982
following his conviction in the Abscam scandal.
   He did not seek election to the post but he remained active
politically as a troubleshooter for the Reagan administration,
serving in 1983 on three different advisory commissions _ on the MX
missile, Central America and foreign aid.
   When the stock market suffered its record plunge last year,
Reagan again turned to Brady, giving him the job of heading a White
House panel that investigated the market meltdown.
   He and the other task force members had only 60 days to figure
out what went wrong and recommend ways to fix it. One of the first
reports written on the crash, the Brady report is still widely
regarded as the best.
   The administration, however, almost immediately distanced itself
from Brady's main recommendation: a call for the Federal Reserve to
coordinate regulation of financial markets.
   But during his confirmation hearing in September, Brady hewed to
the administration's free-market line, saying he was satisfied with
the administration's approach, even though his own proposals were
much tougher.
   Brady was born in New York City in 1930 and grew up on a large
estate in Far Hills, N.J. His family's wealth gave him a substantial
start in business.
   His grandfather, who had arrived from Ireland during the mid-19th
century potato famine, started several electric utilities that later
became part of the Consolidated Edison Co. of New York.
   Brady's close friendship with Bush dates back to the early 1970s
when the two men became better acquainted through Bush's brother,
Jonathan. When Bush left the CIA in 1976, Brady tried to recuit him
as a partner at Dillon Read, but Bush turned down his friend's offer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
