<HEAD>Burning Cotton Forces Evacuations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALTUS, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wind-whipped fire that started in large
bundles of cotton burned several homes Tuesday, forced the
evacuation of parts of town and prompted authorities to send
students home from school.
   Joe Courtney, the city administrator, said the fire broke out
about noon in 40-foot-long storage modules filled with cotton on the
south side of the town. Some homes were reported on fire and a radio
station transmitter apparently burned in the blaze, Courtney said.
   Billowing clouds of smoke blanketed the town in far southwestern
Oklahoma.
   Fire units from as far away as Lawton, Okla., and Vernon, Texas,
were called in to help.
