<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PaulaCooper     11-15 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paula Cooper,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amnesty International Joins Paula Cooper Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International filed a brief with the
Indiana Supreme Court on Tuesday in an effort to prevent the
execution of Paula Cooper, who was 15 when she was convicted of
killing a 78-year-old Bible teacher.
   The human rights watchdog group argued in its ``friend of the
court'' brief that putting Cooper to death would violate
internationally recognized standards of law against executing people
who were younger than 18 at the time of their crime.
   Cooper was convicted in 1985 of killing Ruth Pelke.
   Michael Sutherlin, coordinator of the Indiana lawyers who belong
to Amnesty International, said Indiana's recently revised death
penalty statute, which raised from 10 to 16 the age at which a
person could be executed, should be applied to the Cooper case.
   ``Any beneficial change in the law that would make punishment
more lenient should be applied retroactively,'' said Sutherlin.
   Ten juvenile females have been executed in Indiana since 1676,
the last in 1912, Sutherlin said.
   ``Surely we have become a more civilized nation since 1912,'' he
said.
   The Cooper case is in the first stage of review by the state
Supreme Court. If appeals through the state courts fail to overturn
her sentence, she could pursue an appeal through the federal courts.
   No execution date has been set for Cooper, now an inmate at the
Indiana Women's Prison in Indianapolis.
</TEXT>
