<2ND_LINE>AM-Feed Program,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain Farmers Still Must Idle 10 Percent of Acreage for Benefits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No change will be made in the announced
requirement that farmers will have to idle 10 percent of their feed
grain base acreage to qualify for price supports and other benefits
next year, the Agriculture Department said Tuesday.
   Deputy Secretary Peter C. Myers said the 10 percent acreage
reduction program, or ARP, for 1989 was announced on Sept. 30. But
the law also authorizes further adjustments by Nov. 15 if the
prospective total supply of corn and other feed grains changes
significantly.
   The 10 percent reduction applies to 1989 crops of corn, sorghum
and barley, which carried a 20 percent ARP this year. The ARP for
oats will be 5 percent, unchanged from 1988.
