<2ND_LINE>AM-New Year's Shooting,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Ordered To Keep Block Bullet-Free New Year's Eve</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of manslaughter has been
ordered to spend New Year's Eve trying to prevent the kind of
tragedy that occurred last Dec. 31 when his stroke-of-midnight
gunshot killed a young woman.
   Ellis Pryor, 52, won't be sentenced until late January for the
shooting that neighbors say still haunts him. But Common Pleas Judge
Lisa Richette on Monday directed him to guard his North Philadelphia
block from reckless New Year's Eve gunfire.
   Pryor was shooting a semi-automatic gun into the air at midnight
last New Year's Eve when he staggered and misfired, killing Yvonne
Hunter, 18, while she stood on a nearby porch, Assistant District
Attorney Carolyn Short said. The prosecutor said she will ask for a
five- to 10-year prison sentence for Pryor.
   ``You are appointed captain of that block for the purpose of
discouraging and persuading everybody not to shoot live bullets,''
the judge told Pryor. ``If one live bullet does get fired, I'm
holding you responsible.''
   ``I want you patrolling that block. This will be your way of
redeeming yourself.''
   ``It was a good (order),'' Pryor's wife, Mary, told the
Philadelphia Daily News. ``I guess with his past and everyone
knowing him, they thought that was a good thing to do.''
   Pryor was convicted of involuntary manslaughter, reckless
endangerment and weapons offenses in connection with Ms. Hunter's
death.
   Neighbors said Pryor, who has several children and grandchildren,
has been haunted by the slaying and has not been able to sleep well
since.
   ``He has suffered tremendously,'' said Jo Ann Graham, 42, who has
lived next door to the Pryors for more than 20 years. ``He feels
awful, because she was so young. He's not a man without a
conscience.''
   ``On this block, I feel almost certain that we won't hear any
gunshots,'' Ms. Graham said. ``Everyone knew the young girl, and we
all knew the Pryors. It was devastating. Of course, he realizes he
was wrong.''
   Ms. Hunter ``had went visiting on New Year's Eve, and she was
going to come home at midnight to wish her mother Happy New Year,''
said neighbor Essie Haskins, 80. ``She got as far as the porch where
she was visiting and that's when it happened.''
   The judge told Pryor his street has been ``traumatized by this
death.''
   ``This was outrageous,'' she said. ``This was irresponsible,
immature and reckless. You are lucky only one person was killed.''
</TEXT>
