<HEAD>New General Executive in AP World Services</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Otto Doelling, who has headed AP bureaus in West
Germany, the Middle East and the United Nations, on Tuesday was
named general executive in the World Services Department of The
Associated Press.
   The appointment was announced by AP President and General Manager
Louis D. Boccardi.
   Doelling, 54, joined the AP at Albany, N.Y., in 1961, was
appointed correspondent in Syracuse the following year and
transferred to the World Services Desk in New York in 1964.
   He served as a correspondent and news editor in West Germany from
1965 to 1977, when he was named chief of bureau in Cairo. Later in
1977, he transferred to Nicosia, Cyprus, as chief of Middle East
Services.
   Doelling returned to New York in 1980 to become U.N. chief
correspondent. In 1987, he was named an executive assistant in the
World Services Department, which is responsible for marketing of AP
services outside the United States and administration of AP's
foreign bureaus.
   A native New Yorker, Doelling was graduated from the City College
of New York and Columbia University's Graduate School of Journalism.
He began his reporting career at the Gainesville (Fla.) Sun and
later became an associate editor for Army Times in West Germany.
