<1ST_LINE>r w AM-LemnitzerBurial     11-15 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lemnitzer Burial,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Chairman of Joint Chiefs Buried at Arlington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Army Gen. Lyman L. Lemnitzer, a former
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, was buried with full military
honors Tuesday in Arlington National Cemetery.
   Internment came after a private funeral service at the Old Post
Chapel of Fort Myer, Va., near the Pentagon.
   Lemnitzer, who died Saturday morning at age 89, was buried near
the main entrance of the cemetery, next to Gen. Omar N. Bradley and
near the gravesite of President William Howard Taft.
   After the funeral ceremony, units representing the Army, Marines,
Navy, Air Force and Coast Guard led a procession to the gravesite,
followed by the casket on a caisson and a riderless horse with boots
placed backwards in the stirrups, a symbol of a fallen leader.
   At the conclusion of the interment service, a 17-gun salute was
fired by members of the 3rd U.S. Infantry Salute Guns Platoon.
   Lemnitzer was also given three volleys from the rifles of an Army
unit. After the playing of ``Taps,'' the U.S. flag on Lemnitzer's
casket was folded and presented to Katherine Lemnitzer, the
general's widow, by Maj. Gen. Donald C. Hilbert, commanding general
of the Military District of Washington.
   Honorary pallbearers included retired military leaders Gen.
Bernard W. Rogers, Gen. Andrew J. Goodpaster, Adm. Thomas H. Moorer,
Lt. Gen. Edward L. Rowny and Maj. Gen. James A. Grimsley Jr.
   In addition to serving as chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff
in 1960, Lemnitzer was NATO commander in 1962, a former Army chief
of staff and combat veteran of World War II and the Korean War.
</TEXT>
