<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Corn-Soviets     11-15 0140</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Corn-Soviets,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Buy More Corn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought an additional 1.2
million metric tons of U.S. corn for delivery in the 1988-89
marketing year that began on Sept. 1, the Agriculture Department
said Tuesday.
   The latest sales brought total corn sold to the Soviets for
1988-89 to more than 5.9 million tons. Last year, U.S. corn sales to
the Soviet Union totaled slightly less than 5.2 million tons.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 1.2 million tons
of corn would be about 47.3 million bushels.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.55 per bushel at the
farm level, according to USDA estimates, meaning that the latest
sale could have a farm value of around $120 million.
</TEXT>
