<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Nielsens     11-15 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nielsens,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ABC Launches `War and Remembrance,' But NBC Wins Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first episode of ``War and Remembrance,'' the
opening salvo from ABC's big gun in the November ratings war, placed
fourth in the weekly Nielsens, not good enough to prevent NBC from
winning the week.
   The No. 1 show of the week was a one-hour episode of NBC's ``The
Cosby Show'' in which Cliff and Clair became grandparents. It had a
30.3 rating and a 47 share, the highest-rated ``Cosby'' since last
March.
   NBC dominated the top 10 and won the week ending Nov. 12 with an
average, prime-time rating of 15.6. ABC was second with 14.0 and CBS
third with 11.5.
   Each rating point equals 904,000 homes with television. The share
is a percentage of sets in use.
   ``War and Remembrance'' opened Sunday with a 21.8 rating and a 31
share. The national rating, released Tuesday, was lower than the
17-city overnights available Monday. The first installment's rating
reportedly met ABC's guarantee to sponsors, but the network was
somewhat disappointed since ratings for multi-episode miniseries
often start and finish at a high but sag in the middle.
   The miniseries is a sequel to ``The Winds of War,'' which opened
in 1983 with a rating of 39.1 and a 53 share.
   ``War and Remembrance'' runs 18 hours in seven parts, but the
story doesn't conclude until sometime next year when ABC is
scheduled to run the rest of the 32-hour World War II saga.
   Because of delays in its other programming due to the writers'
strike, ABC rushed the first part of the miniseries to air this
month, one of four ratings ``sweeps'' periods each year when network
affiliate ratings are measured. Originally the entire 32 hours was
to have run in 1989.
   The 10 top-rated shows of the week were: ``The Cosby Show,''
``Cheers'' and ``Golden Girls,'' NBC; ``War and Remembrance,'' ABC;
``60 Minutes,'' CBS; ``Growing Pains,'' ABC; ``Empty Nest,'' ``L.A.
Law'' and ``Dear John,'' all NBC.
   The theatrical film ``Back to the Future,'' which NBC ran against
``War and Remembrance'' on Sunday, placed 11th.
   The only new shows to make the top 20 were NBC's ``Empty Nest,''
``Dear John'' and ``Unsolved Mysteries.''
   CBS' new comedies were in trouble. Mary Tyler Moore's ``Annie
McGuire'' and Dick Van Dyke's ``The Van Dyke Show,'' plus ``Dirty
Dancing'' and ``Raising Miranda,'' were among the 10 lowest-rated
network shows of the week.
   ABC's ``Knightwatch'' had an inauspicious premiere in
second-to-last place.
   The bottom 10 were: CBS' election-night coverage, ``Police
Story,'' ``Annie McGuire,'' ``Dirty Dancing,'' ``National Love and
Sex Test,'' ``The Van Dyke Show,'' ``West 57th,'' ``Simon & Simon,''
``Knightwatch'' and ``Raising Miranda.''
   In news, the three networks finished in a virtual dead heat.
``CBS Evening News'' and ``ABC World News Tonight'' had a rating of
10.7 and a share of 19, barely ahead of ``NBC Nightly News'' with a
10.5 rating and 19 share.
</TEXT>
