<DOCNO> AP881115-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 2037EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Thatcher     11-15 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thatcher,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher To Meet With Reagan, Bush, Greenspan and Sakharov During
Visit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be topped after 7:15 p.m. arrival</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Margaret Thatcher arrives here Tuesday to take
nostalgic leave of President Reagan and size up his successor,
George Bush, whom she has called a symbol of ``all that is best in
America.''
   ``She wants to stress the forward-looking aspects of relations as
well as taking a backward look,'' said British Embassy spokesman
Michael Price.
   Mrs. Thatcher, 63, will call on Reagan on Wednesday for a
three-hour visit summing up an extraordinary eight-year relationship
that was both a personal friendship and a mutually supportive
diplomatic alliance.
   The two leaders, who last met when Reagan stopped by in London in
June on his way home from Moscow, also are expected to map out plans
for their meetings next month with Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev
in New York and London, respectively.
   The White House visit will be followed by a lavish gala dinner in
Mrs. Thatcher's honor _ the last such state dinner the Reagans will
host before the president leaves office Jan. 20.
   On Thursday, Mrs. Thatcher will meet with President-elect Bush to
talk about priorities for future arms control negotiations with the
Soviets, the American trade and budget deficits which have upset
international financial markets and prospects for resolving the
Arab-Israeli conflict, said Price.
   ``The Middle East will be high on the agenda,'' Price said.
   Mrs. Thatcher and Bush will discuss the latest developments in
that troubled area, including this week's Palestine National Council
declaration of an independent Palestinian state in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and the Gaza Strip, and the council's
renunciation of terrorism.
   Bush has pledged to commit his administration to the search for a
solution in the seemingly intractable dispute. Mrs. Thatcher, along
with other European allies, long have urged the United States to
pressure its ally Israel into negotiations with the Palestine
Liberation Organization if it recognizes Israel and forswears
terrorism.
   Mrs. Thatcher, 63, who is the longest-serving Western leader with
nine years in office, has meet Bush numerous times in his role as
vice president.
   ``We know him as a friend, we admire him as a man of unrivaled
experience and we respect him because he stands for all that is best
in America,'' she said before leaving London.
   Barring unforeseen events, Mrs. Thatcher will be in office
through almost all of Bush's tenure.
   The deficit problem, as well as U.S. concern about the
integration of the European Economic Community in 1992, also will
come up at Mrs. Thatcher's meeting with Alan Greenspan, chairman of
the Federal Reserve.
   Mrs. Thatcher will receive Greenspan, as well as Soviet physicist
Andrei Sakharov, at Blair House, the official White House guest
quarters. She is the first leader to stay in the 19th-century
mansion since it was shut down six years ago for extensive
renovations.
   Mrs. Thatcher, who was last here in July 1987, also is scheduled
to hold talks with Secretary of State George Shultz before flying
home Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
