<DOCNO> AP881115-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 2021EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-APAppointments     11-15 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Appointments,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ahearn Named Executive Editor; Mears Returns to Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William E. Ahearn, managing editor of The
Associated Press, was appointed executive editor Tuesday, to succeed
Walter R. Mears, who will become Washington vice president and a
political columnist for the news cooperative.
   President Louis D. Boccardi announced the appointments, effective
Jan. 1, 1989.
   Ahearn's successor as managing editor will be Martin C. Thompson,
who has been AP chief of bureau in Los Angeles.
   Mears, whose Washington career spanned 23 years before he became
executive editor, asked to return to the capital and to the
political writing that was his specialty.
   Boccardi said the change was in line with a plan established when
Mears came to New York five years ago.
   ``He has been a great help to me and an asset to the AP in his
time here, and he will continue those contributions from the city
that has been his professional home,'' the AP president said.
   Mears, who won a Pulitzer Prize in 1977 for his political
reporting, will write three analytical columns a week for the AP in
the new assignment.
   Charles J. Lewis remains in his post as Washington bureau chief.
   Boccardi also announced that Charles J. Hanley, who has been
assistant managing editor, will become deputy managing editor.
   Julie Dunlap was named assistant managing editor@features, and
Mike Silverman was appointed assistant managing editor@national
news.
   Mears, 53, became executive editor in January 1984, after serving
as Washington bureau chief for seven years. He has been an AP
special correspondent since 1975 and a vice president since 1978. He
first joined the AP in Boston in 1955 while still a Middlebury
College student, returned in 1956 and became Montpelier, Vt.,
correspondent later that year. Mears was reassigned to Boston in
1960 and transferred to Washington in 1961.
   Ahearn, 45, has been managing editor since 1985. He joined the AP
in 1971 in New York as a broadcast news writer after serving with
the Army as an infantry officer in Vietnam. Ahearn moved to the New
York General Desk, the AP's main news desk, in 1972. He was named
enterprise editor in 1979 and assistant managing editor in 1981.
   He was graduated from the University of Bridgeport in 1965,
worked as a copy editor on the Bridgeport Post-Telegram, then
attended graduate school at Boston University.
   Thompson, 50, has been chief of bureau in Los Angeles since 1986.
He was chief of bureau in San Francisco for 11 years prior to that.
He joined the AP in Seattle in 1966; was named correspondent in
Reno, Nev., in 1968; and then transferred to the AP's San Francisco
bureau in 1970 where he served as news editor.
   Thompson joined the AP after serving as a newsman for radio
station KEDO in Longview, Wash., and then was news director of radio
station KREW in Sunnyside, Wash. Thompson is a 1960 graduate of the
University of Washington.
   Hanley, 41, joined the AP in Albany following graduation from St.
Bonaventure University. He transferred to the Foreign Desk in New
York in 1976 where he was an editor and a special writer who
traveled extensively on foreign assignments. He was named assistant
managing editor in 1987.
   Dunlap, 40, has been the AP's senior feature editor for six
years. She joined the AP in Philadelphia in 1974 and transferred to
the General Desk two years later. Following a year as an editor at
The New York Times, she returned to the AP and became
enterprise-special assignments editor with responsibility for AP's
six-member regional reporting team and five-member national writing
team. She is a graduate of Penn State University.
   Silverman, 44, joined the AP in San Francisco in 1971 and
transferred to the General Desk five years later. In 1985 he was
named AP's senior national editor, responsible for coordinating
daily coverage of national news. Silverman is a graduate of the
University of Chicago and Stanford University.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1708EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Jordan-PLO     11-15 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jordan-PLO,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Refugees Welcome Declaration of Independent State</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-PLO Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian refugees outside the
Israeli-occupied territories welcomed the PLO declaration of a new
state Tuesday, but some criticized the implied recognition of Israel.
   ``I'm as happy as if I had won millions of dinars,'' said
23-year-old Ahmed Salhi, whose family fled to the Al-Hussein refugee
camp in Amman from Lydda in what is now Israel.
   In Abu Dhabi, a Persian Gulf emirate, teacher Irtifaa Gameel
Khateeb said: ``It's lovely to hear the term Palestinian state .. .
but the Palestinian is still being beaten up'' in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   More than 300 Palestinians have been killed and thousands wounded
since an uprising against Israeli occupation began in the occupied
lands Dec. 8, 1987.
   One of more than 300,000 Palestinians who live in Kuwait,
economist Tewfik Abdel-Latif, called the declaration ``a good
political step that represents an embarrassment to Israel and the
United States. They should now prove their good intentions.''
   He referred to the U.S. refusal to deal with the Palestine
Liberation Organization until it endorsed U.N. Security Council
Resolution 242, which implies acceptance of Israel, and renounced
terrorism.
   The Palestine National Council, meeting in Algiers, proclaimed a
Palestinian state with Jerusalem as its capital and endorsed the
U.N. resolution while stressing Palestinian rights to
self-determination.
   It also said guerrilla actions against Israel would be limited to
military targets in the occupied territories, where the Palestinian
state presumably would be established. The council serves as the PLO
legislature.
   Some pessimism was evident.
   ``I think the Americans will not recognize the PLO regardless of
what concessions we extend,'' said businessman Mohammed Hassan in
Kuwait. ``They will now say what the PLO did is inadequate, we want
more.''
   A dentist at the Al-Hussein camp, Bassam Khadra, said: ``As a
political step it means the recognition of Israel and we reject
that.'' His family is from Safad in what is now Israel.
   In Damascus, Syria, Palestinian groups opposed to PLO chief
Yasser Arafat said the declaration was ``dangerous'' and threatened
the unity of Palestinians involved in the uprising.
   In the Jebel Hussein district of Amman, Saadi Dabbour, a
physician from a Safad family, served Palestinian sweets to visitors
at his clinic to celebrate the Algiers announcement.
   Dabbour said he was ``full of happiness. ... I have been waiting
for this for four decades.''
   Asked about recognizing Israel, he said: ``It is an evil that we
cannot avoid.''
   Abdul-Munim Subeihi, a butcher in the Al-Hussein camp, said his
family fled Lydda in 1948 and he will return someday.
   ``I was prosecuted (in Jordan) ... on charges of smuggling
weapons to the West Bank,'' he said. ``I will go back (to
Palestine). ... I am very happy. There is something now I can depend
on.''
   Shukri Ibrahim, a taxi driver who came to Amman's Nuzha camp from
Jaffa in 1968, said: ``All the people I drove today said they are
celebrating the new beginning, a bright one, the Palestinian state.
Long live Palestine.''
   About 26,000 refugees are crowded into Al-Hussein camp, on the
slope of a hill in the Jordanian capital. Scores of children played
in front of simple concrete houses along narrow dirt lanes that
intersect the main paved road through the camp. The main road was
lined with stalls for the weekly vegetable market and customers
crowded around them.
   More than 100,000 registered refugees live in five official camps
in the Amman area, and at least 100,000 more live in five camps in
northern Jordan. Jordan has about 800,000 registered Palestinian
refugees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
