<1ST_LINE>u i AM-PLO-WorldReax     11-15 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO-World Reax,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab, Moslem Countries Recognize New State; Europe Cautious</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 13 nations recognized the
Palestinian state declared Tuesday, most of them Arab or Moslem
backers of the PLO, but Europe was cautious and Palestinians opposed
to Yasser Arafat condemned the move.
   Javier Perez de Cuellar, the U.N. secretary-general, welcomed the
decision by the Palestine National Council to recognize Israel's
right to exist and said it opens ``fresh opportunities .. . for
progress towards peace.''
   Countries recognizing the state included Algeria, Bahrain, Iraq,
Jordan, Kuwait, Tunisia, Saudia Arabia, North and South Yemen,
Malaysia, Mauritania, Turkey and Indonesia.
   Egypt, the United Arab Emirates and Morocco stopped short of
extending diplomatic recognition but said they supported the move by
Arafat, chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization, and the
Palestine National Council, which acts as the PLO legislature.
   Foreign Minister Esmat Abdel-Meguid of Egypt read a statement to
reporters saying: ``The establishment of a Palestinian state is an
important step toward achievement of a peaceful settlement of the
Middle East crisis through agreement among all parties to the
conflict.''
   Only Egypt among Arab countries has signed a peace treaty with
Israel.
   Britain's Foreign Office called the declaration ``premature.''
Norway said it was a step forward in the Middle East peace process
but that a state without territory could not be recognized, and the
Netherlands described the declaration as ``no breakthrough.''
   In Spain, Foreign Minister Francisco Fernandez Ordonez said the
``step of enormous importance ... will obligate the United States
and Europe to review their policy stand on the Middle East peace
process.''
   Sten Andersson, Sweden's foreign minister, said the decision
``could be a historic step that opens the way for peace and
reconciliation.''
   Greece said it ``salutes the courageous decision of the Palestine
National Council ... within the framework of United Nations
resolutions and international law.'' The Greek government has
diplomatic relations with both Israel and the PLO.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency said the
``foundations of the state-to-be are unsound and unenduring.'' Iran
is Moslem but not Arab.
   Kuwait said it hopes ``this state will realize the hopes and
aspirations of the Palestinian people in building up their national
and pan-Arab identity on their national soil.''
   Syria, which backs Palestinian factions opposed to Arafat, made
no official statement. A commentator on the state radio said: ``The
road to liberation, just rights and peace is the road of struggle
and refusal of any surrender in front of the enemy.''
   A statement from the Fatah Uprising guerrilla group in Damascus
called the declaration a ``catastrophe'' and said of Arafat and his
supporters: ``Their most dangerous aspect is that they threaten the
unity of our people inside the occupied territories and deal a blow
to the unity of the land (Palestine).''
   The Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command
said: ``This is a black day in our history, as they are trying to
fool our people through declaring an illusion independence to cover
their renouncing most of the Palestinian territory.''
   Jordan's official news agency quoted Prime Minister Zaid Rifai as
saying his country ``has always recognized the Palestine Liberation
Organization as the sole and legitimate representative of the
Palestinian people and the PNC represents their will.''
   He said the kingdom will ``continue to support the PLO in its
efforts to insure the national rights of the Palestinian people,
including their right to self-determination and the creation of
their independent state on their national soil.''
</TEXT>
