<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1958EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-AirIncident 1stLd-Writethru a0769-a0774 11-15
0819</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Air Incident, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0769-a0774,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Investigators Call For Immediate Review of Air Traffic
Control</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Combines Urgent series</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assoicated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators on Tuesday called for an
immediate review of air traffic control procedures in the Northeast
after finding that a string of errors allowed a commuter plane to
fly alarmingly close to Air Force One last month.
   The incident, which had been reported previously without detail,
occurred Oct. 12 when Air Force One with President Reagan aboard and
a Bar Harbor Airlines commuter plane flew within 500 feet vertically
and 1.5 miles horizontally as both planes were preparing to descend
to Newark, N.J.
   Standard separation for aircraft is 1,000 feet vertically and
five miles horizontally. At the time of the incident, White House
officials said the president was never in danger.
   But the incident prompted a broad investigation by the National
Transportation Safety Board which said Tuesday that ``numerous
managerial, operational and training deficiencies'' at four Federal
Aviation Administration facilities near Washington, at Philadelphia
and near New York were at fault.
   These errors reflected ``a serious lack of effective management
and quality assurance,'' said the NTSB. It called on the FAA to
conduct an independent investigation of air traffic control
performance at the facilities involved similar to a probe recently
concluded after a series of controller errors at Chicago.
   The board also said it was particularly concerned about its
findings because the FAA on a number of occasions dating back to
l986 had investigated similar shortcomings at the facilities and
indicated improvements had been made.
   ``The seriousness and magnitude of the problems ... justifies the
highest level of FAA attention and action,'' the five board members
said in a letter to FAA Administrator Allan McArtor.
   FAA spokesman Fred Farrar said the agency would have no immediate
comment on the NTSB findings.
   Among the findings that raised the NTSB's concerns were:
   _The controller at the Washington air traffic control center near
Leesburg, Va., who was handling the Bar Harbor plane, was never
aware that Air Force One was in the same vicinity as the commuter in
airspace between Philadelphia and Newark.
   _A senior controller who was handling Air Force One was not clear
on airspace boundaries and allowed Air Force One to penetrate the
Washington center airspace handled by the controllers near Leesburg.
   _A directive to hold up traffic into Newark because of the
impending arrival of Air Force One was misunderstood because the
message was not specific regarding which route Air Force One was
using.
   _Two controllers who observed Air Force One and the commuter
plane converging did not raise an alarm because they assumed there
were plans already made to resolve the potential conflict.
   _An area supervisor involved indirectly in the incident was found
to have been ``assigned to a position for which he was untrained and
uncertified'' while another air traffic coordinator was given duties
``without receiving formal on-the-job training or a briefing on his
responsibilities.''
   The board said these and other shortcomings ``contributed
directly or indirectly to this incident.''
   As a result, the NTSB said, a controller at the Washington air
route center gave the Bar Harbor commuter pilot permission to
descend from 11,000 feet to 7,000 feet, while another controller at
the New York air traffic control center cleared Air Force One to
descend from 11,000 feet to 9,000 feet.
   Both planes were converging toward roughly the same area.
   The two planes were allowed to continue to converge until another
controller noticed the two aircraft and directed the commuter to
halt his descent at 10,000 feet and directed it away from the Reagan
aircraft, the safety board said.
   At one point, two other air traffic controllers, whose primary
responsibility was to monitor traffic flow, ``realized there was a
potential conflict when the radar targets, representing Air Force
One and the commuter plane were about 10 miles apart and at about
the same altitude,'' the investigators said.
   But the two controllers, who were not directly handling either of
the planes, ``did not initiate a (warning) ... because they believed
that some type of separation standard was going to be achieved.''
   When the incident occurred, Reagan was on a campaign trip on
behalf of Vice President George Bush. He had spoken near
Philadelphia and was headed for Newark for another appearance.
During the trip, officials advised reporters of the incident but
provided no details and emphasized that Air Force One was never in
danger of a collision.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the president was not
aware of the incident until later. FAA officials said that the pilot
of Air Force One had been advised that the Bar Harbor commuter plane
was nearby and no evasive action was required.
   Bar Harbor aircraft was flying as Continental Express Flight 3494
and carried 33 passengers and three crew members on a flight from
Baltimore to Newark.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
