<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Politics     11-15 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Likud Asks Labor To Join Government As Junior Partner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The right-wing Likud bloc asked the Labor Party
Tuesday to join a coalition government as junior partner, but both
sides indicated there were too many policy differences.
   Likud and Labor, which leans to the left, spent four years as
equal partners in a tenuous ``national unity'' coalition after
indecisive elections in July 1984.
   In parliamentary elections Nov. 1, Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir's Likud won 40 seats in the 120-member Knesset and Labor, led
by Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, got 39.
   Shamir has been negotiating with small right-wing and religious
parties. On Monday, President Chaim Herzog asked him to form a
government.
   During a 90-minute meeting Tuesday, Shamir said Labor could join
a government under his leadership only if it dropped its insistence
on an international Middle East peace conference.
   Peres did not respond publicly to the demands, but Israel radio
said Labor ministers in the caretaker Cabinet opposed a coalition
under such conditions.
   After two weeks of negotiations, Shamir is in a position to form
a majority coalition with four religious parties and three from the
extreme right. His offer to Labor was seen as an attempt to avoid
growing demands from those potential partners.
   ``I explained to Labor that the good of the country demands the
establishment of a broad-based government, a government which would
include the Likud, Labor and those parties that expressed a
willingness to join a government under my leadership,'' the prime
minister said on Israel television.
   ``We have heard an invitation,'' Peres said. ``Some things were
more explicit, some things were more open-ended. We will discuss it
and then decide.''
   The 4-year-old coalition, in the first half of which Peres was
prime minister and Shamir foreign minister, has been split on how to
achieve peace with Arab nations and end the 11-month-long
Palestinian uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Shamir and Likud refuse to trade occupied land for peace, have
called for increased military measures to end the Palestiinian
revolt and oppose an international conference, which the Arabs
demand.
   Peres and his Labor Party are willing to exchange some of the
occupied land for peace and favor an international conference.
   Yitzhak Modai of Likud said: ``The question is do we have a
common approach on basic issues. After glancing at Labor's election
platform, I would have to say no.''
</TEXT>
