<1ST_LINE>u a AM-KmartCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0783 11-15 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-K mart Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0783,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Crashes Into K mart, Killing One, Injuring 10</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with number of injured; ID of driver, who was
questioned and released; other details; no pickup. Retransmitting to
restore writethru designation.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELLEVILLE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car smashed into a K mart department
store Tuesday, killing one person and injuring 13, authorities said.
   A witness said that after the car had plowed through the store
the driver tried to turn it around and drive back out.
   The car crashed through the front of the building and traveled
about 100 feet into the crowded store, spraying glass and concrete
and scattering employees and shoppers, said police Lt. Joseph
Simonetti.
   ``I just saw everybody flying,'' said Helen Romano, who was
standing outside the store when the accident occurred.
   At least 12 people were struck before the automobile came to a
stop.
   Ms. Romano said the driver of the late model Cadillac El Dorado
tried to drive out.
   The driver, 72-year-old Louis Prosperi of Bloomfield, was
questioned by police Tuesday evening and released.
   ``He stated he had a malfunction in the car,'' said Simonetti.
``The vehicle was impounded and will be given a safety and
mechanical check tomorrow. No charges have been filed or are pending
at this time.''
   The dead woman was identified as Barbara Urbanovick, 37, of
Nutley. Simonetti said she was pronounced dead at the scene.
   Clothing, cameras and jewelry were strewn across the store,
aisles were demolished and thick black skid marks were left on the
linoleum floor.
   One woman, Dorothy Becker, 65, was taken to University Hospital
in Newark where a spokeswoman said she was in guarded condition.
   Eleven others were taken to Clara Maass Medical Center in
Belleville, said hospital spokesman Lew Gardner. All were in stable
condition, with three of them suffering from leg and hip fractures
and the rest from lacerations and bruises, Gardner said.
   Hal Lindsay, district manager of the store chain, said there was
no available estimate of how much damage was done. He said police
would remain at the store to guard against looting.
</TEXT>
