<1ST_LINE>u w AM-TransitionRdp 6thLd-Writethru a0803 11-15 1137</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Transition Rdp, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0803,1,100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Taps Brady, Meets With Kohl</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 16 grafs to move up Brady material, UPDATE with
sources on what Fuller might do; PICKS UP 16th graf pvs bgng, `I
will'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush announced Tuesday that he was
asking Nicholas Brady to remain as Treasury secretary, and a source
said the president-elect also asked New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu
to be his White House chief of staff.
   Sununu, who is retiring as governor, had been one of two top
candidates for the job, along with Craig Fuller, who was chief of
staff for nearly four years in Bush's vice presidential office.
   Bush made the announcement to keep Brady after meeting with
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, the first of a string of sessions the
president-elect has scheduled with foreign leaders. Bush will meet
Wednesday with British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, and will
confer with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev next month.
   Bush also said Tuesday that his administration would work to
reduce the budget deficit while resisting higher taxes and trade
protectionism.
   His decision to keep Brady, 58, in the Cabinet was expected.
   ``Our most important priority is to keep our economy growing with
low inflation and he knows that we must resist the policies that
will impede that effort, such as raising taxes or resorting to
protection,'' Bush said.
   He said Brady ``knows we've got to sit down with the Congress on
a deficit-reduction agreement and we've got to do it soon.''
   Brady, a former investment banker and Bush's longtime friend, is
the second person chosen for the new Cabinet. Bush last week picked
James A. Baker III, his election campaign chairman, as secretary of
state.
   An official announcement of Sununu's appointment was expected
later.
   A source said Bush had decided on Sununu, whom he had invited to
a private dinner Monday night at a vacation retreat in Florida and
who flew back to Washington with Bush on Tuesday.
   Sununu declined to talk about his future as he arrived back at
the nation's capital.
   ``I'm still governor,'' said the 49-year-old conservative
Republican, who was credited with helping Bush save a primary
victory after the vice president lost Iowa's GOP caucuses. ``I'll do
whatever he needs.''
   Bush spokeswoman Sheila Tate, after talking with Fuller and
transition co-director Robert Teeter, said late Tuesday that she
could not confirm the choice.
   Also mentioned as possible candidates for the post were Fuller,
37, co-director of Bush's transition office, and Teeter, the other
co-director.
   Republican sources involved in Bush's campaign and on the outside
said Tuesday night that Fuller would not want a White House post
under Sununu. There has been widespread speculation that he might
accept another post such as a Cabinet job.
   Sununu was promoted for the chief of staff job by conservatives
who felt that he had more of an ideological edge than Fuller.
   ``I will make orderly announcements,'' Bush said. ``We're really
just beginning to take a look at the Cabinet.''
   Bush said he informed Kohl of his choice of Brady and that the
West German Chancellor was pleased. The U.S. dollar has fallen
sharply in relation to foreign currencies, including the West German
mark.
   ``I'll do my best to help the president-elect, serve the people
and to build on this, the longest recovery in the history of the
country,'' said Brady, a former senator from New Jersey who
succeeded Baker at Treasury last August.
   He had no comment on the fall of the dollar.
   Bush said the announcement was not made particularly to calm
world financial markets. But he added, ``I hope to the degree they
need calming they will have that effect.''
   He described Brady, a former co-chairman of the investment
banking house of Dillon, Read & Co., as a man who ``brings to his
office an extraordinary knowledge of financial markets, experience
in the private sector.''
   Bush cited Brady's involvement in the presidential panel that
studied the Oct. 19, 1987 stock market crash, as well as the
Kissinger commission on Central America and the Packard commission
on Pentagon management.
   Bush said he and Brady will sit down soon to focus on the savings
and loan industry crisis, in which about 900 thrift institutions are
either insolvent or ailing. The Federal Home Loan Bank Board says it
may cost the government up to $50 billion to bail them out.
   The Bush-Kohl meeting took place at the vice president's official
residence several miles from the White House. Vice President-elect
Dan Quayle and West German Foreign Minister Hans Dietrich Genscher
sat in on the talks.
   Bush has said he wants to forge close ties with the Western
allies, and the discussions with Kohl and Mrs. Thatcher raise the
possibility of an early meeting with leaders of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization.
   The president-elect has vowed to hold an early summit with
Gorbachev but said he wants to see Soviet progress on issues such as
arms control, human rights and regional conflicts. Reagan has held
four summits with Gorbachev, and he and Bush plan to see him in New
York next month, when the Kremlin leader addresses the U.N. General
Assembly.
   Meantime, the rumor mill worked overtime on who might be
appointed to top jobs in the next administration.
   The Heritage Foundation, a conservative think tank, planned to
deliver 2,500 resumes to the transition office, hoping to place
people with their views in jobs. Chase Untermeyer, the transition's
personnel director, is guiding the selection process for at least
5,000 political jobs.
   Among those expected to round out Bush's economic team are
Richard Darman as budget director and Michael Boskin as head of the
Council of Economic Advisers.
   New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean, who has been mentioned for a
possible Cabinet post, spent the day here Tuesday, delivering a
speech to a conservation group. His name has cropped up for possible
secretary of transportation.
   Sources on Capitol Hill said Bush campaign official Janet Mullins
was a leading candidate to serve as chief congressional lobbyist.
   Loret Ruppe, the Peace Corps director, has been touted as a
possible secretary of health and human services, as has Rep. Willis
Gradison, R-Ohio. At the Commerce Department, Robert Mosbacher's
name has surfaced. He is a Houston oilman who was the Bush
campaign's finance director.
   Meanwhile, Rep. G.V. ``Sonny'' Montgomery, D-Miss., said Tuesday
he had heard that his name ``is at the top of the list'' among
Bush's possible choices for secretary of veterans affairs. However,
he said Bush had not mentioned the new Cabinet level post to him.
   Montgomery, as chairman of the House Veterans Affairs Committee,
last year helped push to passage legislation that elevated the
Veterans Administration to a Cabinet-level agency. He and Bush have
been friends since both were freshman congressmen 22 years ago.
</TEXT>
