<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-CentralAmerica 1stLd-Writethru   11-15 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Central America, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0790,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UN Opposes Outside Interference in Central American Peace Process</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS four grafs on Costa Rica proposal for U.N. observers.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Assembly on Tuesday adopted a
consensus resolution opposing outside interference in the Central
American peace process. The United States blamed Nicaragua for
obstructing democracy in the region.
   ``The United States urges the international community to adopt a
realistic and honest appraisal of the disastrous effects of
Nicaraguan mismanagement and repression upon the search for peace
and democracy in Central America,'' said U.S. Ambassador Patricia M.
Byrne, U.S. alternate representative to the world body.
   As it did last year, the assembly endorsed by consensus a
resolution supporting the peace plan of five Central American
countries signed in Guatemala City on Aug. 7, 1987. The five who
signed the plan, also known as Esquipulas II, are Costa Rica, El
Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras and Nicaragua.
   But in a change from last year, the resolution said the General
Assembly ``appeals to the countries which are outside the region but
which have links with it and interests in it to facilitate the
implementation of the Esquipulas II accords and to abstain from any
action which may impede such implementation.''
   The reference appeared aimed at the United States, which aides
the Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras, as well as Cuba and the
Soviet Union, both of which arm Salvadoran rebels. The peace plan
prohibits foreign aid to rebels.
   Byrne told the assembly that the United States shares the desire
of the Central American peoples for democracy. But she said some
``troubling developments'' and anti-democratic trends in Nicaragua
were not addressed in the resolution.
   One year ago, Byrne said, the peace plan represented a mechanism
for moving toward democracy.
   ``Now, we know that the promise is not yet fully realized and
that one Central American country (Nicaragua) has not lived up to
its commitments,'' she said.
   Byrne said that under the peace plan Nicaragua promised a free
press, freedom of assembly and free elections. ``It has delivered on
none of these promises,'' she said. Nicaraguan elections have been
postponed, the free press is in danger of extinction and political
opposition leaders are in jail, the U.S. envoy said.
   She protested that the resolution calls for international
economic cooperation ``despite the absence of any progress by
Nicaragua to grant the freedoms that are basic to building a healthy
economy.''
   But Nicaraguan Ambassador Alejandro Serrano Caldera told the
Assembly that U.S. aid to the Contras was impeding democracy in the
region and fulfillment of the peace plan.
   He said the U.S. Reagan administration was using ``pressure and
manipulation of opposition groups ... in an effort to create
internal chaos.'' This, he said, had been orchestrated by the former
U.S. ambassador to Managua.
   He criticized the Reagan administration which last week renewed
its economic embargo against Nicaragua. This embargo was declared
illegal by the International Court of Justice in June 1986, he said,
and the General Assembly has demanded its revocation since 1985.
   Meanwhile, Costa Rica on Tuesday proposed that neutral observers
be stationed along Nicaragua's and El Salvador's borders with
Honduras.
   Foreign Minister Rodrigo Madrigal Nieto made the suggestion
during his address to the General Assembly of the Organization of
American States meeting in San Salvador, El Salvador.
   He said stationing U.N. observers would be ``a procedure of
verification and control.''
   The presence of thousands of Contras in camps in Honduran
territory is one of the key obstacles to progress in the peace plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
