<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SmokelessCigarette     11-15 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smokeless Cigarette,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Board Delays Action on AMA Request to Ban `Smokeless
Cigarette'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Arizona Board of Pharmacy on Tuesday
decided it wouldn't act on the American Medical Association's
request that it stop distribution of a new ``smokeless cigarette.''
   The R.J. Reynolds Co. is test marketing Premier cigarettes in
Phoenix, Tucson and St. Louis. The AMA filed a petition Nov. 2
seeking to have the product declared a new and hazardous drug, the
distribution of which then would fall under the auspices of the
pharmaceutical board.
   ``Our obligation is to protect the public health, so we feel that
something needs to be done about this,'' said Norma E. McConnell,
president of the board. But the board ``will not in the morning make
a decision that `yes it is a drug' or `no it isn't,' but we are
working toward that,'' she said.
   Mrs. McConnell said the board hopes to get more information from
the federal Food and Drug Administration, which regulates
distribution and marketing of drugs in the United States and has
more facilities and expertise that the state board.
   A petition the AMA filed with the FDA in April is pending.
   If the Arizona board later decides the cigarette is a drug, its
options include seeking an injunction, such as the AMA suggested in
its petition.
   ``Also, they have the authority as (the) AMA set forth in their
position to seize misbranded drugs,'' said Timothy J. Agan, an
assistant attorney general.
   Arizona law empowers the board to regulate drugs or hazardous
substances sold in Arizona, but it would have to file a lawsuit to
enforce any regulation declaring a product a drug, Agan said.
   Reynolds said in a news release that ``Premier is a cigarette ...
not a drug-delivery system, as the AMA has alleged.'' Its smoke,
Reynolds said, ``substantially reduces many of the chemical
compounds that the critics of smoking have been complaining about.''
   The company also said at the time it found ``it difficult to
understand how the AMA can in good faith suggest that Premier be
banned.''
   Dr. M. Roy Schwarz, an AMA assistant executive vice president,
said the product contains nicotine, an ``addictive drug ... which
has been implicated in cardiovascular disease.''
</TEXT>
