<DOCNO> AP881115-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 2314EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Disney-Labor     11-15 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Disney-Labor,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Members Vote To Accept New Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 9,000 union members at
Walt Disney World voted Tuesday to accept a three-year contract,
averting a strike at the giant theme park.
   The six-union Service Trade Council had rejected similar offers
twice.
   Council president Harvey Totzke said the vote was 1,059 to 677 in
favor of the agreement.
   ``I think they finally took a realistic look at the offer. I can
say it now, it was a fair offer. We got all we could get.''
   ``I'm obviously very happy about it,'' said Bill Ward, Disney
vice president for labor relations. ``We felt that we had a good
contract.''
   The new contract calls for raises of 50 cents an hour to workers
now at top scale. They earn $6.80 an hour in the lowest pay grade to
$9.70 an hour at the top grade. Workers below top scale would
receive raises of 35 cents an hour. In April 1990, workers at top
scale would get pay increases of 45 cents an hour, while those below
top scale would receive 30 cents an hour more.
   The Service Trades Council represents workers in various
categories, including ride operators, animal handlers, monorail
pilots and the people who portray Mickey Mouse, Donald Duck, Goofy
and other characters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
