<TEXT>
   The Missouri Baptist Convention says it
``respects, honors and intends to preserve'' emphasis on the
priesthood of the believer _ a concept discounted to some extent by
the national Southern Baptist Convention.
   The doctrine holds that each member has equal standing in
interpreting Scripture and in other religious rights, but the
national convention had insisted the pastor had ruling authority.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MANSFIELD, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many of the hymns sung in present-day
churches derive from a religious revival in 17th century America,
the ``Great Awakening,'' says a Protestant campus chaplain at
Manfield University.
   Based on research, the Rev. Joanne Weiss says that before that
period, church music primarily was chanted psalms. ``The change from
psalms to hymns took place because worshipers needed a new language
of praise,'' she says.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Physicist John Jackson says a final decision can't
be made about the Shroud of Turin, despite recent carbon-dating
tests showing it came from the Middle Ages and thus couldn't have
wrapped Christ's body.
   Jackson of Colorado Springs, Colo., who has spent 14 years
investigating the shroud, said in a telephone interview with The
Denver Catholic Register, weekly of Denver's Roman Catholic
archdiocese:
   ``Considering all of the scientific data collected through the
years, too many conflicts still exist to accept this latest test as
the final word... The 14th-century date just doesn't square with
some of the scientific data that has been gathered.''
</TEXT>
