<1ST_LINE>s w BC-Amnesty-Farmworkers ADV20   11-15 0831</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Amnesty-Farmworkers, ADV 20,0854</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Nov. 20, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Many Illegal Aliens Resort to Phony Documents to Qualify for
Amnesty</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Alejandro's Amnesty, b0647</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the promise of legal U.S. residency held
before them, thousands and thousands of illegal immigrants are
emerging from the shadows under which they harvested America's fresh
fruits and vegetables.
   In a last, desperate chance to become legal U.S. residents, many
of these farmworkers are using fraudulent documents to prove they
worked here before, thus qualifying for a legalization program that
ends Nov. 30.
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service and organizations
working to help the mostly Mexican immigrants agree there is massive
fraud.
   But the organizations say the INS has developed a ``paranoia''
over the problem and has coerced applicants into signing
``confessions'' that their documents are phony.
   Immigration authorities deny the allegation.
   To qualify for legal residency under the Immigration Reform and
Control Act of 1986, foreign farmhands must prove they harvested
fruits, vegetables or other perishable crops in the United States
for at least 90 days in a one-year period that ended May 1, 1986.
   The INS had estimated that 600,000 farm workers would apply.
Instead, the figure topped 1 million by the first week of November,
and up to 200,000 more are expected before the filing period ends
Nov. 30, according to Aaron Bodin, who heads the INS' Special
Agriculture Workers program.
   Under the initial phase of the legalization program, which ended
May 4, temporary residency was granted to more than 1.7 million
illegal aliens who proved continuous residency in the United States
since Jan. 1, 1982.
   The INS admits the service was ill-prepared with budget and staff
because it underestimated the farmworkers' demand for legalization.
To complicate matters, Bodin said, many of the farmhands were unable
to obtain the documents they needed. So they turned to labor
contractors who hire illegal immigrants, many of whom wrote letters
to anyone who asked _ for a fee.
   ``Every time I call the INS, they're screaming fraud, fraud,
fraud,'' said Christine Brigagliano, an attorney for the non-profit
California Rural Legal Assistance Foundation in San Francisco. ``The
INS is going bonkers with this fraud stuff.''
   ``The farmworkers are being penalized for fraud when we have
created a wonderful black market here,'' Ms. Brigagliano said.
   Mary Lopez, the California-based director of the Martin Luther
King Jr. Farmworkers' Fund, said she received reports of people
paying up to $800 for a phony letter, with the average about $300.
   Bodin said the INS concern over fraud is not paranoia but
suspicion that half the undecided cases that have reached processing
centers may include phony papers.
   Nonetheless, he said, early statistics showed a 92 percent
approval rate for the first 325,000 applications reaching the
centers, where initial decisions are made. Rejections can be
appealed to Washington.
   Those qualifying for legalization under the 90-day prior work
provision will receive temporary residency cards, which will be
adjusted to permanent status in most cases on Dec. 1, 1990. The
immigrants are not required to work in agriculture once admitted.
   The program also is available to those who can show they worked
90 days in each of three years that ended May 1, 1986, and have
resided in the United States for at least six months for each of
those years. They can become permanent residents earlier _ Dec. 1,
1989.
   The agricultural program was included in the 1986 law at the
insistence of growers, especially in the West, who argued they
needed a pool of legal workers who could be ready to harvest
perishable crops on short notice.
   ``The real test is yet to come,'' said Mike Stuart, senior vice
president of the Western Growers Association. ``It will be in the
number of workers who remain working in agriculture.''
   Stuart suggested that those evaluating the program watch how many
newly legalized workers show up to pick strawberries in Orange
County, Calif., in January _ the first harvest after the deadline.
   But for thousands of farmhands seeking a better life, the test
begins when they appear at a U.S. immigration office.
   ``They're being harassed, treated without dignity, told they will
go to jail,'' said Ms. Lopez of the Martin Luther King Jr.
Farmworkers Fund.
   Bodin described most INS personnel as ``cordial, friendly and
trying to help'' but acknowledged their job was ``to determine the
credibility of the applicant.''
   He said farmworkers may find their interviews difficult because
they're victims of ``the labor market they've been in.''
   ``They were paid in cash, they rode around in a pickup truck,
they might not know the names of the farms they worked, only the
crew leader's first name,'' he said.
   ``We try to talk to the applicant and try to get a sense of his
credibility. We have gone the last mile. But we cannot simply take
peoples' word for it. The statute and the regulations require
documentary evidence.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 20</NOTE>
