<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1343EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WeekendTV-Busey ADV25-27   11-15 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekend TV-Busey, ADV 25-27,0687</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv27</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 25-27, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Gary Busey Plays Reporter in Miniseries About Fall of Marcos</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto LA1 of Nov. 14</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When HBO named its miniseries about the
revolution in the Philippines ``A Dangerous Life,'' it wasn't
supposed to describe the filming.
   ``When I got to Manila they gave me a three-page form to fill out
with very personal information to use in negotiations in case I was
abducted,'' said Gary Busey, who stars as a journalist in the
three-part, six-hour film airing on Home Box Office this Sunday,
Monday and Tuesday.
   ``A Dangerous Life,'' as seen through the eyes of a reporter,
tells of the 1986 ``people's revolution'' that brought down the
government of Ferdinand Marcos and brought Corazon Aquino to power
as president.
   During his 5{-week stay in the Philippines, Busey was accompanied
by four bodyguards and three trucks.
   Even so, Busey and the film company were forced to leave the
Philippines on short notice after Juan Ponce Enrile, the former
Minister of National Defense, obtained a court order halting
production, citing invasion of privacy. Another prominent military
officer also filed suit.
   ``All the judges of the Supreme Court were out of town,'' said
Busey. ``They gave us six hours to get out. We left under armed
guard. We went to Australia for the interiors then to Sri Lanka to
finish the exterior scenes. We finally won the case, but it took
months to come to trial.''
   Busey stars as Tony O'Neill, in Manila on assignment when he
witnesses the assassination of opposition leader Benigno Aquino,
Mrs. Aquino's husband. Marcos' right-hand man, Gen. Fabian Ver, is
accused in the murder, but his acquittal spurs Cory Aquino to
challenge Marcos in the presidential election.
   Marcos wins the election amid charges of fraud. Most of the
military sides with Aquino, and Marcos is forced to flee.
   The miniseries also stars Rebecca Gilling as O'Neill's estranged
wife, a fellow journalist; Tessie Tomas as Imelda Marcos; Ruben
Rustia as Marcos; Laurice Guillen as Corazon Aquino, and Joonee
Gamboa as Enrile.
   A number of Filipino actors appear in the miniseries, Busey said.
``They were magnificent. They came prepared, they were very
disciplined. The focus of the series is a story about their country,
which was very important to them. Tessie Tomas, who plays Imelda,
used to do a one-woman show on her. Imelda loved it. These are
actors who are playing people who are still alive who have the
ability to get back at them.
   ``Some members of the cast were pro-Marcos and some were
pro-Aquino. We had a lot of tension. My character is a man who gets
caught up in the passion of the revolution. I talked to
correspondents who covered it. They were very emotional about it.
They stayed with the rebel troops. That's where the story was.
   ``I thought this was going to be easy, but it was like two
lifetimes doing this. I learned an awful lot. It was a rewarding
experience. I learned a lot about human nature and how democracy
works in a Third World country.''
   Busey talked about the film on a break from the theatrical
feature ``Hider in the House.'' He was in his trailer watching the
soap opera ``As the World Turns'' while on location in Duarte, about
25 miles east of Los Angeles.
   ``I've been watching this for 25 years,'' he said. ``When I go to
New York I visit with these guys. I started watching when I was in
college in Coffeyville, Kansas. It's got everything _ sex,
blackmail, revenge. It's a great mental catharsis for an actor.''
   In ``Hider in the House,'' Busey plays a demented man who takes
up residence in the attic of a house being remodeled. The film
company was working at the site of an old house that was due to be
remodeled. The movie also stars Michael McKean and Mimi Rogers.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Nov. 25-27</NOTE>
</DOC>
