<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar has bounced back after a weeklong
slide, supported by the Japanese and U.S. central banks and calming
statements from American officials.
   Monday's rebound took momentum away from traders who are bearish
toward the dollar heading into the next big test for the currency,
Wednesday's report on the U.S. merchandise trade deficit for
September.
   Last week's slide stemmed from fears that President-elect George
Bush and his advisers want the dollar to fall to make U.S. goods
more competitive abroad and shrink the trade deficit.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GULF STREAM, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush, seeking to
calm the financial markets, has said he considers the federal budget
deficit a matter of ``great urgency'' that he intends to tackle
quickly in the new administration.
   Bush also said Monday he was fully committed to the Reagan
administration's policy of coordinated actions with other major
countries to stabilize the value of the dollar on foreign currency
markets.
   The vacationing president-elect added his voice to a chorus of
Reagan administration and Bush aides trying to reassure financial
markets after a huge sell-off last week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Transportation Department has ordered a
wide range of drug testing, including random checks, for more than 4
million transportation workers from airline pilots and flight
attendants to truckers and railroaders.
   Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley said Monday that the
transportation industries are no more immune from drug abuse as
other parts of society.
   He listed a series of accidents and other indicators he said
shows narcotics to be a problem among truck and bus drivers,
commercial pilots and railroad workers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The expected selection of Rep. Henry B.
Gonzalez, D-Texas, as chairman of the House Banking, Finance and
Urban Affairs Committee may further fragment an already-divided
panel and delay a solution to the savings and loan crisis, analysts
say.
   Gonzalez, a hot-tempered, outspoken maverick, is considered the
most likely successor to Rep. Fernand J. St Germain, D-R.I.,
defeated last week in his bid for a 15th term.
   Gonzalez will be taking over at the start of a critical year for
the committee. Regulators estimate as much as $50 billion is needed
to clean up the S&L mess.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allstate Insurance Co. says it will stop doing
business in Massachusetts due to losses from the state's tough
insurance laws, echoing anger among insurers nationwide over
changing regulatory climates.
   Monday's surprise announcement came about a week after California
voters threw the industry into turmoil by approving a controversial
rate rollback on property casualty insurance, which encompasses
automobile coverage.
   Separately, the largest home and car insurer in California, State
Farm Mutual Auto Insurance Co., said it has stopped writing new auto
policies because of chaos surrounding rate-slashing Proposition 103.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chubb Corp.'s swift response to complaints
from farmers and state regulators over its drought insurance may
have saved the company from any lasting damage to its reputation and
profit outlook, analysts say.
   Chubb took a major step toward putting the matter behind it last
week, when it announced a $48 million settlement to a class-action
suit representing 8,000 farmers in 10 midwestern states.
   Farmers had sued when applications for insurance over this
summer's drought were denied.
</TEXT>
