<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court has agreed to hear arguments
on whether investor claims against brokers must be settled by
binding arbitration, an emotional Wall Street issue that was
heightened after the stock market crash.
   Also on Monday, the court said it would rule on the
constitutionality of a Connecticut beer-pricing law, ordered a
Florida court to restudy a decision on oil extraction taxes, and
agreed to hear an appeal by trucking companies seeking tax refunds
in Arkansas.
   The investor-broker case is considered significant because most
contracts between brokerages and clients specify that disputes must
be settled by binding arbitration and not through lawsuits.
</TEXT>
