<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     11-15 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Prices Higher In Quiet Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices have moved higher in quiet
trading led by refined products.
   The December contract for unleaded gasoline rose 1.51 cents to
48.16 cents a gallon on the New York Mercantile Exchange. The
December contract for heating oil increased 0.62 cent to 44.63 cents
a gallon. Other contract months for oil and gasoline also advanced.
   The December contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, closed at $14.27 per barrel, up 32 cents
from Friday's settlement price. Other contract months also gained.
   Traders said activity was light, with many participants attending
the annual meeting of the American Petroleum Institute here.
   Executives from major oil companies are represented at the
three-day meeting in addition to analysts, scientists and government
officials.
   Speakers at the meeting, attended by more than 1,000 oil industry
officials, were not optimistic about the prospects that OPEC would
reach an agreement on limiting crude production at its upcoming
meeting.
   Analysts had forecast a firming of prices in advance of two
meetings involving members of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries. OPEC's price and strategy committees are
scheduled to meet on Thursday followed by the full meeting of all 13
ministers next Monday.
   Opinion is divided over what OPEC might accomplish, but the hope
is that the cartel will move closer to an agreement that would
curtail production among its members and help boost world oil prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 0037EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessMirror Bjt   11-15 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Bjt,0747</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Caught in the Middle: The Sandwich Generation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Caught in a vise between the financial needs of
children and the care of elderly parents, a generation of Americans
is confronted with planning problems that almost defy solution.
   They are the ``sandwich generation,'' age 45 to 55 years, with
college-age children and parents whose incomes are limited.
   Unlike the very poor, the minorities, the elderly and
disadvantaged, this group has little political clout. Its existence
barely recognized, it is nevertheless destined to grow because of
biological and sociological factors.
   Among those factors: Parents are living longer, but their
income-producing years generally are not being extended. And young
marrieds are waiting until the last tick of the biological clock
before having children.
   As a consequence, the sandwich generation's parents become aged
and more dependent just as the offspring are preparing for or
entering college. Rising tuitions add to the pressure.
   To deal with the phenomenon, financial planners are seeking
creative investment techniques for the sandwich generation, but in
almost every instance those techniques require many years to become
effective.
   Moreover, the old and once-trusted method of shifting assets to a
controlled trust and automatically getting them back after the
demise of the parents does not work any more, thanks to the 1986 Tax
Reform Act.
   In addition, the tax laws make inefficient the simple, direct
technique of providing support from the checkbook, because such
funding involves after-tax dollars, effectively reducing the benefit
to 72 cents on the dollar.
   The tax law does leave two exceptions, but many members of the
sandwich generation may find them inapplicable to them. The
exceptions are:
   _If you provide more than one-half of a parent's support, and the
parent earns less than $1,900 a year, you may claim the $1,000
dependency exemption on your tax return.
   _You may claim your parents' medical expenses along with your own
as long as you provide one-half of your parents' support. And in
this case, the $1,000 gross income test need not be met.
   Judy Walsh, an accounting partner in the San Antonio office of
Deloitte Haskins & Sells, believes a member of the sandwich
generation should find a way to transfer assets to parents so that
the parents instead are taxed.
   Walsh, who made a special study of the situation, notes that if
you transferred titled property to your parents, particularly
property with an income, you can effectively move income to their
lower tax bracket.
   One approach along this line would be to set up a trust, put
assets in the trust and instruct the trustee to use all income for
the parents. This income then becomes taxed to the parents.
   While you lose total control of the funds, the trust could be so
arranged that the assets are distributed as provided in the parents'
wills, which means the money could very well revert to you.
   Ms. Walsh suggests that a second plan would be to create the
trust to pay income to the parents for life, with the assets to go
to the sandwich generation's children upon the parents' death.
   This plan might combine support of aging parents at a minimum
after-tax cost and provide gifts to children for education. Still,
there is no assurance that the money would be available in time to
help pay tuition.
   Another strategy is to have aging parents sell their home and use
the funds for support. They would then live in a residence, perhaps
a condominium, purchased by their children, who could tap their own
home for an equity loan.
   If all works as intended, these might be among the results:
   _The aging parents could shelter up to $125,000 of the gain from
the sale of their home.
   _They would have money to live on.
   _They could pay their children rent.
   _The sandwich generation members might have tax deductions from
their equity loan.
   _The sandwich generation members might be able to deduct rental
property losses.
   _They also would have an investment that, if it were properly
selected, might earn an excellent return.
   None of the solutions is without risk, especially in view of
Congress' inclination to change tax laws. But for those in a very
difficult financial squeeze, they at least offer hope that the pain
will be reduced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 0038EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TreasuryBills     11-15 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Bills,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interest Rates on Short-Term Securities Hit Highest Level in Three
Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities rose in the government's latest auction to the highest
level in more than three years.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.2 billion in three-month bills at
an average discount rate of 7.82 percent on Monday, up from 7.54
percent last week. Another $7.2 billion was sold in six-month bills
at an average discount rate of 7.87 percent, up from 7.71 percent
last week.
   The rates were the highest since three-month bills sold for 7.87
percent on April 29, 1985 and six-month bills averaged 7.90 on May
13, 1985.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 8.09 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for
$9,802.30 and and 8.31 percent for six-month bills selling for
$9,602.10.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate home mortgages, rose to 8.35
percent last week after averaging 8.10 percent the week before.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 0039EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SovietGrain     11-15 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Grain,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Sale of U.S. Corn to Soviets Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private exporters have sold an additional
300,000 metric tons of American corn to the Soviet Union for
delivery in the marketing year that began Sept. 1, the Agriculture
Department has reported.
   The sale brings the total of American corn sold to the Soviets
for delivery in the 1988-89 marketing year to 4,715,600 tons, USDA
said Monday.
   The statement did not provide further details, but last week's
price of $134.50 a metric ton for grain delivered at Rotterdam would
make the sale worth about $40.3 million. A metric ton is equivalent
to 2,200 pounds.
   The Soviet Union has been buying U.S. grain in substantial
quantities despite the expiration on Sept. 30 of a five-year grain
agreement between the two countries.
   Negotiations aimed at reaching a new agreement have been going on
periodically for a year, although there have been no formal talks
since Oct. 14, when the United States rejected a Soviet proposal of
a one-year agreement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
