<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SavingsBonds     11-15 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Savings Bonds,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Savings Bond Sales Higher In October</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of U.S. Savings Bonds increased in
October for the second time in seven months, rising 5.6 percent to
$548 million, the government reports.
   The Treasury Department said Monday that sales in October were up
$29 million from September and up $132 million from October 1987, a
12.5 percent increase. Sales had fallen 10.8 percent in September
and risen 3.4 percent in August.
   Treasury officials are looking for increasing sales of savings
bonds because interest rates, starting Nov. 1 and effective through
April 30, will be 7.35 percent, up from 6.9 percent the preceding
six months.
   Since November 1982, savings bonds held five years or longer earn
market based rates. The new rate is the highest since April 30, 1985.
   As of Oct. 31, the total value of savings bonds held by Americans
was $108.5 billion, up 9 percent from a year earlier.
</TEXT>
