<DOCNO> AP881115-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 0048EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AllstateWithdrawal Bjt   11-15 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Allstate Withdrawal, Bjt,0758</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Insurance Officials React To Allstate's Plans To Pull Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts insurance officials reacted with
surprise to Allstate Insurance Co.'s decision to become the third
major insurer in two yeras to stop writing new auto insurance
policies in the state.
   ``We had no advance knowledge,'' Peter Rice, deputy Massachusetts
insurance commissioner, said Monday. ``I guess our overall
assessment is we think the company was premature in assessing the
effect of the recently passed auto reform bill on the market.''
   Allstate officials say frustration and the state's regulatory
climate prompted the company's decision, which comes amid a wave of
anger by insurers nationwide over changing regulatory climates.
   Allstate has lost $115 million in Massachusetts over the past
five years, largely as a result of the ``unique regulatory
environment'' for auto insurance, said Kevin Sullivan, director of
Allstate's Group Auto division.
   Sullivan made his comments during a news conference to announce
Allstate's decision not to renew its license when it expires June 30.
   ``We have no intention to return,'' Sullivan said.
   The announcement came about a week after a number of insurers
doing business in California promised to leave that market _ the
nation's biggest _ after voters approved a measure providing deep
cuts in auto and other insurance rates.
   Allstate will continue selling new policies and follow through on
all its Massachusetts policies until they expire, Sullivan said.
   Last week, a bill was signed into law that will reduce 1989
insurance premiums in Massachusetts by 16 percent, or $400 million,
by cracking down on fraud and abuse in the system, reducing required
coverages and limiting the number of auto cases that end up in
court. The legislation came after industry court challenges and rate
decisions increased rates by nearly one third since 1986 to among
the highest in the country.
   Allstate saw some encouraging improvements for consumers in the
bill. But Sullivan said it did little or nothing to restore free
markets to Massachusetts.
   Massachusetts state law requires all companies wishing to sell
any form of insurance in the state to participate in an open
``high-risk'' auto insurance pool.
   State law also forbids open competition for automobile insurance.
Instead, the state insurance commissioner annually calculates a
single statewide rate for each category of compulsory and optional
insurance. Only Texas has a similar system.
   Allstate, based in Northbrook, Ill., has been doing business in
Massachusetts since 1951. The company has 6.6 percent of the
Massachusetts auto insurance market and 5.2 percent of the state's
homeowners insurance market.
   Massachusetts accounts for some $199 million of Allstate's
premiums annually, or about 2 percent of the company's business in
the United States.
   Allstate has 573 full- and part-time employees at several
locations in Massachusetts. Sullivan said Allstate will ``make every
effort to try to relocate qualified employees'' and predicted there
would be few or no layoffs.
   In California, voters last week approved Proposition 103, which
mandates that property and casualty insurers roll their rates back
to a level 20 percent below those in effect on Nov. 8, 1987. In a
addition, drivers with good records would get an additional 20
percent off.
   The California Supreme Court has delayed the start of the law
while it considers its constitutionality. Sullivan said Allstate was
confident the insurers would prevail in court.
   He also said Allstate had no intention to pull out of California,
which he described as quite different from Massachusetts in that it
allows ``open competition.''
   More than 100 companies sell auto insurance in Massachusetts, but
90 percent of the coverage is written by the top 25 insurers.
Allstate ranked fourth in statewide market share.
   Allstate's departure was preceded in the past two years by Kemper
Group, Fireman's Fund Insurance Cos. and two smaller companies. All
cited millions of dollars in losses in the Massachusetts auto market
for their decisions.
   To continue writing other forms of insurance in the state, Kemper
Group recently won state regulatory and legislative approval to set
up a spinoff company to assume its auto insurance business.
   Fireman's Fund, meanwhile, agreed to pay a $45 million settlement
to the state as compensation to the high-risk drivers' pool so it
could abandon the Massachusetts market. Since reaching that
settlement last year, the company has proposed buying a subsidiary
firm with Massachusetts licenses so Fireman's Fund could re-enter
the state and sell other forms of insurance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
