<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BiotechCompetition     11-15 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biotech Competition,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Experts: U.S. Could Lose Edge in Biotech Race Without Long-Term
Planning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese companies are poised to erode the
United States' lead in the biotechnology race, partly by introducing
biotech lipstick, wine, detergent and other products that help build
grassroots support for the field, according to a panel of industry
experts.
   ``The Japanese are more unique and more innovative in the use of
biotech,'' said Akihiro Yoshikawa, a biotechnology research director
at the University of California at Berkeley. He also predicted Japan
would be the world biotechnology leader by the year 2000.
   Yoshikawa made his remarks at a news conference Monday marking
the opening of Biotech USA, a three-day industry conference and
exhibition. Participants called on American business, government and
research leaders to forge a long-term strategy _ including
government assistance _ to help the United States maintain its
competitive place in the international biotechnology market.
   Industry watchers fear history will repeat itself and the United
States will lose its lead in biotechnology as it lost the lead in
electronics and computer chip manufacturing.
   ``We have a tremendous lead, we discovered it and it's sort of
been our baby,'' said Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla.
   ``We still have time to do something if we can get our act
together,'' said Chiles, who sponsored legislation this year to
consolidate the government's role in biotechnology. ``We can do a
hell of a lot better job than we've done in some other areas. In
fact, we've got to. Other countries are not sitting still.''
   Chiles' legislation failed, but its key elements have been
implemented, he said.
   Yoshikawa joked that ``you don't want to try Japanese biotech
wine,'' but nevertheless praised Japanese companies for introducing
household products created through biotechnology.
   ``People are not afraid of trying something new,'' he said.
``That may be a key factor for Japanese success in biotechnology.''
   The wine is made with a tissue culture of the slow-growing
ginseng root that is produced in a test tube, and purple-colored
biotech lipstick is made with a tissue culture pigment rather than a
costly plant-based coloring agent, he said.
   ``Biotech companies cannot survive...without some systematic
government protections,'' Yoshikawa said, mentioning funding,
product protections and other support mechanisms.
   Japan is the leading threat to America's edge, according to
panelists who said Japanese product approval regulations and patent
laws can slow the introduction of American products in Japan.
   George Rathmann, president of AmGen, a biotech firm based in
Thousand Oaks, Calif., said government support could include
speeding up the U.S. patent process and possibly subsidizing
research.
</TEXT>
