<1ST_LINE>r f PM-DroughtInsurance Bjt   11-15 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought Insurance, Bjt,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another Look: Chubb Moves to Heal Black Eye Over Drought Insurance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chubb Corp. faced a major image problem from
a minor part of its insurance business, but the company's handling
of controversy over its drought insurance should keep its name
relatively unclouded, analysts say.
   ``They really exhibited the type of concern about the quality of
their business and their reputation,'' said Carol Manning, an
analyst at Smith Barney in New York.
   Chubb took a major step toward putting the controversy behind it
last week when it announced a $48 million settlement to a
class-action suit representing 8,000 farmers in 10 midwestern
states. Farmers had sued when applications for insurance over this
summer's drought were denied.
   U.S. District Judge Carl Rubin in Cincinnati still must approve
the settlement.
   Chubb, based in Warren, was prepared to offer $40 million in
insurance for below average rainfall. But brokers sold more than
$300 million in coverage, enraging the farmers who were denied
coverage and prompting at least seven state insurance departments to
launch proceedings against the company.
   Chubb took steps to repair the damage, including granting $11
million in goodwill payments, setting up a crisis center to answer
questions and taking out newspaper advertisements, all in advance of
last week's settlement.
   ``I think they as a company want to get this behind them'' and
``out of the press,'' said Jamie Guenther, an analyst at Duff &
Phelps Inc. of Chicago.
   ``They are a company with a sizable ego to match what is over
time a pretty darn good company,'' Guenther said. ``They have
nurtured their reputation.''
   Chubb ``bent over backwards to appease all parties involved,''
said Michael Lewis, of Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in New York.
   Weather insurance constitutes less than 1 percent of Chubb's
business. Its main lines are commercial property and casualty
insurance, and it also specializes in products such as corporate
officer liability insurance and upper-income homeowners' insurance,
said Guenther.
   Financially, costs associated with the insurance and controversy
could cost investors about 76 cents a share for 1988, Chubb has
estimated. Jeffrey Cohen, of Goldman, Sachs & Co. in New York,
expects 1988 earnings to be $8 a share, excluding one-time tax
benefits.
   Chubb earned $345 million, or $8.29 a share in 1987. It is the
nation's 16th largest property and casualty insurer, with assets of
$9.4 billion as of Sept. 30.
   Analysts said the drought insurance program was unusual partly
because Chubb had an outside managing general agent, Good Weather
International, design and handle the policy. That was a rarity for
Chubb, and unlikely to happen again, said Lewis.
   The company has said Good Weather exceeded its authority in
offering more than $40 million in insurance.
   ``I think they'll be more careful with how they (deal) with
managing general agents,'' said Ms. Manning said.
   Eventually, Lewis said, ``Wall Street will forget about (the
controversy) and concentrate on 1989 numbers.''
   Chubb is not contemplating offering a similar type of drought
insurance next year, said company spokeswoman Gail Devlin. She said
it was not appropriate to discuss plans beyond that.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
