<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Inches Up Against Yen As Share Prices Hit Another Record
High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar inched up against the Japanese yen
today while prices soared to a record high on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange for the third day in a row.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the exchange's
main index, rose 308.51 points, or 1.07 percent, to close at
28,829.41, its all-time high.
   The dollar opened at 123.60 yen and moved in a range of
123.15-123.72 yen. It closed at 123.25 yen, up 0.25 yen from
Monday's finish.
   Dealers said the dollar opened bearish, but continuous
intervention by the Bank of Japan prevented the U.S. currency from
falling.
   ``It appeared difficult to push the dollar below the 123.30 yen
level because of the intevention by the Bank of Japan,'' said a
dealer at a U.S. commercial bank in Tokyo.
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa told a news conference today
there would be cooperative intervention with other major monetary
nations in the currency market if the dollar again drops markedly.
   Another dealer with a major commercial bank said market players
were looking forward to the release of U.S. monthly trade figures
for September, scheduled for Wednesday.
   In the stock market, securities dealers said gains in
large-capital companies such as steel and heavy industry ignited the
rally across the board.
   ``Share prices are rising in an almost ideal pattern,'' said a
securities dealer at a major Japanese brokerage, who demanded
anonymity. ``Steel shares are leading the market, and when they are
resting, other shares such as financials, are taking over.''
   The previous record high for the Nikkei was Monday's close of
28,520.90, followed by Friday's finish of 28,489.57.
