<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TaxIncreases 1stLd-Writethru   11-15 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tax Increases, 1st Ld-Writethru,0669</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Anti-Tax Plan Won't Work, Budget Chief Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf pvs, Panetta said, to CORRECT ``irregardless''
to ``regardless.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The incoming chairman of the House Budget
Committee says tax increases will be needed next year to make
legally required cuts in the federal deficit, despite
President-elect George Bush's anti-tax stance.
   ``Anybody who's dealt with budget issues knows the size of the
challenge is too large to exempt any areas,'' Rep. Leon Panetta,
D-Calif., said in an interview. ``Once you say this area won't be
considered, you paint yourself into a corner.''
   Panetta said new revenues will have to be part of any package for
the required reduction of red ink by tens of billions of dollars,
regardless of Bush's oft-repeated campaign pledge ``no new taxes.''
   Under the Gramm-Rudman balanced budget law, the deficit for the
1990 fiscal year _ which begins Oct. 1 _ is not to exceed $100
billion.
   Last week, just two days after Bush was elected, the Reagan
administration's Office of Management and Budget raised its 1990
deficit estimate to $132 billion. Panetta said he believes the
shortfall will be even higher _ closer to $140 billion or $150
billion.
   If the deficit target is exceeded, the law requires automatic
spending cuts to pare the red ink to $100 billion.
   Panetta said Bush's well-known ``read my lips'' promise to oppose
tax increases ``create a potential for confrontation'' between
Democrats and Republicans.
   ``Republicans will feel a commitment was made that can't be
breached in any way, and Democrats will say why should we vote for a
tax increase if he has made that commitment,'' Panetta said.
   Panetta, who takes over the budget panel when lawmakers return in
January, said he believes Bush's willingness to compromise will be
apparent when he submits his first budget to Congress, perhaps in
February or March. President Reagan will present his final budget to
Congress on Jan. 9, but lame duck presidents' final budgets can be
rewritten by their successors.
   ``If Reagan submits his budget proposal and if it reflects the
same Reagan priorities that he's submitted time and time again, that
have been declared dead on arrival, and if Bush replays those same
priorities, that will be a signal that we're in for more
confrontation on the budget issue,'' Panetta said.
   Panetta said he hopes Bush will begin seeking congressional input
early on so his spending plan reflects agreements with Capitol Hill
on taxes.
   ``If not, I suspect we'll be fighting tooth and nail to see what
can be done,'' he said.
   On the campaign trail, Bush proposed a ``flexible freeze'' plan
for balancing the budget. Under the proposal, overall government
spending would be allowed to keep up with inflation, with cuts in
some programs and increases for others. He never provided any
specifics, however.
   Panetta said that with Bush insisting he will not slash large
chunks of the budget _ such as defense and Social Security _ there
simply will not be enough vulnerable programs left to yield sizable
savings from spending cuts.
   ``I've looked at that thing in a dozen different ways and don't
see how it works,'' Panetta said of the flexible freeze plan.
   Panetta said he believes Bush has not yet made it politically
impossible for himself to agree to tax increases. He said that just
as Reagan agreed to several tax increases despite his anti-tax
rhetoric, Bush could shift his position.
   ``The president will have to say to the American people that
we're facing a major crisis in dealing with the deficit, and the
only way to meet the challenge is to sit down and work out a package
with Congress,'' Panetta said.
   Rep. William H. Gray III, D-Pa., is stepping down after four
years as budget committee chairman. Under House rules, a lawmaker
can only head the budget panel for four years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 0834EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Pepperell Bjt   11-15 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pepperell, Bjt,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Blocks West Point-Pepperell's Defense Against Farley
Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officers of West Point-Pepperell Inc., denied the
use of their ``poison pill'' takeover defense, will have to come up
with another way to battle a $1.4 billion buyout bid from Farley Inc.
   U.S. District Judge G. Ernest Tidwell granted a temporary
injunction Monday blocking the Georgia-based textile maker from
using the pill against Farley's $48-a-share takeover attempt. The
judge also refused to grant Pepperell two preliminary injunctions it
sought against Farley.
   Pepperell spokesman Donald Downs said the company plans to appeal
Tidwell's ruling and declined further comment.
   Pepperell now must fight more aggressively to overcome the bid,
said Deborah Bronston, an analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc. in New York.
   The ruling ``weakens their case, and it becomes incumbent upon
West Point Pepperell managers to come up with their own offer,'' she
said.
   That offer to stockholders could include a leveraged buyout of
the company, a restructuring that would include the sale of
Pepperell assets or a ``white knight'' that would make a friendly
counter offer for ownership of the company, Ms. Bronston said.
   The West Point-based diversified manufacturer of consumer soft
goods including Arrow shirts and Martex towels sought to protect
itself against a possible takeover by Chicago-based Farley, which
owns 2.87 million shares, or 9.8 percent, of Pepperell stock.
   Farley, a maker of clothing, including Fruit of the Loom
underwear, and precision metal products, announced its attempt to
buy Pepperell May 23.
   Farley's offer is based on 16.73 million shares being tendered,
and other conditions, and expires at midnight EST, Nov. 21.
   Pepperell stock closed Monday on the New York Stock Exchange at
$42 per share, down 87{ cents.
   Pepperell's board created the pill in October 1987 to protect
itself against a possible hostile takeover. The pill allowed
stockholders not involved in a takeover attempt to purchase
additional shares, which would sharply increase the cost of a buyout.
   In response to suits by both corporations against each other and
other defendants over the plan, Tidwell voided the rights agreement.
   ``The court finds no authority in either the state law or West
Point's Articles of Incorporation which authorize the rights plan,''
Tidwell wrote. He said the plan discriminated among shareholders
because some were given rights not allowed others in a takeover
attempt.
   William F. Farley, chairman of the company seeking to take over
Pepperell, said, ``We are pleased by the court's ruling and believe
that it will facilitate the successful completion of our offer.''
   ``In light of the court's decision, we believe that the West
Point board should recommend the acceptance of our offer, which is a
full and fair one.''
   Pepperell had countersued Farley and asked for preliminary
injunctions against the takeover on two grounds: that the company
violated a ``standstill agreement'' executed when Pepperell acquired
textile maker J.P. Stevens & Co. Inc. in March and that Farley's
proposed financing package violated federal margin regulations.
   Another defendant in Pepperell's suit was Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc., a New York-based financial services corporation which was
involved in the dismantling of J.P. Stevens. The standstill
agreement approved March 13 specified that none of the parties
involved would assist or encourage any attempt to acquire Stevens,
which Pepperell now owns.
   The suit claimed Drexel was providing assistance to Farley in the
takeover attempt in violation of the agreement.
   Tidwell ruled that neither Drexel nor Farley were parties to the
standstill agreement and, among other things, ``there has been no
showing that either Drexel, or derivatively, Farley, used any
confidential information obtained by Drexel'' in connection with the
buyout of Stevens in the Pepperell takeover attempt.
   Tidwell conceded ``the showing made by West Point indicates that
Farley's financing is substantially suspect and may be a violation
of the margin requirements,'' but ruled ``Farley has adequately
disclosed the potential effect of the alleged margin violations''
and denied the request for an injunction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
