<DOCNO> AP881115-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1005EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Quasar-Discrimination     11-15 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quasar-Discrimination,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quasar Must Pay $3.8 Million in Discrimination Case: Attorneys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury has awarded $3.8 million to three
former Quasar Co. employees, all over 50, who were fired and whose
duties were transferred to younger men, their attorneys say.
   A federal jury Monday awarded $1.9 million _ between $508,000 and
$713,000 to each man _ but the total amount was being doubled to
$3.8 million because the jury found the discrimination was willful,
the attorneys said.
   Quasar, a sales subsidiary of Japanese-owned Matsushita Electric
Corp. of Paramus, N.J., dismissed John Fortino, Carl Meyers and F.
William Schulz during a 1986 company restructuring that affected
approximately 200 workers in Franklin Park.
   Attorney Steven L. Bashwiner, who represented Quasar, declined to
comment on the verdict.
   ``There were several tip-offs that discrimination might be a part
of the picture,'' said plaintiff attorney Norman Berger. ``The
company continued to hire new people. The vast majority of them were
very young, under 40.
   ``They told our clients that their jobs were being eliminated,
but they reassigned those functions to younger people,'' he said.
   Fortino, 58, had been assistant general manager of the
advertising and sales promotion department at Quasar's Franklin Park
facility since March 1979. He was awarded $508,857, or $1.01 million
when doubled.
   Meyers, 53, was a nine-year employee and manager of sales
administration at the site. He receives $728,223, or $1.45 million
when doubled.
   Schulz, 54, had worked for Quasar and its former owner, Motorola
Inc., since 1957. When he was forced to leave, he was national
manager of physical distribution. He was awarded $713,908 or $1.42
million.
   The jury rejected a claim made by a fourth former worker, Sophie
Mustachio of Franklin Park.
</TEXT>
