<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Met Extends $60-Per-Share Offer for Pillsbury</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC today extended for the
third time its $5.23 billion offer for Pillsbury Co., saying that
79.1 percent of Pillsbury stock now has been tendered to the British
conglomerate.
   The $60-per-share takeover offer, which was to expire Monday
night, was extended until Nov. 18.
   Grand Met said that as of the Monday night deadline, nearly 67.6
million shares of Pillsbury common stock, representing approximately
79.1 percent of the outstanding shares, had been tendered and not
withdrawn.
   When it extended its second deadline of Nov. 8, Grand Met
reported that about 74.3 percent of Pillsbury outstanding shares had
been tendered.
   Pillsbury spokesman Larry Haeg said today the Minneapolis-based
food and restaurant company would have no comment on the latest
extension.
   On Oct. 4, Grand Met undertook one of the biggest hostile
takeover attempts on a company with its offer for Pillsbury.
   Pillsbury later announced a restructuring that included spinning
off its Burger King Corp. subsidiary as an independent company.
   Pillsbury and Grand Met also have been skirmishing in court over
the validity of Pillsbury's ``poison pill'' takeover defense, which
would make a hostile acquisition prohibitively expensive.
   Grand Met said Friday a Delaware judge had requested briefs by
Monday from both sides on new motions in the British firm's suit to
quash the pill.
   Meanwhile, the British company's chief of U.S. operations, Ian A.
Martin, said he was taking seriously rumors that a group of
unidentified investors were seeking buyers for all or parts of the
London-based distilling, gambling and franchise conglomerate.
   Martin said one of the potential participants might be Pillsbury.
   Part of the reason Grand Metropolitan might be considered an
attractive takeover target is the difference between its stock price
of about $8 a share and its estimated breakup value of between
$12.50 and $18 a share.
   That degree of discrepancy can invite takeover bids by investors
who hope to profit by selling pieces of a target company.
</TEXT>
