<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Beazer     11-15 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Beazer,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beazer Buying Out Deal Partners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British industrialist Brian Beazer announced a
refinancing plan that eliminates one of the most contentious issues
in his hostile $1.8 billion takeover of Koppers Co.
   Beazer's company, Beazer PLC, plans to acquire the interests of
its partners, Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. and National Westminster
Bank PLC, in BNS Inc. BNS is the shell company formed to launch the
takeover last June.
   The partners are to be bought out by the end of February, Matthew
Thorne, Beazer's group investment director, said Monday.
   In a separate development Tuesday, Beazer announced from Bath,
England, that it has conditionally agreed to sell Koppers' Wolman
division, a leading supplier of timber treatment products and
services, to Hickson International PLC for $67.5 million in cash.
   The deal depends on approval by the Hickson shareholders and
regulatory clearance. It is part of the ongoing program for disposal
of the Koppers chemicals operations.
   Shearson Lehman's ownership of the takeover company BNS was
criticized by Koppers and the Pittsburgh-based company's allies as a
dangerous precedent in which an investment bank was in effect
helping take over a company.
   BNS would then be disbanded, and Beazer would become fully
responsible for debt incurred in the Koppers takeover.
   Shearson owns 46.1 percent of BNS, and a National Westminster
subsidiary, County NatWest Ltd., owns 4.9 percent. Beazer owns 49
percent.
   The transfers are part of a refinancing in which a consortium led
by Citibank will lend Beazer $2.3 billion.
   About $1.3 billion of that will refinance debt from the takeover
and $570 million will substitute for money Beazer planned to raise
by selling high-yield junk bonds, the British company said in a
letter to shareholders. By not issuing the bonds, Beazer expects to
save $25 million in interest expense.
   The remaining $400 million will be temporary financing to be
repaid by future sales from Koppers' chemical operations.
</TEXT>
