<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Mostly Lower In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures were mostly lower in
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting
disappointment about the size of corn sales to the Soviet Union and
a weakening technical picture.
   The corn market registered little excitement about the Soviet
Union's purchase of 300,000 metric tons of U.S. corn. The
Agriculture Department announced the sale late Monday after the corn
market already had closed higher on rumors the Soviets had bought as
much as 2 million metric tons of corn, analysts said.
   Wheat prices were narrowly mixed this morning while soybeans were
under pressure due to weakening chart signals, which prompted one
independent trader to unload a large amount of futures contracts.
   ``The beans are acting pretty well as far I'm concened,
especially with someone pounding on them like that,'' said John
Frazier, a grain market specialist with Balfour Maclaine Corp. in
Chicago.
   In early trading, wheat was 1\ cents lower to 2 cents higher with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.19{ a bushel; corn was 1
cent to 1} cents lower with December at $2.70\ a bushel; oats were \
cent to 1\ cents lower with December at $2.12{ a bushel; and
soybeans were unchanged to 3{ cents lower with November at $7.55{ a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .33 cent to .70 cent higher with December at
72.95 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .53 cent higher
with November at 81.75 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent lower
to .35 cent higher with December at 41.02 cents a pound; and frozen
pork bellies were .33 cent to .38 cent higher with February at 45.10
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mostly lower on Monday while pork futures
were mostly higher.
  
