<1ST_LINE>u f PM-RamadaRestructuring 1stLd-Writethru   11-15 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ramada Restructuring, 1st Ld-Writethru,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ramada Details Planned Sale of Hotel, Restaurant Properties</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 12th graf pvs, The information ... to provide new income
projections provided by Ramada. Picks up 13th graf pvs, ``Ramada
reported ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ramada Inc. shareholders will get cash payments of
$7 per share under a restructuring that will see the sale of the
company's Ramada and Rodeway hotel businesses and its restaurant
operations.
   In a statement mailed Monday to its shareholders, Ramada provided
details of a plan it announced in October to thwart a proposed
buy-out by the company's biggest stockholder, the Pritzker family of
Chicago.
   After completing the restructuring, Ramada will be left with its
casino operations in Nevada and New Jersey, which already provide a
major share of its operating revenue.
   ``The purpose of the plan is to enable you to realize a near-term
return on your investment and provide you with a continuing stake in
Ramada's profitable gaming business,'' said Richard Snell, Ramada
board chairman, in a letter accompanying the statement to
stockholders.
   Ramada stock closed down 37{ cents a share to $8.87{ in composite
New York Stock Exchange trading on Monday.
   Jay Pritzker, president of HCC Corp., an affiliate of the
Pritzkers' Hyatt hotel chain, offered $10 a share for Ramada in
early September. Ramada rejected the $368 million offer as unfair to
shareholders.
   ``It is our firm conviction that a sale of control of the company
at this time is not in the best interests of the company, its
shareholders and other affected constituents,'' Snell said.
   Ramada operates TropWorld Casino and Entertainment Resort in
Atlantic City, the Tropicana Resort and Casino in Las Vegas, Ramada
Express in Laughlin and Eddie's Fabulous '50s in Reno, Nev.
   ``We have been successful in our efforts to establish the company
as an innovative and efficient operator in the gaming industry,''
Snell told shareholders. ``Our strategy has been to provide
something more than gambling. The product we strive to offer to
customers is a complete entertainment experience in a gaming
environment.''
   Al Glasgow, a gaming analyst based in Atlantic City, said the
casinos had attracted Pritzker's attention.
   ``Mr. Pritzker wouldn't have chased Ramada a few years ago, when
it was a neophyte in the casino industry,'' Glasgow said. ``He's
chasing it today because it's matured into a pretty nice-looking
product.''
   The information statement mailed to shareholders Monday projects
operating income from the Atlantic City properties at $48.5 million
in 1989 and $74.5 million by 1991. Operating income from the Nevada
properties was projected at $29.6 million next year and $42.2
million in 1991. Net income was projected by the company at $9.4
million in 1989, $21.5 million in 1990 and $36.8 million in 1991.
   Ramada reported overall net earnings of $4.4 million during the
first nine months of 1988, including a net loss of $2.6 million for
the hotel and restaurant operations. The four gaming facilities
posted a profit of $7.6 million through September, the company said.
   Ramada owns Marie Callender's restaurants and owns, operates,
franchises or has under contract more than 800 hotels under the
Ramada and Rodeway brand names.
   But Snell said Ramada remained optimistic about the long-term
prospects for the hotel and restaurant groups.
   ``We feel confident that they will be attractive to prospective
purchasers,'' he said. ``Both have well-recognized and established
brand names and room in their markets for long-term growth.''
</TEXT>
