<1ST_LINE>a f BC-DegradableTrashBags Adv19-20   11-15 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Degradable Trash Bags, Adv 19-20,0738</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 19</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Nov. 19-20 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Poly-Tech Presents a Bag as Degradable as the Trash</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the makers of Ruffies are accurate in their
view of America, making gains in the garbage bag business is a
matter of appealing to the nation's conscience.
   Poly-Tech Inc., of Bloomington, Minn., is launching a line of
degradable plastic trash bags with hopes that U.S. households will
pay a little extra for Ruffies knowing they have the potential to
turn to dust.
   ``We've gotten just a tremendous response,'' said Robert
Doernbach, chairman and chief executive officer of Poly-Tech, a
company founded in 1958 by flamboyant philanthropist Percy Ross, who
sold out in 1969. ``It's going to be interesting to see if people
will go out and buy those products.''
   It's not the first time degradable garbage bags have been
marketed, but Doernbach says Ruffies is the first nationally
advertised brand to make the move.
   ``On their part it's smart marketing,'' said Frank Rolfes, a
securities analyst for Dain Bosworth Inc. of Minneapolis. ``I think
people like to do the environmentally right thing.''
   By adding photo-sensitive material to the plastic compound, the
bags break down when they are exposed to ultraviolet light from the
sun. Once the chain reaction begins, the bags eventually are reduced
to a fine powder, the company says. The bags will completely degrade
in about three months in direct sunlight, the company says.
   But there's a catch. Doernbach said bags must be exposed to the
sun a minimum of about seven days for the breakdown process to begin
_ give or take a few days depending on seasons and the bag's
distance from the equator.
   Given the dark nature of landfills, ``most bags won't degrade
with the way they are normally used,'' Rolfes said.
   Still, degradable bags are helpful in the fight against litter
and even the darkest landfill can't stop the degrading process of a
bag once it starts, Doernbach said.
   The technology will add about a dime to the retail cost of a
package of 30 tall kitchen container-sized bags, which vary in price
from $1.99 to $2.69 depending on where they are sold.
   ``Hopefully, there's some profit there, but it's not a wildly
profitable thing,'' Doernbach said.
   Ruffies, with about 400 employees in Bloomington, Denver and
Battleboro, N.C., controls about 8 percent of the total U.S.
consumer trash bag market while its two other national competitors _
Glad and Hefty _ each has about a 30 percent share, Doernbach said.
   Poly-Tech posted $71.8 million in revenues in 1987 but earned
just $472,000. Rolfes said the degradable bags could give Poly-Tech
a small sales edge in some locations, but not enough to make a
``night-and-day difference'' because the product could easily be
duplicated by competitors if it skyrockets.
   Rick Tanner, product manager for Glad trash bags in Danbury,
Conn., said he's neither surprised nor worried about the change in
Ruffies.
   ``This is not a hot button with consumers,'' Tanner said.
``(Poly-Tech) is responding to special interests.''
   Tanner and Allen Gray, a spokesman for Mobil Corp., which makes
Hefty bags, said it's a waste of time and resources to make garbage
bags degradable.
   ``The degrading process takes far, far too long to create extra
space in landfills,'' Gray said. ``The money is much better spent on
real solutions to the problems.''
   Although plastics only account for an estimated 7.2 percent of
the country's solid waste as measured by weight, many experts
believe plastics pose a much greater problem than the figures reveal
because they are so light.
   About 9.6 million tons of plastic were discarded in the United
States in 1984 and the volume is expected to increase 9.8 percent to
15.5 tons by 1990.
   Recycling, garbage incineration and reducing the stream of solid
waste are environmental causes more worthy of corporate concern,
Gray said.
   ``It's a matter of taking care of the volume that we generate and
reducing that volume,'' he said.
   Still, Hefty will be keeping an eye on Ruffies sales to see what
consumers want.
   ``Mobil's position has been, if the market demands that the bags
be made biodegradable we'll do it,'' Gray said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Nov. 19-20</NOTE>
</DOC>
