<HEAD>Bipartisan Commission Chairman Says Gasoline Tax Hike Possible</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The co-chairman of the National Economic
Commission told oil industry executives Tuesday that an increase in
the gasoline tax could become a reality under the new administration.
   Robert S. Strauss, a prominent Texas Democrat, said a new tax on
gasoline had been discussed as one possible way to help reduce the
federal government's huge budget deficit.
   ``A great many experts feel ... that if indeed additional revenue
is needed ... that a gas tax or a broad-based energy tax is
something the government should look at very strongly,'' Strauss
told some 1,500 participants at the closing session of the American
Petroleum Institute's annual meeting.
   However, Strauss declined to say whether he had or would
recommend a new gasoline tax to the commission, a bipartisan body
formed to make recommendations on reducing the budget deficit.
   During the three-day meeting, industry leaders have spoken out
against new taxes, arguing that the oil industry is the most heavily
taxed in the nation.
   Amoco Corp. Chairman Richard M. Morrow has called the retail
gasoline tax the ``single most regressive form of taxation,'' one
that would tax the low income most heavily and have a harmful
regional impact.
   Morrow, who also is chairman of the trade group, said Tuesday
that while President-elect George Bush had promised not tol
resources, it is more environmentally acceptable than other fossil
fuels _ and particularly so in addressing such concerns as ozone,
acid rain and the greenhouse effect,'' Morrow said.
</TEXT>
