<1ST_LINE>u f PM-AirFares 2ndLd-Writethru   11-15 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Air Fares, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Major Carriers Put Off End to Short-term Advance Fare Discounts</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf to clarify and UPDATE with Continental also
extending; picks up 4th graf pvs bg'ng, ``Other carriers ...;
^By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Major U.S. airlines have put off for another week the elimination
of a popular category of discount air fares, the so-called ``junk
fare'' used by major business travelers.
   The cuts, which represented an industrywide restructuring of
discount fare programs, had been scheduled to take place today.
   But officials of several carriers said today they had decided to
extend the deadline to Nov. 22. Continental Airlines, which
initiated last Friday the move to eliminate the fares, has extended
them for the same period, according to travel agents. Continental
spokesmen were unavailable for comment today.
   ``Other carriers made that move and we simply matched it,'' said
Al Becker, a spokesman for Dallas-based American.
   Becker said he could not provide an explanation for the
postponement. However, the New York Times reported today one reason
for the change was that some carriers, including Trans World
Airlines, had not yet put the new fares into effect.
   ``I think all the airlines are watching each other,'' said United
spokeswoman Sara Dornacker.
   Bob Gibbons, a spokesman for Northwest Airlines, said the airline
had joined in the delay because of confusion among passengers and
travel agents over elimination of the discount fare.
   ``I think passengers became confused and travel agents and we
wanted to give time for them to sort these issues out,'' Gibbons
said.
   The fare changes involve the discontinuation of most three- to
seven-day advance-purchase fares.
   Besides having the relatively short advance-purchase requirements
the so-called junk fares often did not require a traveler to stay at
the destination on a Saturday night. They also were between 10
percent to 35 percent below full coach fare.
</TEXT>
