<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1338EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-BritishAirways     11-15 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-British Airways,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Airways' Profit Down 2 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Airways PLC reported that its profit
declined 2 percent in its second quarter as its 1987 acquisition of
British Caledonian Airways continued to reduce earnings.
   Britain's largest airline said Tuesday that its net profit in the
three months ended Sept. 30 fell to 91 million pounds, or around
$165 million, from 93 million pounds, or $168 million, a year
earlier. Per-share earnings slipped to 12.6 pence, or 23 cents, from
12.9 pence, or 23 cents at prevailing exchange rates.
   The decline occurred despite a 12 percent rise in second-quarter
revenue, to 1.19 billion pounds, or $2.2 billion, from 1.06 billion
pounds, or $1.9 billion.
   The latest quarterly results for the airline were in line with
most analysts' forecasts.
   In the first six months of its fiscal year, British Airways'
profit fell 5 percent to 144 million pounds, or $261 million, from
151 million pounds, or $273 million. Per-share earnings declined to
20 pence, or 36 cents, from 20.9 pence, or 38 cents.
   Half-year revenue rose 13 percent to 2.21 billion pounds, or $4
billion, from 1.96 billion pounds, or $3.5 billion.
   Results for the former British Caledonian operations, acquired by
British Airways last year for 253 million pounds, or $458 million,
were included in the figures for the current fiscal year but not in
those of the previous year.
   British Airways Chairman Lord King said second-quarter results
from most market segments were satisfactory but that there was a
disappointing performance from European and British operations.
   ``The winter months are our most vulnerable period,'' he said.
``However, present (passenger) traffic levels remain high for this
time of year and our forward bookings are ahead of last year.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1342EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f AM-CircuitBreakers     11-15 0155</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Circuit Breakers,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Siemens Offers To Inspect, Fix Circuit Breaker Boxes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The maker of I-T-E circuit breaker boxes is
offering to inspect and repair, if necessary, breaker boxes which
could overheat and malfunction, the Consumer Product Safety
Commission announced Tuesday.
   According to the manufacturer, Siemens Energy and Automation Inc.
of Alpharetta, Ga., some of the breaker boxes were made with
incorrect components.
   The I-T-E circuit breaker boxes, or ``load centers,'' can be
identified by the five-digit code marked on top of the wiring
diagram label inside the door. Those in question are:
   H2586-H3186, made Aug. 25-31, 1986.
   J0186-J30-86, made Sept. 1-30, 1986.
   K0186-K2486, made Oct. 1-24, 1986.
   If the wiring diagram has a sticker labeled ``inspected lugs,''
it already has been checked and corrected if necessary, Siemens
reported. Anyone finding boxes with the codes in question but
without the inspected sticker should contact Siemens at
1-800-334-2982 or the Safety Commission, 1-800-638-2772.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
