<DOCNO> AP881115-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1415EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     11-15 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0357</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were mixed today in a light session
that reflected investor reluctance to participate ahead of the
government's potentially market-moving monthly trade report.
   ``The real focus is on the trade numbers tomorrow,'' said Peter
J. DaPuzzo, manager of retail equities at Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc. in New York. ``We won't see anything more clearly until after
those numbers come out.''
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had lost 62.41
points over the previous four sessions, was up 6.58 to 2,071.66 by 2
p.m. EST.
   Among broader market indicators, the New York Stock Exchange
composite index of all listed issues fell 0.19 to 151.23. The
American Stock Exchange's market-value index fell 0.05 to 289.35.
   Declining issues slightly outnumbered advances on the NYSE, with
696 down, 628 up and 571 unchanged. Volume on the Big Board totaled
76.89 million shares with two hours of trading left.
   Wall Street strategists said the market remains preoccupied with
the weak dollar and fear of higher interest rates, which hurt stocks
in the aftermath of Vice President George Bush's presidential
election victory a week ago.
   If the Commerce Department report on the September merchandise
trade deficit is substantially above the expectations of a $10.5
billion shortfall, many investment professionals expect the market
to weaken because it will likely mean the dollar will fall sharply.
   They said government reports today that showed higher retail
sales and industrial production in October, suggesting economic
strength, had little effect on the stock market although they
implied higher inflation and hence higher interest rates in the
future.
   The most-active NYSE issues included Prime Computer, which jumped
1~ to 17} on volume exceeding 1.7 million shares. New York investor
Bennett LeBow said he wanted to buy the company for $20 a share.
   J.C. Penney rose 1 to 53 after the retailer said third-quarter
earnings improved slightly from a year earlier.
   Among blue chip stocks, IBM rose ] to 117{; International Paper
fell | to 43{ and Eastman Kodak rose } to 44}.
</TEXT>
