<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   11-15 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures End Sharply Lower On Late Sell-Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly lower
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade as a late round of speculative
selling sent soybean and corn prices down sharply.
   Prices were weak throughout the session amid bearish chart
signals and disappointment over the relatively slow pace of grain
exports.
   The Agriculture Department's announcement late Monday of a
300,000-metric-ton corn sale to the Soviet Union failed to rally the
corn market, which was expecting a Soviet corn purchase of up to 2
million metric tons.
   Jerry Zusel, manager of CBOT floor operations for Balfour
Maclaine Corp. in Chicago, said most of the selling was done by
speculators while the outnumbered buyers were largely commercial
traders.
   ``There's just not enough cash business right now to support
these price levels,'' Zusel said. ``And if you can't go up, you've
got to go down.''
   At the close, wheat was 5\ cents lower to 2 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.15{ a bushel; corn was 1
cent to 5\ cents lower with December at $2.66\ a bushel; oats were 3
cents lower to { cent higher with December at $2.10} a bushel; and
soybeans were 4 cents to 16 cents lower with November at $7.43 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
