<1ST_LINE>u f AM-OilPrices     11-15 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Prices,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Decline In Dull Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices drifted lower Tuesday in dull,
directionless trading, reversing the gains of the previous session.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the December contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil,
declined 37 cents to settle at $13.90 a barrel, after rising 32
cents on Monday.
   Other contract months also lost ground.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange, the
December contract for unleaded gasoline settled at 46.96 cents, down
1.20 cents. The contract had risen 1.51 cents Monday.
   The December contract for wholesale home heating oil, which rose
0.62 cent in the previous session, fell 0.23 cent to settle at 44.40
cents.
   William Byers, senior energy analyst for Bear, Stearns & Co.,
said technical factors dominated trading in the absence of any
market-moving news.
   ``It was so dull, incredibly quiet. There was nothing to say
about the market,'' he said.
   Many traders were attending the American Petroleum Institute's
annual convention in New York while those who remained at their
desks stayed on the sidelines in advance of upcoming OPEC meetings.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries was scheduled
hold pricing and strategy committee meetings on Thursday followed by
a full meeting of all 13 ministers next Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1911EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SmallBusiness-Poll     11-15 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Small Business-Poll,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polls Finds Budget Gap Biggest Concern of Small Businesses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A majority of the nation's small-business owners
believe the federal budget deficit is the No. 1 issue facing
President-elect George Bush, and they favor spending cuts to reduce
the shortfall, a poll said Tuesday.
   The 21,000 entreprenuers responding to Arthur Anderson & Co.'s
third annual Small Business Survey also expressed general optimism
about the economic outlook despite the lingering budgetary problems.
   Two-thirds of those polled said the deficit was the most pressing
issue of the day. Forty-five percent listed tax rates, 26 percent
domestic programs, 25 percent foreign policy and 15 percent defense
spending.
   The respondents were asked to pick the two most important
political issues facing the incoming administration.
   Spending cuts were picked by 55 percent of those surveyed as the
best solution to the deficit problem, while 44 percent favored both
spending cuts and increased taxes.
   ``Emerging and owner-managed businesses appear to see taxes as
both a concern and a reality,'' said James P. O'Halloran, an Arthur
Anderson partner.
   ``To reduce our deficit, most small businesses prefer a reduction
in spending by cutting defense spending, welfare and foreign aid.''
   As far as the economy was concerned, 60 percent of the
respondents predicted they would record at least a 5 percent gain in
sales in the upcoming year, with 35 percent foresaw an increase of
more than 10 percent.
   Three-fourths estimated profits would stay the same or increase
over last year.
   ``In past studies, the executives' predictions have been right on
target because they are aware of their competitive environment and
the pressures facing small business, and are committed to setting
and reaching optimistic goals,'' O'Halloran said.
   Arthur Anderson, based in Chicago, is one of the world's largest
accounting and tax consultants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1620EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     11-15 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0201</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices creaked to a mixed finish today in a
particularly slow session, reflecting widespread reluctance to
participate ahead of the government's potentially market-jolting
monthly trade report.
   ``The only thing I've noticed is nothing's happened,'' said
Edward P. Nicoski, a technical analyst at Piper Jaffray & Hopwood
Inc., a Minneapolis-based investment firm. ``Everybody's just
waiting to see what those numbers are going to do.''
   The Commerce Department is due to report the September
merchandise trade balance Wednesday morning and most expectations
are for a $10.5 billion shortfall. If the deficit exceeds that
amount, some fear it could trigger a selloff in the dollar, stock
and bond markets.
   The trade statistics vary widely from month to month but remain
one of the most sensitive market movers. That's largely because the
huge trade deficits the United States has been racking up over the
past several years are seen by many economists as a reflection of
eroding economic might.
   Wall Street strategists said other figures released today that
showed higher retail sales and industrial production in October
caused little reaction in the market.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
