<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1939EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Retail     11-15 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Retail,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dayton Hudson Reports Third-Quarter Earnings Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   J.C. Penney Co. Inc. said Tuesday its third-quarter earnings
declined 6.7 percent, while Dayton Hudson Corp. said its income rose
35 percent during the period and Carter Hawley Hale Stores Inc.
reported a 5.6 percent earnings gain for its first quarter.
   Penney said its third-quarter earnings declined to $160 million
from $171 million in the same period a year earlier. Penney's
per-share earnings increased to $1.17 from $1.14 as it had 13
percent fewer shares outstanding in the latest quarter.
   Penney attributed some of the earnings decline to accounting
changes.
   The company said its revenue totaled $3.61 billion, down from
$3.76 billion a year earlier.
   The retail industry has been struggling through a slump that
began in February 1987. Some companies, like Penney, are still
showing profit declines. Other companies have showed earnings gains,
but securities analysts caution that the results, when compared with
last year's depressed numbers, may look stronger than they really
are.
   Dayton Hudson said it earned $45.6 million, or 54 cents per
share, in the quarter ended Oct. 29, up from $33.6 million, or 34
cents per share, in the comparable period a year ago.
   Third-quarter revenue increased to $2.87 billion from $2.54
billion for the same period in 1987.
   Kenneth A. Macke, chairman and chief executive officer of Dayton
Hudson, said sales at its Mervyn's department stores strengthened
during the quarter because of improved inventory content.
   Mervyn's has been a trouble spot for Dayton Hudson in the past.
   The company also owns Dayton's and Hudson's department stores and
Target discount stores.
   Carter Hawley Hale said it had earnings of $11.3 million, or 52
cents a share, during its first quarter, compared with $10.7
million, or 49 cents per share in the same period a year ago.
   Carter Hawley Hale said it had a $4 million operating loss in the
latest quarter.
   The company, parent of the Broadway, Emporium Capwell,
Thalheimers and Weinstock's department stores, said sales were
$636.7 million in the quarter, up from $610.6 million in the same
period a year earlier.
   For the first nine months of the year, Penney said it earned $372
million, or $2.74 per share, compared with $328 million, or $2.18 a
share, in the comparable 1987 period. The 1987 results included a
$140 million pre-tax charge for the relocation of Penney
headquarters to Dallas from New York.
   Revenue during the period totaled $10 billion, down from $10.39
billion.
   Dayton Hudson's net earnings for the nine months were $104.9
million, or $1.24 per share, compared with $94.7 million, or 97
cents per share, a year earlier.
   Revenue for the first nine months increased to $8.1 billion from
$7 billion a year ago.
</TEXT>
