<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 1940EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-API     11-15 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-API,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Industry Facing Serious Energy Problems, Study Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Falling energy prices and rising profits at many
oil companies are concealing more serious industrywide problems that
a national energy policy must address, the American Petroleum
Institute said Tuesday.
   ``The truth is that the state of the nation's energy health today
is perceived as `good' only because enough inexpensive foreign oil
is available,'' the industry's main trade group said in a report.
``Our condition could turn to `poor' or `critical' if that supply
were disrupted ....''
   The report, ``Energy Security White Paper: U.S. Decisions and
Global Trends,'' was issued during the group's annual meeting.
   The survival of domestic exploration and production is in
question as lower crude prices discourage investment in new oil
development, the report said.
   Dependence on foreign oil, primarily from the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries, has increased U.S. vulnerability to
the dangers of a supply disruption and price volatility, it said.
   Despite recent huge quarterly profits by major oil companies, the
gains came in ``downstream'' sectors such as refining and chemical
manufacturing, said Charles J. DiBona, president of the trade group.
But the favorable earnings were offset at least partly by losses in
``upstream'' _ production and exploration operations _ stemming from
low crude prices.
   The paper calls for a national energy policy to ensure an
adequate and secure supply of oil at reasonable prices while
reducing vulnerability to a future oil crisis.
   The report does not specifically call for tax incentives to help
offset the crude prices, but contends correct ``government
decisions'' could increase domestic oil supply by 2 million barrels
a day by the end of the 1990s.
   Only 921 oil rigs are working in the United States, compared with
about 1,000 a year ago and 4,000 in 1981, the group noted. Those
rigs are producing approximately 8 million barrels of oil a day and
output is falling 3 percent a year while demand is rising about 2
percent annually, the report said.
   Consequently, foreign imports have soared to 43 percent from 31
percent just three years ago and some economists predict that in
five years the United States may be importing half of its oil.
   The report said dependence on foreign supplies, primarily from
the Middle East, increased U.S. vulnerability to a supply disruption.
   With demand increasing rapidly, the current glut of oil on world
markets could dry up in the 1990s, the report said.
   ``Then any number of unpredictable developments around the
Persian Gulf could directly, swiftly and critically affect oil
supply,'' the paper said.
   In addition, another steep plunge in oil prices, like that which
occurred in 1986, threatens the survival of smaller oil companies,
damages the economies of oil states dependent on the industry for
revenue and ``hurts the country's long-term energy security,'' the
report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
