<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged downward Tuesday in
uncertain trading in advance of Wednesday's report on the nation's
merchandise trade deficit for the month of September.
   Gold prices rose. Republic National Bank of New York said gold
bullion was bid at $423.00 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up from
$422.85 late Monday.
   Forecasts of the trade deficit ranged widely from $9 billion to
$11 billion. Traders said any number above the range would be likely
to drive the dollar lower, while a figure below the range probably
would spark a rally.
   ``Eight or 12 (billion dollars) is clearly going to move the
markets,'' said Wayne Lyski, a portfolio manager of Alliance Capital
Management in New York.
   Trade deficits and the markets' reaction to them are notoriously
difficult to predict. Currency dealers said sentiment toward the
dollar is predominantly bearish, and any rally caused by a good
trade number might be quickly swamped by a wave of selling.
   The trade deficit in August was $12.2 billion.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar was slightly helped
Tuesday by the government's report of a rise of 0.9 percent in
retail sales in October, the biggest increase in seven months.
Strong economic growth attracts investors to dollar-denominated
securities.
   The market shrugged off a 0.4 percent advance in industrial
production in October, which fell within expectations, traders said.
   In contrast to other recent sessions, there were no reports of
intervention by central banks to support the dollar against other
currencies. The dollar had rallied on Monday on the strength of
central-bank purchases and reassuring statements from officials of
the United States, Japan and West Germany.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose to 123.25 Japanese yen from 123.00 yen
Monday. Later in London, the dollar traded higher at 123.40 yen.
Later in New York, the dollar fell to 123.23 yen from 123.75 yen
Monday.
   In London, one British pound fell to $1.8060 from $1.8090 late
Monday. Later in New York, the pound rose to $1.8083 from $1.8074.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late rates
Monday, included: 1.7433 West German marks, down from 1.7465; 1.4626
Swiss francs, down from 1.4665; 1.2337 Canadian dollars, up from
1.2313; 5.9535 French francs, down from 5.9635; and 1,297.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,300.25.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates
Monday, included: 1.7465 West German marks, up from 1.7452; 1.4630
Swiss francs, down from 1.4645; 5.9660 French francs, up from
5.9615; 1.9685 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9735; 1,300.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,303.50, and 1.2344 Canadian dollars, up from
1.2297.
   Gold prices moved higher, but traders said there wasn't enough
interest in the metal to sustain a big rise.
   In Hong Kong, gold closed at $424.07 a troy ounce, up from
$422.51 an ounce late Monday. Gold closed in London at $423.75 a
troy ounce, up from $420.95 late Monday. The late Zurich price was
$423.00 an ounce, up from $420.00.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose to $424.40 a troy ounce from $423.90 at Monday's close.
   Silver bullion rose in London to $6.41 a troy ounce, up from
$6.39 late Monday. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current
delivery fell to $6.368 a troy ounce from $6.418 an ounce Monday.
</TEXT>
