<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet     11-15 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street,0598</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks advanced marginally Tuesday and volume
fell to the lowest level in seven weeks, reflecting investor
reluctance to participate ahead of the government's potentially
market-jolting monthly trade report.
   Brokers said buying was largely limited to the components of the
Dow Jones industrial average, which finished with a 12.09 gain to
2,077.17, snapping a four-session losing streak. Most broader market
barometers nudged higher.
   The Commerce Department was due to report the September
merchandise trade balance Wednesday morning and most expectations
were for a $10.5 billion shortfall. If the deficit number
substantially exceeds that amount, some fear it could trigger a
selloff in the dollar, stock and bond markets.
   ``Everybody's just waiting to see what those numbers are going to
do,'' said Edward P. Nicoski, a technical analyst at Piper Jaffray &
Hopwood Inc., a Minneapolis-based investment firm.
   Although the huge trade deficits racked up by the United States
can vary widely from month to month, they remain one of the most
powerful market movers and have become a symbol of American economic
weakness.
   Despite widespread reluctance by investors to participate in the
stock market ahead of the trade-number release, some Wall Street
strategists said the conditions have been laid for some gains over
the next several days.
   ``I think barring something totally unforeseen in terms of a
negative trade number, we're setting ourselves up for a fairly
significant rally,'' said John Conlon, executive vice president and
director of equity research at Nikko Securities Co. International in
New York.
   ``There's been a lot of liquidation over the last week or so by
traders and a good deal of skepticism in the market,'' he said.
``That's a potent combination for stocks to go up.''
   Others were more cautious, based on technical analyses that
showed a lack of demand for stocks.
   ``We're oversold enough to give us a pop, but based on breadth, I
really don't think we'll get much to the upside,'' Nicoski said.
   Advancing issues barely outnumbered declines in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 715 up, 709
down and 534 unchanged.
   Volume on the NYSE floor totaled 115.17 million shares, down from
142.90 million in the previous session. It was the lowest level of
trading since a 113.72 million-share day Sept. 28.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trading at regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market,
totaled 137.24 million shares.
   Prime Computer led the NYSE's most-active list, rising 1~ to 17}
on volume of 2.3 million shares. New York investor Bennet Lebow
undertook a $20 a share offer for the company.
   J.C. Penney rose 1 to 53 after it reported third-quarter earnings
that exceeded expectations. Among other retailers, Dayton Hudson
rose ] to 39| after it reported a 35 percent gain in third-quarter
earnings.
   Among gaining blue chips, Woolworth rose ~ to 51\, General Motors
rose } to 81[ and IBM rose ] to 117{.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market rose $3.264 billion or 0.12
percent in value.
   The NYSE composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.29 to 151.33.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose 0.71 to 308.44, and S&P's
500-stock composite index rose 0.62 to 268.34.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market fell
0.22 to 372.14.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index rose 0.19
to 289.59.
