<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-15 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0791</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Plunge Despite Continuing Strike in Peru</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices plummeted Tuesday on New York's Commodity
Exchange as edgy speculators ignored bullish supply-and-demand
factors and sold heavily on fears that the market had topped.
   On other markets, precious metals were mixed; grains and soybeans
were lower; livestock and meat futures were mostly higher; energy
futures retreated; and stock-index futures advanced.
   The miners' strike in Peru, the world's sixth-largest copper
producer, entered its fifth week with no hint of a settlement but
most futures traders sold the market anyway.
   Copper settled 2.7 cents to 6.1 cents lower with the contract for
delivery in December at $1.299 a pound and the spot November
contract at $1.369 a pound, about 17 cents below the record high of
$1.538 reached Nov. 2.
   ``The market is caught in the throes of bearish sentiment,'' said
George Anagnos, metals market analyst with Thomson McKinnon
Securities Inc. in Chicago.
   ``It's sort of like a snowball going down a hill,'' Anagnos said.
``It tends to gain momentum to the downside.''
   The sell-off was sparked by weakening technical signals, the
chart patterns followed by many speculators, he said. As more people
sold, prices kept falling to levels that triggered further selling.
   But Anagnos noted that last year's extraordinary copper rally,
which saw prices hit $1.46 a pound on New Year's Eve, included a
20-cent correction, so the price slide of the past two weeks was not
unprecedented.
   ``This doesn't indicate the market is incapable of resuming its
upside move,'' he said. ``The fundamental situation to me still
portends upward prices.''
   In addition to the Peruvian strike, bullish fundamentals include
tight supplies and strong demand for copper, which is heavily used
for construction and by almost every industry.
   Gold futures rose slightly but silver prices fell on the
Commodity Exchange.
   Gold settled 40 cents to 60 cents higher with December at $425.60
a troy ounce; silver was 5 cents to 5.2 cents lower with December at
$6.393 a troy ounce.
   Soybean futures prices settled at a 3{-month low on the Chicago
Board of Trade on a late round of speculative selling. Corn also
finished sharply lower while wheat futures were mixed.
   Prices were weak all session amid bearish chart signals and
disappointment over the relatively slow pace of grain exports. Even
the Agriculture Department's announcement late Monday of a
300,000-metric-ton corn sale to the Soviet Union did not rally the
corn market, which was expecting a Soviet corn purchase of up to 2
million metric tons.
   Jerry Zusel, manager of CBOT floor operations for Balfour
Maclaine Corp. in Chicago, said most of the selling was done by
speculators while the outnumbered buyers were largely commercial
traders.
   ``There's just not enough cash business right now to support
these price levels,'' Zusel said. ``And if you can't go up, you've
got to go down.''
   Wheat settled 7 cents lower to 1} cents higher with December at
$4.13} a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 5{ cents lower with December at
$2.66 a bushel; oats were 3} cents lower to { cent higher with
December at $2.10 a bushel; soybeans were 4 cents to 15{ cents lower
with November at $7.43{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures settled sharply higher on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, buoyed by improving cash markets and strong buying by
commercial players, analysts said.
   Pork futures enjoyed some spillover support from the adjacent
cattle pits but gains were limited by expectations of lower cash
prices on Wednesday and concerns about the rapid buildup of pork
bellies in cold storage.
   Live cattle settled .70 cent to 1.25 cents higher with December
at 73.35 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .45 cent to 1.30 cents
higher with November at 82.05 cents a pound; live hogs were .27 cent
lower to .38 cent higher with December at 41.05 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were unchanged to .40 cent higher with February
at 44.87 cents a pound.
   Oil futures prices drifted lower on the New York Mercantile
Exchange in dull, directionless trading, reversing the gains of the
previous session.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 32 cents to 37 cents
lower with December at $13.90 a barrel; heating oil was .23 cent to
.69 cent lower with December at 44.40 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .55 cent to 1.20 cents lower with December at 46.96
cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures posted modest gains on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for December delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 settled .65 point higher at 269.50.
</TEXT>
