<2ND_LINE>AM-Drexel-Judge, 1st Ld-Writethru,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Refuses 2-1, to Remove Judge in Drexel Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new grafs 3-4 with SEC comment, picks up 3rd graf pvs,
Drexel has...SUBS last three grafs to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A divided federal appeals court on Tuesday
refused to oust U.S. District Judge Milton Pollack from presiding
over the civil insider trading case against investment giant Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc.
   In a 2-to-1 decision, the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
declined to intervene and remove Pollack over an alleged conflict of
interest. The Wall Street firm did not immediately say whether it
will appeal further.
   But the decision was welcomed by officials at the Securities and
Exchange Commission, which brought the massive civil-fraud case
against Drexel more than two months ago.
   ``Naturally we're pleased,'' said Daniel Goelzer, general counsel
for the SEC in Washington. ``We didn't feel that Judge Pollack was
required to recuse (disqualify) himself and the court agreed with
us.''
   Drexel has claimed that it is playing a key role in financing the
acquisition of Palais Royal Inc., a Houston-based retailing company
in which Pollack's wife Moselle is a major stockholder.
   Although she has no direct relationship with Drexel, Mrs. Pollack
stands to gain about $35 million in the transaction.
   Drexel and other defendants, including Drexel's high-yield bond
financier Michael Milken, have contended that their connection to
the judge's wife creates an appearance of partiality by Pollack
toward them. They have requested another judge that would make the
case free of any possible taint.
   In sometimes heated court sessions, Pollack, an 82-year-old
jurist with a pro-government reputation, balked at stepping aside,
calling the Drexel move an ``illusionary diversion.''
   Other lawyers familiar with the case have called the Drexel move
a tactical strategy to get another judge because of fear by defense
attorneys that Pollack would rule harshly against the firm.
   ``We conclude that an objective observer knowing and
understanding all the facts and circumstances could not reasonably
question Judge Pollack's impartiality,'' wrote Circuit Judge Richard
J. Cardamone, with Judge Lawrence W. Pierce concurring.
   But Judge J. Edward Lumbard disagreed in a sharply worded
dissenting opinion, saying: ``It is clear to me that a reasonable
person knowing these ultimate conceded facts would reasonably
question Judge Pollack's ability to supervise such litigation
impartially.
   ``Such a reasonable person's next question would be `Why hasn't
the judge stepped aside?' Moreover, Judge Pollack's expressed
resentment to the suggestion of recusal and his castigation of
Drexel and its counsel has confirmed these doubts. He cannot act
impartially in these cases,'' Lumbard wrote.
   Drexel spokesman Steven Anreder said ``we naturally are
disappointed with today's decision in the U.S. Court of Appeals. We
have not yet had an opportunity to review it, and we will be doing
so in the next few days.''
   The SEC filed a 184-page civil fraud complaint against Drexel,
Milken and three other employees Sept. 7, accusing them of trading
on inside information, cheating clients, manipulating stock, keeping
phony books and other violations.
   The SEC also claimed Drexel used the organization of convicted
takeover speculator Ivan F. Boesky as a front for its alleged
illegal activities.
   The defendants have denied any wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
