<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AutoSales Bjt   11-15 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Early November Sales Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car and light truck sales by U.S. automakers rose
14.9 percent in early November compared with results a year ago that
were depressed by the absence of buyer incentives.
   The seven manufacturers assembling cars and light trucks in the
United States said Tuesday they sold 295,497 vehicles during the
Nov. 1-10 period this year, compared with 228,665 vehicles during
the same time last year.
   That amounted to a 14.9 percent increase in the daily sales rate.
There were nine selling days during the period this year and eight
last year.
   U.S. automakers have sold 10,190,150 vehicles in 1988, a 7.6
percent increase over the 9,437,194 sold during the Jan. 1-Nov. 10
period last year. There have been 266 selling days so far this year,
one more than at the same time last year.
   ``That's very olid,'' analyst Joseph Phillippi of Shearson Lehman
Hutton of New York City said of the sales figures. ``Our outlook
calls for continued moderate steady growth without any ripples.''
   Ron Glantz, an auto analyst with Montgomery Securities Inc. in
San Francisco, said, ``The '89 model year is starting off very, very
well.''
   Part of the reason for the increase in year-to-year sales was a
lack of incentives in early November last year. The super-low
financing and big cash-back offers of last summer ended with the
1987 model year on Sept. 30, 1987.
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. reported
they sold 172,325 cars during the Nov. 1-10 period this year
compared with 130,062 during the same period last year, a 17.8
percent daily sales increase.
   Ford recorded the largest period-to-period increase, selling
57,275 cars in early November this year, compared with 40,877 during
the same period last year, a 24.5 percent rise in the daily sales
rate. Since New Year's Day, the nation's No. 2 automaker has sold
1,923,078 cars, a 9.4 percent increase from the 1,750,770 it had
sold during the same period last year.
   GM, the industry's sales volume leader, sold 88,238 cars during
the first 10 days of this month, a 16.4 percent rise in daily sales
over the 67,364 cars it sold during the same time last year. For the
calendar year, GM has sold 0.7 percent more cars in 1988 than 1987,
rising to 3,167,132 cars this year from 3,133,795 last year.
   Chrysler, the nation's No. 3 carmaker, said it sold 26,812 cars
in the Nov. 1-10 period this year, compared with 21,821 cars sold
during the same time last year _ a 9.2 percent increase in daily
sales. Chrysler also said it has sold 930,457 cars so far in 1988, a
11.7 percent increase over the 829,958 cars it had sold between Jan.
1-Nov. 10 of last year.
</TEXT>
