<2ND_LINE>AM-Pillsbury, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0297,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Met Extends Offer for Pillsbury Again</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs bgng Separately, Burger King... to clarify
that different franchisee groups that met with Burger King and Grand
Met. Picks up 9th graf, A number...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC on Tuesday extended its
hostile $5.23 billion tender offer for Pillsbury Co. for the third
time, and said Pillsbury shareholders had tendered 79.1 percent of
the company's outstanding shares under the offer.
   The $60 a share offer, which was to expire Monday night, was
extended to Nov. 18.
   The offer, launched Oct. 4, is conditioned on the removal of
Pillsbury's ``poison pill'' defense. Judges in two states have left
the pill intact despite lawsuits from Grand Met and dissident
shareholders. The pill would make a takeover prohibitively
expensive. Further court action is pending on the issue.
   Grand Met said 67,595,940 shares of Pillsbury common stock had
been tendered and not withdrawn by the Monday night deadline.
   Pillsbury, which has rejected the bid as inadequate, had no
comment on the extension of the offer.
   Chairman Philip Smith has told Pillsbury shareholders they would
be better off keeping their stock in light of the food and
restaurant company's proposed spinoff of its Burger King business
into a separate public company.
   Pillsbury shareholders would receive a special dividend and stock
Burger King stock under the planned restructuring. The company also
is considering other moves to enhance shareholder value, Smith has
said.
   Separately, Burger King Chairman Jerry Levin met Tuesday in Miami
with key franchisees a day after Ian Martin, chief of Grand Met's
U.S. operations, met with the 15-member National Business Council,
the official representative of Burger King's 1,200 franchises.
   A number of franchisees are upset over Pillsbury's plan to spin
off Burger King, on the grounds that corporate support for their
businesses would decline from the surviving, debt-burdened company.
   Martin told franchisees that Grand Met would spend a significant
amount of money to renovate existing Burger King restaurants, build
more, and improve the company's marketing. The strategy could lead
to streamlining and management changes at Burger King headquarters
in Miami, Martin said.
   ``We think Burger King is a fantastic brand,'' Martin said in an
interview after the franchisee meeting at The Bilmore Hotel in Coral
Gables. ``You can't have more than 5,000 outlets with that brand
name and not have a tremendously powerful brand names.''
   ``I'm impressed. I'm very impressed with him,'' said Manny
Garcia, who owns 38 Burger King restaurants in central and northern
Florida. ``I think they'll do the things necessary to move the
system forward.''
   Martin said his company was ``paying very serious attention'' to
rumors that somebody, possilby inspired by Pillsbury, might mount a
takeover bid for Grand Met. He called the notion that Pillsbury
could take over Grand Met, in a so-called Pac Man defense against an
unwanted suitor, ``farfetched.''
   In such defense, a target attempts to thwart a hostile buyout by
taking over its suitor.
</TEXT>
