<1ST_LINE>r f BC-ICC-Guilford     11-15 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-ICC-Guilford,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ICC Overturns Arbitrator's Ruling In New England Rail Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Interstate Commerce Commission on Tuesday
overturned a federal arbitrator's ruling that would have reinstated
union pay rates and work rules that were slashed by Guilford
Transportation Industries last year in a sweeping cost-cutting
reorganization.
   The ICC, on a 3-1 vote, ordered that union and company
negotiators return to the arbitrator's mediation table to try to
work out new pay rates and work rules for the freight line, the
largest privately-owned railroad in New England.
   Last year, Guilford reorganized its subsidaries, Boston & Maine
and Maine Central, putting them under Springfield Terminal, a tiny
rail line with much lower wage scales. Guilford officials argued
that the move was necessary to cut costs and keep the company
competitive.
   In June, arbitrator Richard Kasher ruled that workers transferred
to Springfield Terminal must be the wages they received under their
Boston & Maine and Maine Central contracts and be subject to the
work rules under those pacts.
   But ICC Chairwoman Heather J. Gradison, ruling Tuesday on an
appeal from the company, said the arbitrator's decision on pay rates
and work rules failed to give Guilford officials ``management
flexibility.''
   She voted with the majority to send the issue back to the
arbitrator and negotiators for mediation, although she noted that
``we have never seen anything to lead us to believe that (the two
sides) can or will come up with an agreement.''
   ``Our objective is we want to see this railroad operate. We want
to see management be fair to labor. We want to see labor be fair to
management,'' she said. ``It's tempting to impose a solution here
today, but we believe you understand your business better than
anybody else.''
   Commissioner Karen Phillips, voting with Gradison and
Commissioner Frederic N. Andre, said she feared that forcing
Guilford to comply with the old union wage scales and work rules
would cripple the company and its ability to compete.
   Guilford Transportation, the Billerica, Mass. company owned by
Timothy Mellon, a reclusive heir to the Mellon banking family of
Pittsburgh, reorganized last year, saying it could not compete under
the union wage and rule restrictions.
   In a statement released following the commission meeting, the
company said it would ``wok within the process prescribed by the ICC
in the hope that it will pave the way for the railroad to meet the
competitive challenges of the New England marketplace while at the
same time meeting the requirements of the railroad's employees.''
   Commissioner Paul H. Lamboley, the lone dissenter, said it was
inappropriate to ``dissect'' portions of the arbitrator's decision.
``You can't break out bits and pieces of it,'' he said, adding that
the commission was venturing into an area beyond its expertise.
   Eugene F. Lyden, international vice president of the United
Transportation Union, said he was disappointed with the commission's
ruling on pay rates and work rules, but applauded the panel's votes
upholding other sections of the arbitrator's decision.
   The commission ruled 4-0 to affirm Kasher's decision to provide
Boston & Maine and Maine Central workers not rehired by Springfield
Terminal with severance pay and benefits in accordance with the old
contracts.
   And the commission agreed that workers hired by Springfield
Terminal must receive the difference between their new salaries and
their old, higher wages for up to six years. But the workers would
be subject to the new work rules that Guilford officials say would
make the company more efficient.
   The commission also voted unanimously to require Guilford to
honor the seniority employees built up at Boston & Maine and Maine
Central.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0283 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 2139EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-USG-Kohler     11-15 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-USG-Kohler,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kohler Division To Buy Tub And Shower Maker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SCHAUMBURG, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sterling Plumbing Group Inc., a
subsidiary of Kohler Co., will purchase USG Corp.'s Kinkead
Division, a manufacturer of tub and shower enclosures, the companies
said Tuesday.
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed.
   Kinkead employs about 425 people at manufacturing plants in Union
City, Tenn., and Hickman, Ky., and warehouses located throughout the
country, USG said.
   Sterling manufactures faucets, drain products, valves,
stainless-steel sinks and Vikrell bath fixtures.
   Chicago-based USG said it was selling Kinkead due to its recent
recapitalization and its decision to concentrate on its core
business of manufacturing and distributing gypsum wallboard and
other building products.
   Kohler, based in Kohler, Wis., is a leading manufacturer of
plumbing products. Kohler also makes engines and generators and
operates real-estate and hospitality services in east-central
Wisconsin.
   USG Chairman Robert J. Day said the company restructuring program
was proceeding as scheduled and that proceeds from the sale of
various divisions were expected to exceed the $535 million in
after-tax income originally envisioned.
