<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AirFares 1stLd-Writethru f0276 11-15 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Fares, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0276,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Continental Plan Could Boost Most MaxSaver Fares</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 18th graf pvs, Some examples...to CORRECT that fares are
one-way sted round trip. Picks up 19th graf, _Between Newark,
N.J....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just days after initiating an industry move to
drop discounts aimed at business travelers, Continental Airlines
announced a restructured ``MaxSaver'' program Tuesday that is
expected to boost most remaining cut-rate fares.
   Continental said MaxSaver fares _ which are used by most vacation
travelers _ would be based on the length of a flight under the new
formula.
   Competition on individual routes, not mileage, had determined the
fares in the past.
   It was not immediately clear whether other big carriers would
follow Continental's move, but the airline has been the pacesetter
on fares in recent years.
   The airline planned to notify travel agents about the new fares
Tuesday night and Wednesday, spokesman Ned Walker said in a
telephone interview from Continental's headquarters in Houston. He
said the new MaxSaver fares would take effect next Wednesday.
   ``You will see some MaxSavers going up and some MaxSavers going
down,'' Walker said. ``We are returning air fares to a more rational
level.''
   He said fares for longer flights generally would be raised while
those for shorter hauls would mostly be reduced.
   Some travel agents told about the changes said they appeared to
have the effect of raising roughly two-thirds of Continental's
MaxSaver fares and cutting the remaining third or so.
   ``They're going to raise it to the level that it should have been
in the first place,'' said Jack Bloch, the owner of JB's World
Travel in New York.
   MaxSaver tickets must be purchased seven to 14 days in advance
and require an overnight stay.
   Air fare structures have become geographically ``out of whack''
as a result of airlines frequently matching each other's fare
increases in recent months, said Robert Decker, an airline analyst
for Duff & Phelps Inc. in Chicago.
   The changes come amid plans by Texas Air Corp. subsidiary
Continental and other big U.S. airlines to eliminate another
category of discount air fares _ the ``junk fares'' available four
to seven days before a flight and used mainly by business travelers.
   In a move initiated by Continental and followed by several major
carriers, the junk fares were slated to be eliminated on Tuesday.
But the airlines decided to extend the deadline by a week because of
confusion over the change.
   Only about 10 percent to 20 percent of all airline passengers use
the last-minute junk fares, according to some analysts' estimates.
   The popular MaxSaver fares, by contrast, are used by most
vacation travelers.
   More than 90 percent of air travelers use some form of discount
fare, be it last-minute or advance purchase, according to the Air
Transport Association, an industry trade group based in Washington.
   The discounts generally aren't available for flights during
holidays like Thanksgiving and Christmas.
   Some examples of changes in Continental's one-way MaxSaver fares
are:
   _Between Newark, N.J., and Houston: current off-peak fare, $129;
current peak fare, $159; new off-peak, $139; new peak, unchanged.
   _Between Boston and Dallas: current off-peak, $149; current peak,
$169; new off-peak and peak, both unchanged.
   _Between Phoenix and Tampa, Fla.: current off-peak, $174, current
peak, $204; new off-peak, $159; new peak, $179.
   _Between Newark and Los Angeles: current off-peak, $159; current
peak, $184; new off-peak, $179; new peak, $199.
   _Between Denver and Seattle: current off-peak, $114; current
peak, $144; new off-peak, $129; new peak, $149.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
