<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-88 2205EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-UnitedPilots     11-15 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-United Pilots,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Strikes One Contract Provision Pilots Said Hindered Buyout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has struck down a provision of
United Airlines' contract with union machinists, ruling the language
was intended to hinder the pilots union's attempt to buy the
carrier, union and company officials said Tuesday.
   The Air Line Pilots Association sued in April to block two
provisions in United's contract with the International Association
of Machinists on the grounds .
   The pilots union claimed the provisions were restrictive
covenants aimed at blocking its more than $4 billion proposal to buy
the airline, said ALPA spokesman Hank Krakowski in Chicago.
   U.S. District Judge James Zagel on Saturday rejected one
provision, which would have prohibited the pilots' union from
participating in an employee ownership plan unless the machinists
and other unions agreed to the terms, Krakowski said.
   Russell Mack, United's vice president for corporate
communications, said late Tuesday the airline would have no comment
on the ruling.
   United spokesman Joe Hopkins confirmed Zagel's rejection of the
provision, but said Tuesday he did not know the details of the
lawsuit or of the judge's decision.
   Krakowski said that under the stricken provision, any stock
ownership option tendered to the pilots would have to be offered to
the other unions and subjected to possible arbitration.
   ``We'd be in the position of trying to buy a company and not
knowing what the price was going to be until after arbitration,''
Krakowski said.
   Local 1487 of the Machinists, which negotiated the contract with
UAL, issued a statement confirming Zagel's rejection of the
provision, but made no further comment.
   Richard Delaney, president of the local, was in Florida on
Tuesday and would not be available for comment until next week, said
a union officer who declined to be identified.
   Zagel let stand the second provision challenged in the ALPA
lawsuit. That provision would give the Machinists a choice of
reneging on their existing contract or extending it for three years
in the event of any takeover.
   In April 1987, the machinists refused to join ALPA in its buyout
attempt, citing what union officials called philosophical and
technical problems with the pilots' proposal.
   Despite that refusal, ALPA officials said last December they
considered the possibility of a sympathy strike against United if
the machinists and the airline failed to agree on a contract.
   The machinists' pact, containing the two provisions challenged by
ALPA, was reached Nov. 15, 1987, hours before expiration of a 30-day
``cooling-off'' period.
   ALPA, which has made three offers to acquire the airline, has
enlisted the aid of a syndicate of banks and the investment firm
Salomon Brothers Inc.
   The pilots' first proposal for a $4.5 billion employee takeover
of United was made in April 1987 and rejected by its parent UAL
Corp. that same month as inadequate.
   Two months later, in June 1987, ALPA came back with a
recapitalization plan, under which ownership of United would have
been transferred to employees and stockholders. The company also
rejected that proposal.
</TEXT>
