<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0311 11-15 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0311,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher; Stocks Up In Early Tokyo Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei closing, later
dollar trading, comments. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar moved higher against the Japanese
yen in Wednesday morning trading, while share prices rose to another
record high on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar opened at 123.58 yen, up from Tuesday's close of
123.25 yen, and by late morning was changing hands at 123.50 yen.
   Exchange dealers said activity was slow as investors waited for
the release of the U.S. Commerce Department's report on the nation's
September trade deficit, scheduled for later Wednesday in Washington.
   ``But in general, the market sentiment toward the dollar is
bearish,'' said an exchange dealer at a U.S. commercial bank in
Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the market's
main price index, rose 99.21 points from Tuesday's record close to
finish the morning session at 28,928.62, a record for the early
session.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, dealers said the Nikkei index
briefly topped the 29,000-point mark for the first time, but moved
back slightly due to profit-taking.
   ``Share prices appear to be as bullish as they can be,'' said a
dealer at Nikko Securities Co. in Tokyo. ``Financial shares were
down today but other shares, such as construction, are leading the
market.''
   The dealer said it was a good sign that different types of issues
were variously leading the market.
   ``As long as this sort of cycle continues, the Nikkei will
continue to grow for some time,'' he said.
</TEXT>
